<FIRST>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0782 01-11 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0782,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS Geiringer; Separates moved for AMs as a0777 on Morrison
and a0659 on Harsoyo.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Herbert Morrison</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MORGANTOWN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Herbert Morrison, 83, whose emotional
description of the crash of the Hindenburg touched millions 52 years
ago, died Tuesday.
   Morrison was a reporter for Chicago radio station WLS on May 6,
1937, when he described the explosion of the airship as it
approached its landing in Lakehurst, N.J. Thirty-six of the 97
people aboard died.
   Morrison became the eyes and ears of the world as the only
broadcaster at the scene. Millions heard his tear-filled account of
the explosion, the fire and people falling from the sky.
   Morrison served in the Army Air Corps during World War II and
later became the first news director at television station WTAE in
Pittsburgh. He retired after developing a radio and television
section for the university relations department at West Virginia
University.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Raden Haji Harsoyo</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raden Haji Harsoyo, a retired general
major and former commander of the Indonesian contingent of U.N.
peacekeeping forces in the Vietnam War, died Tuesday of heart
disease at age 63.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>William McDonald</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William J. McDonald, a nationally noted
cleric who served as auxiliary bishop of the San Francisco
Archdiocese for 12 years, died Saturday of a heart attack at age 83.
   McDonald was ordained in San Francisco in 1928, serving as a
parish priest before going into education. He took a doctorate from
the Catholic University of America in Washington, remaining as a
faculty member.
   McDonald was president of the International Federation of
Catholic Universities from 1960 to 1963 and editor of the Catholic
Encyclopedia. He served as auxiliary bishop in the Washington, D.C.,
Archdiocese from 1964 to 1967, when he was transferred to San
Francisco.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Karl Geiringer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Karl Geiringer, an internationally
known author of books on composers such as Johann Sebastian Bach and
Franz Joseph Hadyn, died Tuesday. He was 89.
   Geiringer studied with Guido Adler, one of the fathers of modern
musicology, at the University of Vienna. There, he received his
doctorate and later became curator of the archives of the Society of
the Friends of Music, which house major collections of the
manuscripts of composers Johannes Haydn and Robert Alexander
Schumann.
   Geiringer, who came to the United States in 1939, wrote more than
100 articles for Grove's Dictionary of Music and Musicians. He also
worked for the British Broadcasting Company, and organized the
collection of instruments owned by the Royal College of Music.
   Geiringer, who was named professor emeritus at University of
California Santa Barbara in 1973, also authored ``Instruments in the
History of Western Music.'' Composers and musicians throughout the
world used his books, which were translated into 11 languages.
</TEXT>
