<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 0032EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Britain-Minesweepers     01-11 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Britain-Minesweepers,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Mine-Sweepers To Head Home From Gulf In March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three British mine-sweepers which have been part of
a task force helping to clear mines from the Persian Gulf will head
home in early March, said Armed Forces Minister Archie Hamilton.
   The decision was made because of the Aug. 20 cease-fire that
halted fighting in the 8-year war between Iran and Iraq, the absence
of any recent mining, and achievements of European and U.S.
mine-sweepers in removing mines from international waters, Hamilton
said Tuesday night.
   A four-ship task force of high-technology British Hunt Class
mine-hunters arrived in the gulf in September 1987, following
Iranian mining of the area. Since then, the Royal Navy has located
and destroyed 10 mines.
   Hamilton said that should circumstances change, Britain would
return three mine-hunters to the gulf.
   Britain's Armilla Patrol of three destroyers or frigates will
remain in the gulf and the Indian Ocean area to provide assurance
and protection, if necessary, to British shipping, he said.
</TEXT>
