<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 0101EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-JusticeCuts     01-11 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Justice Cuts,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budget Move Guts Public Affairs Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a round of layoffs dubbed ``The Tuesday
Massacre'' by a Justice Department spokesman, more than 20
department employees including some career public affairs officers
were fired in an effort to save money.
   ``I don't think they gave any thought to how the work would get
done,'' laid-off spokesman Thomas Stewart said Tuesday. ``It's such
a clownish performance to take all the press officers out of the
press office and tell the director to run it with what's left.''
   The public affairs office, currently served by 10 spokesmen who
handle hundreds of phone calls from reporters each day, will be left
with four after the layoffs take effect Feb. 10. Of those four,
three will be political appointees.
   Ten people from the office of legislative affairs also are losing
their jobs, said Thomas Boyd, assistant attorney general in charge
of that office.
   The 21 people being laid off receive annual salaries and benefits
totaling $955,983, said Deborah Burstion-Wade, deputy director of
public affairs. Of that, the public affairs employees represent
$613,392 and the legislative affairs workers represent $342,501.
   Burstion-Wade, who will keep her job, denied that the layoffs
were politically motivated and added, ``Anytime you have a budget
crunch, you have to make some tough decisions.''
   Loye Miller, public affairs director, said he was surprised by
the layoffs when Thornburgh's staff informed him Tuesday morning,
even though he knew the Office of Management and Budget was planning
cutbacks.
   Miller and Boyd said their offices had been overstaffed and
underfunded, according to budget authorization levels. As a result,
money had been transferred from other areas to pay for them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
