<FIRST>r a PM-CarnegieCentennial     01-11 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Carnegie Centennial,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carnegie Gears Up for 1991 Centennial With Season-Long Festivities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A modern Soviet composer will help Carnegie Hall
celebrate its centennial as a reminder that a compatriot _ Peter
Ilich Tchaikovsky _ was at the hall when it opened.
   Carnegie Hall's centennial will be celebrated during the entire
1990-91 season and will be highlighted by a series of world
premieres, Carnegie President Isaac Stern said Tuesday.
   Carnegie Hall made its debut on May 5, 1891, with a concert by
the New York Philharmonic and two conductors, Walter Damrosch and
Tchaikovsky. Tchaikovsky conducted two of his works.
   Soviet composer Alfred Schnittke will write a work for the
Cleveland Orchestra as part of the centennial, said Carnegie General
Manager Judith Arron.
   ``Since Tchaikovsky came and opened the hall, it is fitting that
one of the most celebrated of Russian composers today could write a
new piece for us,'' she said.
   Tchaikovsky memorabilia and manuscripts on loan from the Soviet
Union will be the first exhibit in a Carnegie Hall Museum adjacent
to the hall.
   Under a $500,000 Centennial Commissioning Project, 10 or more
compositions will be premiered during the centennial season, Mrs.
Arron said.
   All the pieces will be making their debuts in Carnegie except for
Sir Michael Tippett's setting of poems by William Butler Yeats for
soprano Jessye Norman and the Chicago Symphony.
   The composition is a joint commission with the Chicago orchestra,
which is celebrating its 100th anniversary the same season, Mrs.
Arron said.
   The first performance will be in Chicago. But Sir Georg Solti's
final performance with the orchestra as its music director will be
at Carnegie, she said.
   Solti, whose term as music director ends, has directed the
Chicago Symphony since 1969.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
