<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     01-11 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC Barely Edges CBS in Final Football Playoff Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here's how NBC analyst Gerald Jaffe watches
football:
   ``I'm sitting there watching the game and when that fourth
quarter started, I'm thinking, we're looking at a 7:25 (p.m.)
finish, and there goes the week for us.''
   But the San Francisco 49ers wrapped up a 28-3 victory over the
Chicago Bears in the NFC championship. Jaffe was relieved, not
because he's a 49ers fan, but because the high-rated game ended
early enough to keep CBS from edging NBC for the victory the weekly
A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings.
   NBC won the week, its 29th in a row, by a tenth of a rating point
over CBS, 15.5 to 15.4. It was CBS' highest average rating since
March 1987. ABC had a 12.8.
   CBS also got help from Monday night football _ but on the other
two networks. ABC and NBC split the audience with competing college
bowl games.
   ``When you have two bowl games head to head, and the competition
appeals to a different audience, they're going to get a big
number,'' said Jaffe.
   Sure enough, CBS Monday shows ``Designing Women,'' ``Murphy
Brown'' and ``Almost Grown'' had their highest ratings of the season.
   CBS won the new ratings race decisively, thanks to pre-emptions
on NBC and ABC for football last Monday. The ``CBS Evening News''
had a rating of 13.5 and a 23 share. ``ABC World News Tonight'' had
a 12.3 and 21. ``NBC Nightly News'' had an 11.6 and 20.
   Each rating point equals 904,000 homes with television. The share
is a percentage of sets in use.
   CBS' new talk show starring Pat Sajak didn't go up against NBC's
late-night king Johnny Carson himself Monday night, but the premiere
of ``The Pat Sajak Show'' out-rated ``The Tonight Show'' with guest
host Jay Leno in the 17 largest television markets.
   Sajak had a rating of 7.0 and a 25 share for the hour it was
opposite ``Tonight,'' which had a 6.1 and 18 share. For the entire
90 minutes, Sajak had a 6.7 and 25. Sajak also competes against the
first half of ``Late Night with David Letterman,'' but Letterman was
a repeat Monday night. Sajak went up against a Carson rerun Tuesday,
and Carson was to return in a new show Wednesday night.
   Michael Eisenberg, CBS vice president for national research, said
Sajak increased CBS' rating in the 90-minute time period by 64
percent. CBS had previously run reruns and low-budget original
dramas in the time period.
   In prime time, ``The Cosby Show'' returned to first place last
week with a 28.6 rating and 43 share. The rest of the top 10 were:
``NFL Championship Post-Game,'' CBS; ``60 Minutes,'' CBS;
``Cheers,'' NBC; ``Murder, She Wrote,'' CBS; ``A Different World,''
NBC; ``Roseanne,'' ABC; ``Golden Girls,'' NBC; ``Empty Nest,'' NBC;
and ``Who's the Boss?'' ABC.
   The lowest-rated prime-time shows of the week were: ``Scarface,''
``Oh, God, You Devil,'' ``Mission Impossible,'' ``Sugar Bowl,''
``West 57th,'' ``Tattinger's,'' ``TV 101,'' ``HeartBeat,'' ``Dirty
Dancing'' and ``Knightwatch.''
</TEXT>
