<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 0226EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     01-11 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With George Bush heading to the White House, some
residents of his adopted state are doing strange things to get
tickets to the Black Tie and Boots Ball, a Washington inaugural bash
organized by Texans.
   One Houston socialite called Rep. Charles Stenholm demanding
tickets to the ball because she had bought a $6,000 gown for the
evening and intended to come. When she was told that no tickets to
the Jan. 21 event were available, the woman burst into tears and
proclaimed flatly that she would come anyway.
   Stenholm, president of the Texas State Society, a group of Texans
who live in Washington, says such behavior is not uncommon as his
office prepares to throw a party that's become a hot inaugural event
even though it isn't on the official schedule of events surrounding
Bush's inauguration.
   One Texan who didn't get tickets called Stenholm's office in a
snit because he had heard that non-Texans were going to the ball. He
demanded that guests be required to show Texas birth certificates at
the door to be admitted, said Chino Chapa, Stenholm's press
secretary.
   That request was turned down, Chapa said, because ``our guest of
honor wouldn't have qualified.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Mississippi Senate need no
longer worry about having staff members deliver nasty letters to
them at the Capitol.
   Charles H. Griffin, secretary of the Senate, sent a one-page
memorandum to Senate staffers this week banning hand deliveries of
those types of correspondences.
   ``The Senate staff will deliver to senators legitimate
communications involving legislative and governmental affairs,''
Griffin's memo says.
   The memo instructs staff members not to deliver unsigned or
derogatory, defamatory or obscene materials.
   The policy was formulated after a senator complained during the
Legislature's August special session on county government reform,
the Senate secretary said.
   ``People have the right to petition, but not to the point of
writing an obscene letter,'' said Griffin.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON HEIGHTS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Owners of radio station WSEX say
they got as ``much mileage'' out of their name as possible.
   They turned to the NFL's Chicago Bears in changing the call
letters to WCBR on Monday.
   The station, northwest of Chicago, won a battle with the Federal
Communications Commission in 1983 to change from WTCO to WSEX.
   ``The WSEX name instantly put us on the map,'' station manager
Michael Krafcisin said. ``But we got as much mileage as we could
from the name, and we wanted to capture something that was warm and
fuzzy.''
</TEXT>
