<FIRST>r i PM-Australia-Shooting     01-11 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Australia-Shooting,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Chief Shot To Death In Driveway At Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the country's most senior law
enforcement officials was shot to death in the driveway of his home
in an apparent execution-style slaying.
   Assistant Federal Police Commissioner Colin Winchester was shot
twice in the head at point-blank range late Tuesday.
   Immediately afterward, police blocked roads leading in and out of
the capital and searched all vehicles.
   Federal Police Commissioner Peter McAulay said drug gangs were
among possible suspects in the killing and newspapers speculated it
was related to drug investigations.
   Winchester, 55, was shot with a .22-caliber pistol while still in
his car after driving home from work, said a police spokesman, who
could not be named as is customary here.
   Justice Minister Michael Tate said the killing lowered the nation
to a new level of crime.
   ``For someone to assassinate an officer in a private home is a
new thing for Australia,'' he said during an emotionally charged
news conference.
   Winchester ranked among Australia's top 10 senior police
officials. Chief Superintendent Lloyd Worthy said the style of
killing pointed to a professional gang, but he declined to elaborate.
</TEXT>
