<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>New President to Attend Tokyo Funeral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush will lead the U.S. delegation to
the funeral of the late Japanese Emperor Hirohito on Feb. 24, five
weeks after Bush is inaugurated as president, the president-elect's
spokesman said.
   Bush will be accompanied by his wife, Barbara, spokesman Steve
Hart said Tuesday. He had no other details on the itinerary,
composition of the delegation or other travel planned by the
incoming president.
   Hirohito died Saturday of intestinal cancer at the age of 87. He
was succeeded as emperor by his son, Akihito.
   The Japan trip is the first foreign travel announced for Bush,
who will be inaugurated Jan. 20.
   The announcement confirmed that the incoming administration will
continue to stress the importance of U.S. ties with Japan, described
at the State Department earlier Tuesday as the most important U.S.
bilateral relationship in the world.
   The late Japanese monarch is now known as the Emperor Showa,
using the historical name of his reign, which covered 62 years
marking Japanese military expansion, the nation's defeat in World
War II, reconciliation, reconstruction, dramatic economic growth and
new prosperity.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Drive to Amend State Insurance Laws Opened</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The organization Citizens Action has announced
plans to campaign for changes in insurance laws in 14 states,
patterned after the successful ballot initiative in California.
   Robert M. Brandon, vice president of the federation of statewide
citizens organizations called Citizens Action, said Tuesday a
``consumer revolt against skyrocketing insurance rates'' has been
spreading as a result of the passage of Proposition 103 in
California, which ordered rollbacks in auto insurance rates.
   Brandon said the campaigns varied, but that in general they seek
tougher regulation, lower rates, full disclosure of financial
information and elimination of anti-trust exemptions for insurance
companies.
   He said campaigns were planned or underway in Connecticut,
Florida, Illinois, Indiana, Maine, Maryland, New Hampshire, New
Jersey, New York, Ohio, Oregon, Pennsylvania, West Virginia and
Wisconsin.
   Citizens Action is a federation of statewide citizens and
consumer organizations representing 1.75 million members.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>California Businessman Heads Postal Board</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   San Francisco businessman Robert Setrakian has
been elected chairman of the board of governors of the U.S. Postal
Service.
   A member since 1985, Setrakian succeeds John Griesemer as head of
the board, which oversees the operations of the Postal Service.
   Griesemer, the chairman for two years, had not sought re-election
as head of the board. He remains a member of the body.
   Setrakian, a former member of the Federal Maritime Commission,
previously headed Midstate Horticultural Co. in San Francisco, the
California Growers Winery and the Coastwise Steamship Line.
   Postmaster General Anthony Frank told the board that the agency
had handled nearly 2.9 billion cards and letters during the
Christmas season, about 2 percent more than a year earlier.
   That included a record 183,268,000 pieces of first class mail
canceled on Dec. 19. That beat the 168 million handled on the
similar day, the last Monday before Christmas, in 1987.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Book On Terrorist Groups Published By Pentagon</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new Pentagon-published book on terrorism
doesn't break new ground on the issue, but officials say it should
make Americans more aware of the threat terrorism represents to
national security interests.
   The book, ``Terrorist Group Profiles,'' describes the Abu Nidal
group in the Middle East as ``the most dangerous terrorist
organization in existence.''
   Charles S. Whitehouse, assistant defense secretary for special
operations and low-intensity conflict, said the 131-page book
published Tuesday should be helpful as a comprehensive reference
document.
   ``This is not an intelligence document, but rather a compilation
of open-source material that has been verified by classified
sources,'' Whitehouse added.
   ``Copies will be distributed starting today to public government
agencies, to public libraries as well as to government libraries. It
will also be distributed to law enforcement activities, diplomatic
posts and domestic and overseas Department of Defense components and
activities,'' he said.
   Whitehouse said the publication had nothing to do with recent
Reagan administration claims that Libya is building a plant that
could supply chemical weapons to terrorists.
   The official said that while Libya appears to be increasing its
support of terrorism around the world, Iran must still be considered
the world's top supporter of terrorism.
</TEXT>
