<DOCNO> AP890111-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 0447EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MississippiBurning     01-11 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mississippi Burning,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Theater Manager Changes Mind, Will Show ``Mississippi Burning''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of the only movie theater
here has decided to show ``Mississippi Burning,'' saying the film
about three civil rights workers' slayings would bring negative
publicity no matter what he did.
   ``Well, we didn't want to get any bad publicity for the town and
that's the only reason I didn't want to run it here,'' Shelly
Steiger said in announcing his change of mind. ``But it looks like
we're going to get it anyway.''
   Residents may have to wait some time to see the picture here,
though. Steiger said he contacted Orion Pictures in Atlanta on
Tuesday but wasn't told when the film would be available.
   ``They only have so many prints and I have to wait until the big
cities get through with them,'' the 64-year-old Steiger said. ``I'm
playing pictures now that played in Meridian back in November and
December.'' Meridian is a city of 45,000 residents about 40 miles
southeast of here.
   The movie has been released in five test markets and opens
nationally Friday.
   Steiger's mother, Lulu Ellis, who owns the 500-seat Ellis
Theater, said earlier this week that she and her son had decided not
to show the movie. She said church groups were threatening to
boycott the theater if it showed the movie.
   During most movies at the theater, blacks customarily sit in the
balcony while whites, a few blacks and Choctaw Indians sit down in
the orchestra seats. Steiger said this was by custom and was not
required by the theater management. The film is an account of the
deaths of James Earl Chaney, 21, who was black, and whites Andrew
Goodman, 20, and Michael Schwerner, 24. The three disappeared June
21, 1964, after they were released from jail in Philadelphia. They
had been stopped on speeding charges after investigating the burning
of a church by the Ku Klux Klan.
   The three were found 44 days later, shot to death and buried in a
soggy earthen dam near here.
   The movie stars Gene Hackman as an FBI agent investigating the
case and was directed by Alan Parker.
   Steiger said he wasn't sure how the picture will be received at
the theater.
   ``I don't know. Of course we're just a small town so we don't
have that kind of draw,'' Steiger said. ``I'm not just showing it
for the money. If people want to see it that's their prerogative.
And if they want to see it bad enough they can go to Meridian
because I know it will open there before here.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890111-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 0412EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon-Shiites     01-11 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Shiites,0741</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shiite Feud Splits Families, Threatens Syria-Iran Alliance</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fierce battle between rival Shiite
Moslem factions for dominance of Lebanon's largest sect has split
families and jeopardizes the strategic alliance between their
masters, Iran and Syria.
   Amid the carnage of Lebanon's 13-year civil war between
Christians and Moslems and the country's myriad other mini-wars
between feuding militias, the Shiite conflict has fractured
Lebanon's largest sect.
   Shiite sources said the battle has pitted brother against
brother, father against son as they side either with the
fundamentalist Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, or the
secular, pro-Syrian Amal militia led by Lebanon's Justice Minister,
Nabih Berri.
   More than 500 people, many of them civilians, have been killed
and about 1,500 wounded since the inter-Shiite rivalry broke into
open warfare in April.
   In Beirut's southern slums, a Shiite bastion devastated by the
fighting, huge posters of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini and Imam Mousa
Sadr, Amal's charismatic founder who mysteriously disappeared in
Libya in 1978, hang side by side, indicating a false unity among the
1 million Shiites.
   The two sides have vied for years for control of the country's
Shiite community, now one of Lebanon's most powerful sects.
   Hezbollah, at the cutting edge of Khomeini's Islamic revolution
abroad, seeks to create an Iranian-style Islamic republic in Lebanon.
   It has built an impressive Tehran-funded social, educational and
welfare network that has in the past few years been pumping an
estimated $5 million a month into Hezbollah's coffers. This has
wooed many Shiites from Amal.
   The more nationalist Amal, armed by Syria, wants to reunite
divided Lebanon under a multi-sect government in which the Moslem
majority will share power equally with the traditionally dominant
Christians.
   ``Any Moslem who willingly abides by the rules of a non-Moslem
state is a traitor,'' says a Hezbollah slogan daubed on walls in the
squalid slums of south Beirut.
   ``Traitors are those who kidnap foreigners and carry out acts of
terrorism all over the world to serve Iran's interests at the
expense of Lebanon's Shiites,'' said Amal's security chief in the
southern port of Tyre, who identified himself only as Hamza.
   Hezbollah is considered the parent organization for Shiite
fundamentalist factions who hold most of the 15 Western hostages
kidnapped in Lebanon.
   Lebanese and Western intelligence agencies also blame Hezbollah
zealots for the 1983 suicide bombings of U.S. and French targets in
Lebanon, in which hundreds of people were killed, as well as other
terrorist attacks in the Middle East and Western Europe.
   ``All Lebanon's Shiites are branded terrorists because of such
acts,'' Hamza said. ``Many Lebanese Shiites have been deported from
foreig countries because of this.''
   Amal drove Hezbollah out of the Tyre region and most of south
Lebanon in April in a crackdown that followed the Feb. 17 kidnapping
of U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William Higgins.
   The following month, the fundamentalists, trained by Iranian
Revolutionary Guards based in the Bekaa Valley of eastern Lebanon,
seized large chunks of Amal territory in Beirut's southern slums.
   They have repeatedly clashed since, despite efforts by Syria and
Iran to cool tempers.
   Several Amal leaders have been assassinated. Among them was
Amal's south Lebanon commander, Daoud Daoud, and two senior
lieutenants. Their car was riddled by unidentified gunmen as they
drove through south Beirut in October. Amal blamed Hezbollah.
   The fundamentalists accuse Amal of preventing them from carrying
out the ``holy duty of Jihad (holy war) to liberate Palestine from
Zionist occupation.''
   To ``liberate the holy city of Jerusalem and the rest of
Palestine is the duty of every Moslem,'' Hezbollah's weekly magazine
Al-Aahd said in a recent editorial.
   Amal believes that the ``liberation of Palestine is a collective
duty of all Arabs and Moslems,'' said Abu Hassan Qobeissi, Amal's
security commander in south Lebanon.
   Speaking from his headquarters in the hilltop village of Zifta,
25 miles northeast of Tyre, he said, ``Hezbollah will not be allowed
back into the south to fire a missile into northern Israel ... and
provoke the Israelis into demolishing our villages and towns with
their planes.''
   Amal's main military objective is limited to driving the Israelis
out of their self-proclaimed ``security zone,'' a strip of Lebanese
border territory running from the Mediterranean coast to Mount
Hermon they have occupied since 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
