<DOCNO> AP890111-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 0536EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PuertoRico     01-11 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Puerto Rico,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Appeals Court Hears Arguments on Wiretapping in Puerto Rico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A case stemming from wiretap evidence obtained in a
$7 million Wells Fargo robbery investigation could have a
far-reaching impact on Puerto Rico's status as a U.S. commonwealth.
   The 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals heard arguments Tuesday on
the legality of federal wiretapping on the island in the civil case,
Camacho vs. the Puerto Rico Telephone Co.
   A ruling is not expected for at least a month.
   At issue is a provision in the 35-year-old Puerto Rico
Constitution that forbids any telephone wiretapping as part of
citizens' rights to privacy.
   The plaintiffs believe that because Puerto Rico does not enjoy
the status of the 50 states, its citizens should not be subject to
federal laws that violate their constitution. Puerto Ricans don't
have the right to vote in U.S. elections, don't have a voting member
of Congress and don't pay federal income tax.
   ``We have no access to the way the laws are enacted,'' said
Charles Hey-Maestre, one of the attorneys who brought the lawsuit on
behalf of the defendants in the Wells Fargo trial in Hartford, Conn.
   Hey-Maestre represents the Instituto Puertorriqueno de Derechos
Civiles, a Puerto Rican-based civil rights organization, and the
Center for Constitutional Rights, a New York-based public law
organization in Puerto Rico that first filed the suit in Puerto Rico
where. A federal judge there dismissed the lawsuit.
   Attorneys representing the telephone company said company
officials had no choice but to obey the FBI's request to place
wiretaps. They claimed Tuesday that the lawsuit asks the court to
interfere in congressional matters.
   ``It is not in the function of this court to act as a political
branch of the government,'' said Lino Saldana, an attorney for the
Puerto Rico Telephone Co. ``Congress has legislated on a matter of
national concern and made that legislation applicable to Puerto
Rico. It has given Puerto Rico a treatment it has accorded all the
states in the union.''
   ``That's the rub,'' said Judge Hugh Bownes, interrupting Saldana.
   Saldana also contended that the company cannot be sued because a
1964 federal law provides immunity for communications carriers from
liability for their assistance of federal officers in pursuit of
criminals.
   The appeals court case dates to 1984, when the telephone company
obeyed a federal court order obtained by the FBI to place wiretaps
on the phones of several alleged members of the Macheteros, an armed
underground group fighting for Puerto Rico's independence.
   Five of those subsequently arrested with the aid of the wiretaps
are on trial in Hartford on charges of conspiring to rob the
Hartford Wells Fargo armored car company of $7 million in 1983.
   The five have claimed they are ``prisoners of war'' and are being
targeted because of their advocacy of Puerto Rican independence.
   The wiretap tapes are in evidence against the defendants in
Hartford. Attorneys said that the tapes could be inadmissible if the
court rules that federal wiretapping in Puerto Rico is
unconstitutional.
</TEXT>
