<FIRST>r a PM-OperationRescue     01-11 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Operation Rescue,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Issues Injunction Against Abortion Protesters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has barred Operation Rescue, which gained
attention with its protests during the Democratic National
Convention, from obstructing anyone entering area abortion clinics.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Ward issued the permanent injunction
against the Binghamton-based group Tuesday at the request of lawyers
for women's organizations and clinics that had sued in April.
   A lawyer for the plaintiffs said his clients asked for a
permanent injunction when they learned that Operation Rescue had
planned another series of protests here for Thursday, Friday and
Saturday.
   Ward ordered that if the injunction is violated, a $25,000 fine
will be imposed against Operation Rescue on the first day and
doubled for each additional day it is violated.
   The injunction does not preclude members of Operation Rescue from
protesting on sidewalks outside abortion facilities.
   But the order bars them from trespassing on the grounds of
clinics in New York and Nassau, Suffolk and Westchester counties or
obstructing people from entering the buildings. It also prohibits
members from physically abusing or harassing anyone who seeks
services or works at clinics where abortions are performed.
   Michael Tierney, a lawyer for Operation Rescue, declined to
comment about the order because he had not seen it.
   David Cole, a lawyer at the Center for Constitutional Rights,
which represented the plaintiffs, said the judge had previously
issued two temporary restraining orders against members of Operation
Rescue.
   The first was in response to a week-long demonstration by the
group in May and the second was for demonstrations planned in
October, said Cole.
   Ward fined Operation Rescue $50,000 for demonstrations actually
carried out at two clinics in May. The fine has not yet been paid,
he said.
   The plaintiffs in this case include the National Organization for
Women and clinics in the area, Cole said.
   More than 450 anti-abortion demonstrators were arrested in
Atlanta during last summer's Democratic convention. Since then, it
has held demonstrations in cities including New York, Indianapolis,
Milwaukee, Detroit, Philadelphia and Boston.
</TEXT>
