<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mostly lower in busy European
trading late this morning. Gold prices fell.
   Traders in Rome said the market appears to have engaged itself in
an arm-wrestling match with the U.S. and West German central banks.
   Both banks have intervened in the market this week to stem the
dollar's climb, and the Bundesbank reportedly intervened again early
today.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.25 yen to a closing 126.95. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 126.45 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.8270 West German marks, down from 1.8355
   _1.5573 Swiss francs, down from 1.5645
   _6.2265 French francs, down from 6.2555
   _2.0705 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0589
   _1,341.75 Italian lire, up from 1,338.50
   _1.2010 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2012
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7760, compared with
$1.7643 Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $402.30 a troy ounce,
down from $404.75 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $403.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $403.30, down from $405.10 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.70 to close at a bid $404.48.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.92 a troy ounce,
down from Tuesday's $5.98.
