<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 0639EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PoliceCorruption     01-11 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police Corruption,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Narc Testifies That Officers Stole Drugs, Cash From Dealers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police officers in a now-disbanded narcotics
unit stole tens of thousands of dollars in drugs and cash from
dealers and divided the proceeds among themselves, a former member
of the elite squad testified.
   Leo Ryan also said he falsified a police report on a 1982 search
of a suspected drug dealer's home in exchange for a $1,000 bribe
from a prominent attorney.
   ``We really didn't care if they got convicted or not,'' Ryan said
of the dealers.
   The ex-cop turned informant testified in U.S. District Court
Tuesday at the racketeering and conspiracy trial of former Lt. John
Wilson and five other members of the defunct ``5 Squad,'' which was
created in 1980 to combat drug trafficking.
   Ryan, the government's first witness in the trial that began last
week, described more than two dozen searches during which officers
stole drugs or money. The drugs were resold to other dealers and the
proceeds split, he said.
   The indictment alleges the officers stole drugs and more than
$400,000 in cash from dealers.
   Ryan, who was convicted last year of tax evasion, said he first
stole drugs in 1982 when he and several defendants found two trash
bags containing marijuana during a search of a home.
   Former officer David Grove, one of the defendants, suggested
taking some of the marijuana, Ryan said. He said he objected, but
Grove and another squad member, Charles Hund, assured him that
``they knew a guy (they could sell the drugs to), they could trust
him, and I didn't have to worry about it.'' Ryan said he later
received $1,000.
   Hund is expected to testify for the prosecution.
   Ryan testified that one of the biggest hauls occurred on June 13,
1983, when officers found nearly $250,000 in cash while searching
the home of Walter Roeder, a suspected dealer.
   Ryan said Wilson had him tell Roeder the officers would turn the
cash over to the IRS if Roeder didn't give them some of it. Roeder,
who is expected to testify for the prosecution, eventually agreed to
give the officers half of the money, Ryan said.
   ``We were all pretty happy'' and celebrated at dinner before
returning to headquarters, where Wilson divided the cash in his
office, Ryan said.
   Ryan also said he received $1,000 from Charles Peruto Jr., a
prominent criminal attorney, for falsifying a report on the 1982
search of the home of a suspected drug dealer he represented during
which drugs were found.
   Peruto later said Ryan's testimony was ``absolutely false.''
   Peruto's name is not mentioned in the indictment and prosecutors
declined to comment on Ryan's allegation.
   Wilson and the other defendants are charged with a racketeering,
conspiracy and other crimes, including bribery of public officials,
extortion, robbery, selling drugs seized from dealers, filing false
police reports and filing false income tax returns. If convicted on
all charges, they face prison terms ranging from 20 years to 80
years.
   In addition to Wilson and Grove, the other defendants are former
officers Ronald Giongo, Richard Jumper, Frances Hilt and James
Cattalo.
</TEXT>
