<DOCNO> AP890111-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 0645EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DoctorSlain     01-11 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Doctor Slain,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Accused Killer Tried to Have Himself Committed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeless man accused of killing, raping and
robbing a pregnant doctor at Bellevue Hospital had tried to have
himself committed to the hospital's psychiatric ward last summer but
was turned away, officials say.
   The hospital's staff advised Steven Smith to go to a clinic
because his case wasn't serious enough, said Bellevue spokesman
James Walsh.
   Smith pleaded innocent Tuesday to rape, robbery and two counts of
murder in the slaying of Dr. Kathryn Hinnant, 33, whose body was
found in her office Sunday morning.
   Smith had been secretly living in an equipment room on the 22nd
floor of the hospital since last month, police said. He had
apparently moved freely throughout the 25-story building, often
wearing stolen hospital staff clothing, investigators said.
   At Smith's arraignment, Executive Assistant District Attorney
James Kindler said Smith told police after his arrest that he had
strangled Hinnant while forcibly stealing her coat, jewelry and
other property.
   Marvyn Kornberg, Smith's lawyer, said the confession was improper
because police failed to call Smith's lawyer first.
   Kornberg said his client has a ``psychiatric background.''
   Smith was admitted briefly to Bellevue Hospital in December,
after he allegedly tried to commit suicide by taking rat poison,
Walsh said.
   ``He has a psychiatric history and a history as a felon,'' Walsh
said.
   Smith's brother, who said his name was Nick, told The New York
Times that Smith had been hospitalized for psychiatric treatment in
the past.
   ``He's abnormal,'' his brother said. ``He doesn't act ordinary.''
   From April 1 to April 28, Smith was confined to a psychiatric
hospital in Columbia, S.C., for a suicide attempt, police said.
   Hinnant's family lives in Columbia, S.C., but Smith's presence
there appeared coincidental, police said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
