<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     01-11 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hezbollah Repulses Amal Attacks In South Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lebanon-Shiites</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AHMED MANTASH</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem guerrillas who
were pinned down in a mountain stronghold in south Lebanon repulsed
four attacks by Syrian-backed rivals, police reported today.
   As the fighting entered its fourth straight day today,
authorities said at least 12 fighters of the pro-Syrian Amal militia
were killed in fighting Tuesday night and eight people wounded in
earlier battled died in hospitals.
   The latest casualties raised the toll since the fighting began
Sunday to at least 107 killed and 220 wounded, police said. Amal has
admitted it has lost 38 fighters and Hezbollah 35. The other 34
fatalities were civilians.
   At least 136 people have been slain and 300 wounded since Amal
and the Tehran-supported Hezbollah, or Party of God, renewed Dec. 31
their nine-month battle for control of Lebanon's 1 million Shiites,
the country's largest sect.
   Police said about 1,000 Amal fighters used artillery, rocket
launchers and tanks on Tuesday night to shell 500 Hezbollah
guerrillas they had cornered in an enclave near Israel's
self-proclaimed security zone.
   Amal forces, backed by Syrian-supplied T-54 battle tanks, tried
four times to storm Hezbollah positions around the strategic village
of Jbaa but were driven back, police said.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named under standing
regulations, said: ``The Amal fighters are facing tough resistance
from the Hezbollahis who are manning firing positions in the
mountains.''
   Police said Amal fighters were regrouping today for a new
offensive against Jbaa, 10 miles southeast of Sidon and the key to
Hezbollah's defense lines.
   Amal blocked Hezbollah's supply lines to the fundamentalists'
9-square-mile bastion, which extends from Jbaa to the nearby hamlets
of Ein Bouswar and Louwaizeh, a Hezbollah base, and the wooded
slopes of Mount Safi.
   During one of their attacks Tuesday, Amal fighters broke into
Jbaa in savage fighting, but Hezbollah counter-attacked to push them
back.
   Amal on Monday recaptured four neighboring villages in the
southern Iklim el-Tiffah, or Apple Province, which had fallen to
Hezbollah the day before.
   Amal's leader in south Lebanon, Atef Aoun, said on Tuesday his
militia was determined to ``finish off Hezbollah in the south.
   ``We were stabbed in the back by Hezbollah. The price that
Hezbollah has to pay will be its existance in the south.''
   The fighting raged despite efforts by Iran's first deputy foreign
minister, Ali Mohammad Besharati, and Syrian President Hafez Assad
to end the bloodshed.
   Syria, with 40,000 troops in Lebanon, is the main power broker in
the war-battered Mediterranean country. It was Iran's main Arab ally
in the war against Iraq, but Hezbollah's challenge to its power in
Lebanon has put that strategic alliance under increasing strain.
   Besharati and Assad met in the Syrian capital of Damascus
Tuesday. Beirut's pro-Syrian Ash-Sharq daily said they agreed to
continue efforts to find a settlement.
   Hezbollah seeks to create an Iranian-style Islamic republic in
Lebanon. The more secular, nationalist Amal favors a multisect
government in Lebanon, with Moslems sharing power equally with the
long dominant Christians.
   Amal drove Hezbollah out of most of south Lebanon in April. A
month later, Hezbollah ousted Amal from most of south Beirut in
three weeks of fighting. About 380 people were killed and 1,150
wounded in those battles.
   Syria deployed troops in south Beirut to quell the fighting, but
fighting flared again in November with 42 people killed and 87
wounded.
</TEXT>
