<FIRST>r a PM-NickellAppeal     01-11 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nickell Appeal,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Appeals in Cyanide-Poisoning Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman convicted of killing her husband and a
woman with cyanide-laced pain relievers has asked for a new trial
because a juror's involvement in an unrelated product-tampering case
was not disclosed.
   An attorney for Stella Nickell raised the issue on Monday before
the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   The juror, Laurel Holliday, said that she sued a company after
biting into a cracker that contained an aspirin substitute and that
she settled the case for $500 in 1988, two months before she became
a juror in the cyanide case.
   Ms. Holliday's lawsuit was not disclosed to the court before she
was seated as a juror.
   Mrs. Nickell was convicted May 9 of causing the product-tampering
deaths in 1986 of her husband, Bruce Nickell, 52, and Sue Katherine
Snow, 40. They died after taking Extra-Strength Excedrin capsules
laced with cyanide.
   Ms. Snow apparently was the victim of poisoned capsules placed at
a store to make Nickell's death look random, prosecutors said.
   The deaths touched off a nationwide tampering scare and prompted
a manufacturer's recall.
   Mrs. Nickell was sentenced to 90 years in prison.
   Public defender Thomas Hillier asked for a new trial for Mrs.
Nickell last spring, but U.S. District Judge William Dwyer denied
the request.
   The judge said the juror, during jury selection, interpreted
questions narrowly and literally but did not answer untruthfully.
</TEXT>
