<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-Libya     01-11 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Libya,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Say Investigation Launched Into Frankfurt-based Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German investigators have launched
a criminal probe into a Frankfurt-based company amid allegations it
helped Libya build a chemical weapons plant, officials said today.
   ``We are currently collecting and reviewing evidence regarding
the operations of I.B.I. (Engineering company),'' said an official
with the criminal investigation division of the West German Customs
Service in Cologne.
   But he also told The Associated Press, ``There is nothing yet to
indicate criminal wrongdoing. The evidence is still being examined
and we are far away from taking anything to the prosecutor.'' He
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   American authorities say they have evidence that companies in
West Germany and other countries helped build a plant in Rabta,
Libya, that is capable of making chemical weapons. Libya says the
plant was built to make medicines.
   But West German officials say they have no proof West Germany
companies were involved and have cleared two other companies _
Imhausen-Chemie of Lahr and the Hamburg-based Pen Tsao medical
material company _ of any wrongdoing.
   West German and British news media have reported that I.B.I.'s
owner, Ihsan Barbouti, was responsible for civil engineering at the
Libyan plant.
   British news reports say that Barbouti currently lives in London
and that he owns a string of companies in foreign countries.
   U.S. accusations that West German firms helped build the Libyan
plant sped up Bonn's plans to improve export controls, a government
official said today.
   At a November meeting in Washington, President Reagan told
Chancellor Helmut Kohl that American officials believe firms from
West Germany and other countries helped build the Libyan plant.
   The federal government in Bonn on Tuesday announced a new package
of measures aimed at cracking down on violators of West Germany's
export laws.
   An Economics Ministry official today said West Germany has been
looking into improving its export controls ``for years'' but that
the November meeting in Washington served to quicken these efforts.
   ``It certainly resulted in a speeding up of this process to
improve export controls,'' said the official who demanded anonymity.
   However, the official told The Associated Press that there had
been ``long discussions before this meeting'' on improving export
control measures.
</TEXT>
