<FIRST>r a PM-Crash-WrongBody     01-11 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Crash-Wrong Body,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Victims Of Pan Am Bombing Returned To Right Families</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mixup in which the caskets of two
victims of last month's Pan Am jetliner bombing were shipped to the
wrong cities was straightened out and the remains returned to the
right families.
   The casket containing the body of 20-year-old Karen Hunt was
flown from Boston and arrived at a Rochester funeral home Tuesday,
and the body of Mary L. Johnson, 25, of Wayland, Mass., was flown
from Rochester to Boston.
   Ms. Johnson's relatives were an hour from burying the body they
thought was hers Sunday when FBI agents informed them of the mixup.
   The mistake was discovered last week when the medical examiner's
office in Rochester concluded that the body sent to the Hunt family
was not Ms. Hunt.
   Ms. Hunt's father, Robert Hunt, said the family planned a prayer
service but would not bury her until spring, when the ground thaws.
   ``We've got her body back now,'' said Hunt. ``We'll never get
over this. But at least we can start the healing process.''
   Gregory Jones, an FBI spokesman in Washington, said authorities
recovering bodies from the Dec. 21 explosion over Lockerbie,
Scotland, apparently correctly identified the bodies of the two
women but somehow flew the caskets to the wrong cities.
   ``We have no feelings at all of anger and bitterness about
this,'' Ms. Johnson's father, Robert Johnson, said earlier this
week. ``It's one of those simple mistakes that can be made. It seems
terrible at the time, but it's not a big mistake.''
   The body reported to be Ms. Hunt's arrived Thursday in Rochester.
   The family was already concerned that it was not her because
Scottish authorities' description of the clothing on the body didn't
seem to match Ms. Hunt's clothes. The medical examiner's office
confirmed their suspicions.
   Ms. Hunt was returning to New York after completing a semester in
London as part of a Syracuse University program.
   Ms. Johnson, a graduate of Brown University, was returning to
Wayland for Christmas with her family after spending 14 months
abroad, touring India and teaching English in Taiwan.
</TEXT>
