<FIRST>r a PM-Steinberg     01-11 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steinberg,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steinberg Reportedly Agrees to Examination by Prosecution Psychiatrist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for alleged child killer Joel Steinberg
charged that Hedda Nussbaum is a ``malingerer'' and a ``fraud'' who
has stayed at a psychiatric facility to avoid being tried for Lisa
Steinberg's death.
   Defense lawyer Ira London said Ms. Nussbaum's stay at a
psychiatric institution is part of the ``packaging of her'' by her
lawyer, Barry Scheck.
   ``We feel she's avoided prosecution by hiding in a mental
institution,'' London said of the prosecution's chief witness.
   Steinberg, 47, a disbarred lawyer, is charged in the 1987 death
of his illegally adopted 6-year-old daughter, who was taken from the
Greenwich Village apartment he shared with Ms. Nussbaum and died
three days later.
   Ms. Nussbaum, his long-time companion, was arrested along with
Steinberg. But charges were dropped after prosecutors concluded she
had been abused by Steinberg and was in no physical or emotional
shape to harm or help the child.
   She testified for the prosecution.
   Meanwhile, Steinberg agreed to be examined by prosecution
psychiatrists later today, sources who spoke on condition of
anonymity said Tuesday. But the sources said there was no guarantee
he wouldn't back out at the last minute.
   The question of Steinberg's mental state at the time of the
child's death, and whether he would present an insanity defense, has
become a key issue in the trial.
   London on Tuesday attacked Ms. Nussbaum's credibility as he told
state Supreme Court Justice Harold Rothwax why he should permit
testimony by a psychiatrist who interviewed Ms. Nussbaum at a
hospital shortly after the girl's death.
   ``Her condition for the past year is a fraud,'' London told
Rothwax, ``and it is part of her packaging.'' The lawyer told the
judge that whether Ms. Nussbaum is a ``malingerer'' is a credibility
issue the jury should look at.
   London said the psychiatrist would testify that Ms. Nussbaum
``has not needed that kind of treatment for the past year.''
   The judge granted London's request to allow the testimony.
   The attorney refused to say whether Steinberg would submit to the
psychiatric examination today, the deadline set by the judge. The
trial is to resume Thursday.
   Results of a prosecution psychiatric examination would be
presented to the jury only if the judge concludes that Steinberg's
attorneys are in effect presenting an insanity defense through the
testimony of their witnesses.
   Rothwax set the deadline for the examination after indicating
that he might rule later that an informal insanity defense was being
pursued.
   If Steinberg refuses to be examined by a prosecution
psychiatrist, and the judge concludes that his lawyers are indeed
presenting an insanity defense, the jurors will be told about his
refusal to be examined.
</TEXT>
