<FIRST>r a PM-ArsonArrest     01-11 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arson Arrest,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Arrested in Arson Fire Which Killed Four People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who ``kept popping up too many times'' at
fires was charged with setting four blazes, including one that
killed four people and another for which he had someone else
indicted, police said.
   Buddy Marts, 21, was arrested Tuesday and charged with murder and
arson for the fatal fire in August. Police said he may be
responsible for at least 25 blazes.
   ``He was at a lot of them,'' said Detective Tim O'Meara. ``His
name kept popping up too many times.''
   O'Meara said Marts admitted setting the fatal fire, and ``tells
us he needs a lot of help.''
   The fire in August was in a building that contained both stores
and apartments. According to O'Meara, Marts told authorities he
didn't know anyone in the building when he set fire to packing
materials on the first floor.
   ``When he'd have a fight with someone, he'd vent his frustration
by setting fires,'' said Chief of Detectives Edward Wodnicki.
   ``If he would see a pile of garbage in an alley, something would
tell him to set it on fire,'' O'Meara said. ``A lot of the fires
were just garbage fires.''
   Marts was charged with arson in three other fires that damaged
property but caused no injuries.
   In one of those fires, prosecutors won an indictment Nov. 29
against Michael J. Gillon, 21, based on Marts' testimony. They said
they would move to drop charges against Gillon today.
   Detective Wayne Micek said police had spoken with Marts several
times over the last four months. Each time, he offered information
about where certain fires started, who was seen nearby or who was
running from the scene.
   Micek said officers examined the records of a number of fires and
noticed that Marts had been at the scene of several. ``It just
clicked,'' Micek said.
</TEXT>
