<FIRST>u i PM-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru a0488 01-11 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0488,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>President To Lift State Of Emergency At Midnight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with military official saying some anti-terrorism
powers to be maintained and ADD Indian troops withdrawing. No pickup. ^By
DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa said
today that the 5{-year state of emergency will be lifted at
midnight, providing for the release of hundreds of political
prisoners, a government spokesman said.
   Premadasa, who took office nine days ago, had promised to end the
emergency in an effort to chart a more peaceful course for this
Indian Ocean island nation ravaged by ethnic violence since 1983.
   A military official, however, said security forces will retain
the power to arrest and detain suspects without charge for up to 90
days and search houses without warrants under an anti-terrorism law
adopted four years before the state of emergency. The official
cannot be identified under briefing rules.
   The state of emergency has been extended on a month-by-month
basis since May 1983. Premadasa had already vowed it would not be
renewed on its next expiration date, Sunday.
   But today he told his Cabinet the emergency would be lifted three
days early, according to Festus Perera, minister of information and
spokesman for the Cabinet.
   The state of emergency empowered security forces to arrest and
detain people without charge, dispose of bodies without inquests and
search houses without warrants.
   On Tuesday, Premadasa told top government officials: ``We have
lived under emergency regulations for now more than five years. I
feel that is enough time for everybody.''
   About the time the announcement was made, a small bomb exploded
in a market in central Colombo, injuring two people. Police said
they did not know whether the bombing was related to the ethnic or
political strife or stemmed from a private dispute.
   Sri Lanka, famed for its beaches and gemstones, fell into a
vicious cycle of violence in 1983 as extremists from the Tamil
minority launched an insurgency seeking autonomy from the Sinhalese
majority.
   More than 8,500 people _ mostly Sinhalese _ have since died in
massacres, ambushes and guerrilla battles. The dead include more
than 600 Indian soldiers, part of a peacekeeping force sent to Sri
Lanka at the government's invitation in July 1987 to try to disarm
Tamil insurgents.
   In his campaign for president, Premadasa pledged to press for
withdrawal of the 50,000 Indian troops. A few thousand were reported
to be pulled out earlier this month.
   In addition, more than 650 government supporters _ mostly
Sinhalese _ have been killed by Sinhalese extremists who opposed
former President Junius R. Jayewardene's efforts to make peace with
the Tamils by granting them some autonomy in northern and eastern
Sri Lanka.
   Jayewardene, who initiated the state of emergency, had governed
Sri Lanka since 1977. The Constitution barred him from seeking a
third term.
   Premadasa, prime minister under Jayewardene, won the Dec. 19
presidential election and was sworn in Jan. 2.
   Within five days, 574 political prisoners who had been held
without charge under the emergency were freed. About 1,800 more
political prisoners were still being held, but Premadasa said all
would be freed as quickly as possible.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890111-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1139EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   01-11 0811</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0849</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout
the nation.
   Jan. 7
   The Phoenix Gazette on testing airport security with fake bombs:
   ``Congratulations!'', the note said. ``You have found our phony
bomb! We are TF-1, the largest television network in France, and it
is with due respect and great pleasure that ... we found your
company to be keen and consistent with security matters.''
   Authorities at the freight offices of three airlines at Kennedy
International Airport, where the fake bombs were found, were not
amused. French television reporter Alain Chaillou and his American
producer, Bruce Frankel, were arrested after they delivered their
make-believe bombs.
   Certainly there have been more sophisticated gestures by the
media for the sake of a story. But probing the integrity of security
... is certainly a benevolent undertaking.
   There are risks, of course. Alain Chaillou and Bruce Frankel are
charged with falsifying an incident, a federal offense, and face
prison sentences if found guilty. But the benefits of their crude
charade quickly became apparent, as Air France announced that
because of the incident the airline would inspect every cargo
shipment.
   Alain Chaillou and Bruce Frankel did what journalists are
supposed to do, serve the truth fearlessly.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 4
   The Westerly (R.I.) Sun on the safety of older airplanes:
   Ever since a passenger plane flying in Hawaii lost a chunk of its
fuselage, we have been hearing a lot about stepped-up inspection of
aged aircraft. ...
   When an Eastern Airlines Boeing 727 sprang a leak and lost cabin
pressure at 31,000 feet the other day, that was just one further
sharp reminder that the problem demands even more attention.
   The program begun by the Federal Aviation Administration ... is
laudable, but it still needs tightening. The program's deficiencies
are symbolized in the two aforementioned episodes.
   A crack in one plane has just been detected. But the system
missed the flaw that caused an emergency landing in Charleston
(W.Va.) when cabin air suddenly wooshed out through a hole in the
roof.
   That kind of discrepancy tends to make travelers nervous, and
rightly so.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 6
   Carlsbad (N.M.) Current-Argus on illiteracy:
   An estimated 23 million people in this country cannot read books
or newspapers. They cannot read street signs, restaurant menus, job
applications or welfare forms. Nor can they understand a bus or
subway schedule.
   An additional 35 million are functional illiterates, which means
they can read just well enough to scrape by.
   Last April, Congress approved a $50 million-a-year program to
deal with the national disgrace of illiteracy. But given the federal
government's fiscal constraints, the states, counties and cities
will bear the major responsibility for dealing with this problem.
   Stemming the rising incidence of illiteracy will require a
substantial investment of time and money. But the costs of failing
to do so are much higher.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 10
   St. Louis Post-Dispatch on abortion rights:
   The Supreme Court has decided to review Missouri's law regulating
abortions.
   That won't necessarily lead to a reconsideration of Roe vs. Wade,
the 1973 court decision legalizing abortion nationwide, but neither
is it a decision that people concerned with protecting privacy and
reproductive rights can welcome.
   Should, for example, abortions be performed in public hospitals?
The Missouri law forbids this; a decision by the 8th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals last July struck that provision down.
   Can a state require doctors to perform viability tests for
fetuses when the pregnancy is beyond its 19th week? Missouri law
requires this, in another provision the appeals court ruled against.
   What is the consequence of a state declaring that ``the life of
each human being begins at conception?'' Missouri declares this, in
yet another provision thrown out by the appeals court. ...
   The Missouri case is an important measure of the Supreme Court's
respect for women's hard-won rights to privacy and reproductive
freedom. They are rights that ... all Americans should hope the
Supreme Court will continue to hold ... in esteem.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 10
   Los Angeles Herald Examiner on Emperor Hirohito's funeral:
   Who attends Emperor Hirohito's upcoming funeral may be as
important a symbol to some Japanese as the monarch's
long-anticipated death.
   New Zealand and Australia, two countries where memories of the
brutal Japanese Army have not yet faded, are debating whether to
send any prominent officials at all.
   The Japanese government undoubtedly will be scrutinizing the list
of other attendees, hoping to gauge the country's international
acceptance as a peace-loving economic superpower. ...
   Photographs of mourners overcome with grief outside the Imperial
Palace make many Westerners wonder how one man could garner and
retain such respect.
   After all, Hirohito's 62-year reign included a catastrophic war
and the declaration that he was not a ``god incarnate.'' And he had
little to do with the most dynamic economic recovery in Japanese
history.
</TEXT>
