<HEAD>UNDATED: Japanese history.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 10
   Topeka (Kan.) Capital-Journal on American credibility:
   Americans have heard Washington's denials of any deal to trade
arms to Iran for hostages in Beirut or elsewhere; they have heard
official claims that the Nicaraguan Contras were a military
force-in-being that never intended to overthrow the Sandinistas and
many similar tales.
   The average citizen no longer knows when to believe his own
government on such matters.
   Such ``disinformation'' has not been peculiar to the Reagan
administration. It was practiced a lot by the Johnson
administration, for example. ...
   The Bush administration would be well advised to set about
restoring U.S. credibility _ at home and aborad.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 9
   Battle Creek (Mich.) Enquirer on poverty in America:
   President Lyndon Johnson declared war in his first State of the
Union message: a War on Poverty. ``It will not be a short or easy
struggle,'' he predicted on Jan. 8, 1964.
   Twenty-five years later, Americans are better off, but battles
still need to be fought for select groups.
   The poverty level was 13.5 percent in 1986, which translates to
32.5 million Americans living in poverty. ... Since 1964, the lowest
nationwide poverty rate was 11.1 percent in 1973, which climbed to
14 percent by 1983.
   In 1986, the poverty rate was 10.5 percent for whites. However,
rates were 33.1 percent for blacks and 28.2 percent for Hispanics.
...
   In terms of age, the highest poverty rates are among young
families. ...
   If President-elect George Bush adheres to the 1988 Republican
platform, no new major federal anti-poverty programs appear likely.
So if the war is to continue, local and state efforts need to focus
on:
   Encouraging our youth to get the education they need to stay out
of the poverty cycle. ...
   Better training of minorities and women for jobs in the local
work force. ...
   Voluntary or mandatory action to get quality day care so single
parents can get available jobs.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 9
   The Daily Oklahoman, Oklahoma City, on Oliver North:
   The government's case against Oliver North is slowly crumbling
away, and that's neither surprising nor lamentable.
   After nine months of costly legal preparations for trial of the
former White House aide, independent counsel Lawrence Walsh has
asked for dismissal of the two charges that were central to the
prosecution.
   He had little choice but to drop the conspiracy and theft counts
because of the Reagan administration's refusal to release classified
material a judge said North needs to get a fair trial.
   With the heart of this case gone, Walsh should now move to drop
the remaining 12 charges and put an end to this fruitless endeavor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 8
   The Palm Beach (Fla.) Post on Oliver North:
   Independent counsel Lawrence Welch, saying he was concerned that
government secrets were at risk, asked the federal court to withdraw
two main charges against Col. (Oliver) North. ...
   The sensitivity of the evidence is something the public will have
to accept on the word of ... Walsh, who had promised to put up a
fight for it. ...
   If a former president or even a sitting president can give
evidence that could help a defendant, he should be made to do so.
   A constitutional case can be made for executive immunity when the
issue is between the executive and Congress, but a president should
not be above the law when a citizen's freedom is at stake.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 10
   The Clarion-Ledger, Jackson, Miss., on Oliver North:
   Was Iran-Contra prosecutor Lawrence Walsh correct to seek to
dismiss conspiracy and theft charges against former White House aide
Oliver North? Probably.
   Was justice served by the move? Probably not.
   The move to dismiss conspiracy and theft charges against North
adds yet another troubling conflict in the Iran-Contra affair. ...
   The American people are simply left with no choice but to trust
the judgment of those keeping the classified information. They are
left no choice but to accept Walsh's decision about what charges he
can most effectively prosecute.
   But North still would face 12 other charges. Those charges should
be pursued.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 6
   The Daily News, Longview, Wash., on Democrats and vote
projections:
   The Democratic Governors Association called a news conference in
Los Angeles (Jan. 4) to urge Congress to approve nationwide uniform
poll closing.
   The Democratic Party may be as bad off as some observers
suggested. Its governors _ who should be providing some party
leadership _ are hung up on network predictions in presidential
races.
   They imply that these projections are decreasing voter
participation by convincing supporters of projected losers that they
have no reason to vote. But November's race produced nothing to
support that idea.
   Their complaint really boils down to the lack of suspense in the
past couple of presidential races for voters on the West Coast.
   That doesn't call for legislation that would inconvenience much
of the rest of the nation. Suspense will return to the presidential
race when the Democrats deliver a candidate who can avoid being
buried in an electoral landslide.
</TEXT>
