<HEAD>UNDATED: electoral landslide.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 4
   The Hudson Dispatch, Union City, N.J., on 30 years of Fidel
Castro:
   Thirty years ago, (Fidel) Castro was a youthful liberator and the
foe of a corrupt tyranny. Cuba's economy was among Latin America's
most advanced.
   Many positive changes were to come in health standards, literacy
and basic social services.
   Cuba today remains poor, unfree and dependent. Free speech and a
free press are stifled. ... Its record of human rights abuses
remains an international scandal, the worst in Latin America.
   So far, Castro has resisted the Soviet lead of economic and
social liberalization, and modification of orthodox communism. He
continues to expouse a Cold War with the United States, and as long
as he does, his nation remains rooted in stagnation.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 10
   Herald and Review, Decatur, Ill., on nuclear waste:
   Nuclear plants had a record year in 1988: They provided a full 20
percent of the nation's electricity. ... But another report should
give the rest of us pause.
   In the same week, the non-profit research organization Public
Citizen said 1987 was a dismal year for nuclear power industry.
   In 1987, the private agency said, there were at least 492
violations of safety regulations at U.S. nuclear power plants.
Moreover, there were nearly 3,000 ``mishaps,'' 430 emergency
shutdowns and 104,000 incidents in which workers were exposed to
measurable doses of radiation. ...
   The gravest problems facing mankind today involve pollution and
the environment. Despite mandates from the federal government that
every state establish hazardous waste sites and low-level nuclear
waste storage sites, no one wants such facilities in their back
yard. ...
   In the past, we tended to assume we would solve the questions of
what to do with radioactive waste and spent materials ``up the
road.'' Now that road appears to be a dead end. It's possible
there's no place on Earth to put this stuff safely.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 9
   Portland (Maine) Press Herald on federal pay raises:
   President Reagan has endorsed a proposal by an independent salary
commission to increase substantially the pay rates of members of
Congress and other federal employees. Under current law, the salary
hikes will take effect unless Congress specifically votes against
them. ...
   Congress would be doing itself _ and the country _ a big favor by
going along with the proposal.
   It will take courage because there has been substantial public
criticism of the plan, which calls for a whopping 50 percent
increase in congressional pay _ from $89,500 to $135,000. ...
   As part of the pay package, senators and representatives would
have to give up the odious practice of accepting outside honorariums
from special interest groups for speeches and other approaches. ...
   Accepting a pay increase _ even a big one _ under these
conditions is defensible. Continuing the practice of accepting
outside payments from special interest groups is not.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 8
   The Duluth (Minn.) News-Tribune on federal pay raises:
   Silence from this carping corner as Congress moved inexorably
toward a 50 percent pay hike for itself may have seemed tacit
acceptance of its wisdom _ or inevitability.
   Perish the thought. We think the idea stinks.
   Election to Congress is a public service. Those who opt for such
service shouldn't have to sell the family silverware to do so, but
they shouldn't expect to get even moderately rich while doing so. If
$135,000 a year isn't moderately rich, it'll do 'til the real thing
arrives.
   Sure it's costly to live in Washington, but the thousands of
District of Columbia residents not at the top of the federal pay
scale manage to do it on a lot less than $135,000 a year.
   Washington is costly _ just look at your 1988 taxes on the form
you'll fill out soon to pay for that profligacy.
   But before you do, why not send a message to Congress: Until they
do a 50 percent better job, their employers have decided not to
grant them a 50 percent pay hike.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 9
   Philadelphia Inquirer on Cambodia:
   Ten years ago this month the Vietnamese army marched into Phnom
Penh, putting an end to the rule of the notorious Khmer Rouge
regime, which had killed one million Kampucheans (Cambodians) in its
warped attempt to create a communist Arcadia.
   This year, squeezed by its Soviet backers, Hanoi has pledged to
pull its troops out of Kampuchea (Cambodia) by the end of 1989.
   But without the presence of Vietnamese troops, well-armed Khmer
Rouge guerrillas could eventually march back into Phnom Penh.
   The United States is in a position to prevent such a disaster,
but it can't do it alone.
   The United States should pressure China to stop sending arms to
the Khmer Rouge, something the Chinese at last seem willing to do.
   The United States should also encourage all the key players to
agree to a formula for an interim government headed by Prince
Sihanouk, hopefully as a prelude to free elections.
   Here, the United States could use a promise of improved relations
with Vietnam, complete with economic aid, as a carrot to get Hanoi
to cooperate.
</TEXT>
