<FIRST>r a PM-Professors-TaxBreak     01-11 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Professors-Tax Break,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Historic Tax Break For Professors Falling Into Disuse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tax break for Brown University
professors that dates back to the days of King George III is being
phased out but still gives 32 faculty members a discount on their
property taxes, officials said.
   The Ivy League school has been phasing out the break, which
applies to the first $10,000 of the assessed value of a professor's
home, since 1966. Brown acted because of complaints that the tax
break costs the city money and is unfair.
   All newly hired or promoted professors since then have been
required to forgo their right to the exemption.
   ``Every year, there are a few less,'' said city tax assessor
Theodore Littler.
   Joyce M.K. Lewis, tax assessor in the suburb of Barrington, said
the exemption dates to the university's charter, issued by King
George in 1764.
   Originally, Brown tenured professors were exempt from all
property taxes, but the university and the Legislature narrowed the
exemption during the Civil War, Lewis said.
   When the university started phasing out the tax break 23 years
ago, 135 professors took advantage of it, 90 of whom lived in
Providence.
   Last year, the exemption for 25 city residents cost the city
$5,971, said Ancelin Lynch, university associate director for
government and community relations. That works out to about $240 per
professor.
   The school has 390 tenured professors as of last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
