<DOCNO> AP890111-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1150EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Angola     01-11 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Angola,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Observer Chief Defends Monitoring Procedure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUANDA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of the U.N. observers
appointed to monitor the withdrawal of Cuban troops from Angola said
today he is satisfied he will be able to conduct an independent
verification of the departure.
   South Africa and UNITA guerrillas fighting the Angolan government
have expressed doubt that an independent verification will be
possible.
   ``I think there will be no difficulties in carrying this
assignment out,'' Gen. Pericles Ferreira Gomes of Brazil told
reporters when asked about the ability of the 70 military and 20
civilian observers to verify the numbers of departing Cuban troops.
   But he also said the success of the 27-month mission depended on
the ``good will'' of the Angolan and Cuban governments, who agreed
to the phased withdrawal Dec. 22 and who are to supply the precise
numbers of Cuban troops when the monitoring procedure officially
begins April 1. South Africa and UNITA leaders have questioned the
wisdom of relying on such figures.
   Cuba first sent troops to Angola in July 1975 to support members
of the Angolan Popular Liberation Movement (MPLA), who were fighting
South African and U.S.-backed UNITA guerrillas for control of the
Portuguese colony that was to become independent in November of that
year.
   UNITA, or the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola, whose guerrillas number an estimated 25,000, is not party to
the agreement signed by Angola, Cuba and South Africa. The group
claims it is continuing attacks on Angolan forces in the south of
the country.
   On Tuesday a symbolic contingent of 450 Cuban troops departed by
plane for Havana. They reportedly were followed today by about 1,000
more troops on a Soviet ship.
   Under the terms of the U.S.-brokered agreement, 3,000 Cuban
troops are to have left this southern African nation by April 1.
Ferreira Gomes said he had been informed all 3,000 would be gone by
Sunday.
   He declined to give figures on departures through today, saying
it was up to the the Angolans and Cubans to make the figures public.
   Ferreira Gomes said under the terms of the agreement, designed to
bring independence to the South African controlled territory of
Namibia, both Cuban troops and arms were to be sent back to Cuba.
   He said 50,000 was the ``basic figure'' for the number of Cuban
troops to be withdrawn. But he added Angolan and Cuban officials
were to furnish exact figures on Cuban troops in Angola once the
U.N. observer mission is officially established April 1, when the
entire team is to have arrived in the country.
   He said the monitoring procedure of the unarmed observer force
will consist of checking the number of troops departing from four
ports and one airport against lists furnished by the Cubans and
Angolans.
   The general said the Angolan government is committed to providing
transport when needed to the U.N. observers, who have the mandate to
travel anywhere in the country.
   Road travel is difficult if not impossible in most of Angola
because of land mines and the presence of UNITA guerrillas.
   The Angolan government has requested U.N. assistance to defray
the estimated $800 million cost of the Cuban withdrawal. The U.N.
Security Council recently approved a $20.4 million budget for the
observer mission through mid-1991.
   The members of the observer mission are Algeria, Congo, India,
Jordan, Norway, Spain, Yugoslavia, Czechoslovakia, Brazil and
Argentina.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
