<DOCNO> AP890111-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Bentsen     01-11 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bentsen,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Finance Chairman Hints No Change in Tax for Catastrophic Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, chairman of the Senate
Finance Committee, indicated today that Congress will leave intact
the tax increase on older Americans that pays for new protecting
them against costs of catastrophic illness.
   ``We might have some oversight hearings, but they would be more
to publicize'' details of the program than to determine how the tax
should be changed, Bentsen said at a news conference.
   The Texas Democrat acknowledged receiving a lot of letters
protesting the new tax, but he said ``the mail shows a lot of people
don't know details of the bill and there is a great deal of
misinformation on that legislation.''
   Scores of House members are co-sponsoring signed bills to repeal
or modify the new tax.
   Bentsen said much of the outcry is coming from wealthy retired
people who want more of the costs of catastrophic care financed by
taxpayers in general.
   On another topic, Bentsen said he expects Congress to crack down
on leveraged buyouts of corporations. He offered no details,
although one likely method would be to curtail the interest
deduction allowed on money borrowed to finance certain takeovers.
   ``I want to make sure the cure is not worse than the situation we
are facing now,'' Bentsen said. His committee and the House Ways and
Means Committee already have scheduled hearings on the issue.
   The former vice presidential candidate expressed hope that
President-elect George Bush will make substantial changes in the
budget that President Reagan submitted Monday. He said the 50
percent pay raise and mail allowances Reagan recommended for
Congress were excessive.
   Even with the new tax on the elderly, Bentsen said, the
catastrophic protection ``is the best buy in town. There's nothing
in the private sector that offers what it offers at those prices.''
   The catastrophic bill was enacted last year to protect
Medicare-eligible elderly Americans against costs of an illness that
could wreck them financially. The program is estimated to cost about
$33 billion over five years.
   Most of the cost will be paid by a surtax on several million
elderly people whose incomes are high enough that they pay a tax on
part of their Social Security benefits. This would hit only those
who pay at least $150 a year in income taxes. Congressional aides
say this exempts a typical couple with income under $11,000.
   The surtax for 1989 is 15 percent of the income tax paid, with a
maximum of $800 per individual, or $1,600 for a couple if both
spouses are eligible for Medicare. The surtax will jump to 25
percent next year and then rise by up to one percentage point a year.
   The premium for Part B Medicare coverage, for doctors' services,
has been raised to $31.10 a month to help pay for the
catastrophic-care program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
