<FIRST>u a PM-TeamstersTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0477 01-11 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teamsters Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0477,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Set To Let Jury Deliberate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with final instructions; PICKS
UP 4th graf pvs, `The government ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.R. KROPKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge began final instructions to the
jury this morning in the trial of two Teamsters officials charged in
a $700,000 payroll-padding scheme that allegedly involved the late
union boss Jackie Presser.
   Harold Friedman and Anthony Hughes were accused of racketeering
and embezzlement in the 2{-month-old trial. Presser, president of
the 1.6 million member union, also was charged in the case but died
in July at age 60.
   The jury received instructions from U.S. District Judge George W.
White before they were to begin deliberations. The trial opened Oct.
24 and included testimony from some 80 witnesses.
   The government said Hughes, 52, was a ``ghost employee'' at
Bakery Workers Local 19, which is affiliated with Teamsters Local
507 here. Dozens of grocers and bakers testified for the government
that they had no contact with Hughes.
   Much of Tuesday's closing arguments concerned Presser's actions
from the early 1970s through 1981, when Hughes and three other men
allegedly were paid a combined $700,000 from union dues without
working.
   ``The defense would have you believe all this was Jackie
Presser's responsibility,'' prosecutor Stephen Jigger said.
   ``Poor, powerless Harold Friedman, living in the fear of Jackie
Presser. I submit to you that the evidence in this case indicates
not only what Jackie Presser did but also what Harold Friedman and
Anthony Hughes did.''
   Friedman, 66, a Teamsters international vice president and Ohio's
most powerful Teamster, testified that Presser had unquestioned
power at Local 507, where he served as secretary-treasurer while he
was international president.
   ``The evidence demonstrates abuse of union office by Harold
Friedman, Anthony Hughes and Jackie Presser for the benefit of their
friends and cronies,'' Jigger said.
   The defense said it was Presser who hired John A. ``Jack'' Nardi
Jr., the son of a dead reputed organized crime figure, George Argie,
an admitted past operator of an illegal gambling operation, and
Allen Friedman, who is no relation to Harold Friedman. Each
testified for the prosecution that they were paid and did little
work, if any.
   The defense said Allen Friedman often was too ill to work.
   Harold Friedman was accused of two counts each of labor
racketeering, embezzlement and filing false reports with the Labor
Department; Hughes was charged with two counts of labor racketeering
and one of embezzlement.
   Defendant Friedman's attorney, Paul Cambria, said his client put
in long hours of work for his members and that his participation in
a scheme to embezzle members' money ``just doesn't make any sense.''
   ``I ask you not to be misled,'' Cambria said. ``You must
determine whether my client was a thief. Jackie Presser is gone.
Whether it had a lot to do with him or not is another story. My
client is on trial, not Jackie Presser.''
   John R. Climaco, Presser's former attorney, has said that
Presser's defense would have been that the FBI authorized him to
hire the ``ghost employees'' to enhance and protect his status as an
FBI informant.
   But prosecutors contend Presser couldn't have been authorized to
hire ``ghost employees'' because they were working as early as 1972
and Presser didn't become an FBI informant until 1977. Harold
Friedman's attorney said last week that Presser was a government
informant in 1963.
   The trial culminated the U.S. Justice Department and the
Department of Labor's six-year effort to uncover wrongdoing in the
Cleveland power base of Presser, who rose to the presidency of the
nation's largest union in 1983 and held the job until his death.
   Presser was the fourth of the last five Teamsters presidents to
be indicted; he inherited the job from Roy Williams when Williams
was sent to prison for conspiring to bribe a U.S. senator.
</TEXT>
