<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--LegislativeBoxes     01-11 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Legislative Boxes,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Mail Boxes Pose Problems At Legislature</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill boxes outfitted with combination
locks to foil would-be thieves at the new Legislative Office
Building work so well they even keep out their owners.
   ``We need a safecracker,'' complained one legislative official.
``The supervisor of the bill room ought to be (bank robber) Willie
Sutton.''
   The 697 boxes, which cost about $10,000, are stuffed daily with
legislative bills, schedules and records. The documents are
essential for keeping track of legislation and other developments at
the Capitol.
   The boxes replaced an older system, in which bills were stuffed
in pigeon holes assigned to news organizations, lobbyists and other
groups. There were no locks and doors, and sometimes material was
taken.
   Since this is the first session the boxes are being used, they're
``probably a little tight'' and more difficult to open, said David
B. Ogle, executive director of the Legislative Management Committee.
``People will get used to them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
