<FIRST>r a PM-People-Sadler     01-11 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Sadler,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Green Beret' Singer Barry Sadler Missing, Family Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer-author Barry Sadler, who suffered
brain damage when he was shot in the head last year in Guatemala, is
missing and needs medical attention, his family says.
   Sadler's wife and children said he was discharged Sunday night
from a Veterans Administration Hospital in Cleveland, Ohio, and they
don't know where he is now.
   Sadler, 48, whose ``Ballad of the Green Berets'' was a No. 1 song
in 1966 and who also has written a series of best-selling adventure
novels, was shot in the head during a robbery attempt at his home in
Guatemala City in September.
   He was brought to a VA hospital in Nashville and transferred to
the hospital in Cleveland in November.
   Sadler's wife, Lavona Ruth Sadler, and her children, who live in
Hendersonville and Murfreesboro, had planned to go to Ohio and fly
Sadler back to the Nashville hospital Monday.
   But Mrs. Sadler said the hospital night shift in Cleveland
believed ``they had to release him because he had not been adjudged
legally incompetent.''
   Hospital spokeswoman Jane Kennedy-Aspis was not immediately
available for comment this morning, her office said.
   Mrs. Sadler filed a lawsuit Tuesday seeking to establish a
guardianship for her husband, contending he is ``unable to attend to
his business affairs, make rational decisions or control all of his
bodily functions.''
   He also has a life-threatening blood clot in his left leg and a
catheter that could cause serious infection, the lawsuit said.
   Probate Judge Jim Everett appointed Thor Sadler, 24, as his
father's temporary guardian Tuesday and set a hearing for Jan. 18 on
a permanent guardian.
</TEXT>
