<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1233EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--LoggingBan     01-11 0143</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Logging Ban,0146</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thai Leaders OK Ban to End Logging After Lethal Floods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cabinet has approved a nationwide
ban on logging, which was blamed for aggravating November floods
that killed more than 350 people, an official said Wednesday.
   Agriculture Minister Sanan Kachornprasart announced Tuesday that
$23.5 million had been allocated to create an armed force to guard
the forests.
   The floods, fed by heavy rain, caused havoc in 12 southern
provinces. In the worst-hit area, Nakhon Sri Thammarat, many people
were killed when mud, logs and trees cascaded down barren hillsides
and buried entire villlages.
   The ban would end the 301 logging concessions awarded nationwide.
It is expected to take effect when Prime Minister Chatichai
Choonhavan and King Bhumipol Adulyadej sign it within two weeks.
   Choonhavan says Thailand's need for wood products can be met by
imports.
</TEXT>
