<FIRST>r w PM-Reagan-Hostages     01-11 0143</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Reagan-Hostages,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Thinks of Hostages, Won't Guess When They'll be Freed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said today the plight of
American hostages in Lebanon has never been out of his mind since
they were seized, but he declined to speculate on whether they might
be released as he leaves office.
   ``I can only pray and continue what we've been (doing),'' Reagan
told reporters in response to a question. ``We've been exploring
every channel possible for their release, and they've never been out
of my mind since they were so unfairly seized.''
   The president was then asked if there might be a repeat of what
happened in 1981, when American hostages held in Iran were released
on Inauguration Day.
   ``I won't hazard any speculation on that,'' he said. ``It's just,
it's a great tragedy. We hope that it can be resolved.''
</TEXT>
