<DOCNO> AP890111-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1255EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NJInsurance     01-11 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NJ Insurance,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Kean: Abolish No Fault, `Shoot It And Put Us Out Of Our
Misery'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Faced with repeated political defeats, angry
motorists and insurance rates averaging more than $1,000 a car, Gov.
Thomas H. Kean said it may be time to abolish New Jersey's no-fault
auto insurance system.
   ``If we can't have real no-fault, it is time to admit the system
doesn't work and close it down, shoot it and put us out of our
misery,'' Kean said in his State of the State message Tuesday.
   Kean has said before it may be time to abolish the 16-year-old
system, arguing that rates will continue to rise if lawmakers do not
pass his proposal to place strict limits on lawsuits. But he has
never said it so combatively or in such a prominent forum.
   Kean spokesman John Samerjan said Wednesday that the governor
made the statement out of frustration with lawmakers and has not
been working on a formal proposal to abolish the system.
   More than 20 states have no-fault insurance, under which the
medical bills of accident victims are paid regardless of who was at
fault, said Leonard Karp, a spokesman for the state Department of
Insurance.
   For six years, the Legislature has refused to limit lawsuits to
only the most seriously injured. Lobbyists for the legal profession
contend such limits will strip victims of their right to sue in
exchange for a savings of only $100 per car.
   Auto insurance rates in New Jersey are among the highest in the
nation.
   The Joint Underwriting Association, a state-backed agency created
under the Kean administration in 1983 to cover drivers unable to
purchase coverage in the private market, is staggering under a
deficit of more than $2.5 billion.
   To keep the JUA afloat, all of the state's more than 4 million
drivers pay an average of $220 per car in annual surcharges.
   A series of reforms took effect Jan. 1 to contain rising rates by
increasing deductibles, requiring accident victims to pay part of
their medical costs and imposing a fee schedule on how much doctors
may charge.
   The reforms also allow drivers to limit their right to sue in
exchange for lower premiums, but Kean has said such an option is
inadequate.
   ``I was shocked. It's like he was looking for something dramatic
to round out his speech,'' said Michael M. Rossi III, president of
the Independent Insurance Agents of New Jersey. ``We just went
through a long, arduous task of legislative wheeling and dealing and
now we're seeing the beginning of that law. He has to give the law a
chance to work.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
