<SECOND>AM-BRF--Architecture Award,0163</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pelli Firm Wins Design Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cesar Pelli &amp; Associates, designer of the World
Financial Center office towers in Manhattan and a master plan for
Hartford, Conn., on Wednesday was named winner of the American
Institute of Architect's Architectural Firm Award for 1989.
   The award is issued annually to a firm that has consistently
produced distinguished architecture for at least 10 years. The AIA
award jury praised the firm as ``an outpost of consistent quality
finely realized.''
   The firm, which is based in New Haven, Conn., was formed in 1977
by Pelli, Diana Balmori and Fred Clarke.
   Their designs include the expansion and renovation of the Museum
of Modern Art; Northwest Center in Minneapolis; apartment buildings
on the sites of Carnegie Hall and the Museum of Modern Art; and the
proposed new Madison Square Garden. The firm also has designed
master plans for Rice University, Erieview, Ohio, and the Fan Pier
development in Boston.
