<FIRST>r a PM-ParkSquatter     01-11 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Park Squatter,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politicians Take Sides In Move To Evict Long-time Park Squatter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 71-year-old woman facing eviction from
her ramshackle home in a state park ridiculed a suggestion that she
be allowed to stay, in new quarters, as an honorary park ranger.
   ``They want to make me a park ranger? I'm laughing through my
tears, really,'' said Doris Gagnon. ``They must think I have a screw
loose.''
   The Department of Environmental Protection, which is drafting
plans to develop the park, decided Tuesday to initiate eviction
proceedings after Gagnon ignored a Monday deadline for leaving the
property, officials said.
   At the same time, a letter from the eight Republicans on the
15-member Milford board of aldermen was sent to department
Commissioner Leslie Carothers proposing the compromise that would
permit Gagnon to remain.
   ``I think everyone wants the park to move forward. But I think it
would be better to go in the direction of honoring Doris _ she is
sort of folklore in this city,'' said Frederick Lisman, the
aldermen's Republican chairman.
   Wanda Rickerby, spokeswoman for the department, said Carothers
would not respond until she had received the proposal.
   Gagnon's home on Long Island Sound was one of 100 that were
demolished to make way for the park. After losing a court battle to
save her house in 1971, she established a series of ramshackle
homesteads in the vicinity of her old property. She has a small
camper and shacks with no running water.
   She said she expects to win millions of dollars in compensation
when the showdown over her eviction reaches the courts.
   The Republican aldermen proposed the state build a small house
for her in an out-of-the-way part of the park. As honorary park
ranger, she would look after things, Lisman said.
   ``To ask the taxpayers to again foot the bill is totally
irresponsible,'' said Joseph Castignoli, the Democratic leader on
the Board of Aldermen. ``No matter how small the house is, it's
going to cost the taxpayers.''
   Castignoli noted that the state, after determining the value of
Gagnon's home in 1969, provided $15,000 in compensation. After
Gagnon refused the payment, the state used it to satisfy two liens
on the property.
   Gagnon said Monday she gets water and takes showers at friends'
homes but lives at the homestead year-round.
</TEXT>
