<HEAD>At Least 21 Killed in Rebel Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist rebels burned the
headquarters of a military battalion and four buses in a new wave of
violence this week that killed at least 21 people, military
officials said Wednesday.
   In the latest attack, which occurred before dawn Wednesday, New
People's Army guerrillas commandeered two government vehicles from
deposed President Ferdinand Marcos' hometown and then burned four
buses owned by the provincial governor's family, officials said.
   Batac police chief Florentino Dumlao Gov. Rodolfo Farinas of
Ilocos Norte province said last year he had rejected demands by the
rebels for payment of ``revolutionary taxes.''
   In one of the bloodiest attacks, about 80 rebels raided a remote
army detachment in the province of Agusan del Sur early Tuesday,
said Col. Cristobal Gurrea, an army brigade commander on Mindanao
island. He said four soldiers were killed.
   He said that shortly afterward, rebels burned two houses used as
headquarters of a nearby army battalion.
   Military reports also said six rebels were killed in other
attacks on Negros island.
   The rebels have been fighting to topple the government for 20
years.
