<FIRST>u i PM-ChemicalConference 3rdLd-Writethru a0571 01-11 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chemical Conference, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0571,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conference Condemns Use Of Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 3rd pvs, ``U.S. delegates..., to UPDATE
with State Department comment. Pick up 4th pvs, ``The document...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the world's nations today condemned the use
of chemical weapons and urged a speedy conclusion to negotiations in
Geneva on eliminating toxic arms from the face of the earth.
   In a compromise between the United States and Arab nations, the
final declaration did not explicitly link the control of nuclear and
chemical weapons but referred to a 1978 United Nations document that
does so.
   U.S. delegates said they were pleased with the declaration, which
officials from 150 nations adopted by consensus after a five-day
meeting.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said the
administration was pleased with the outcome of the conference.
   ``The U.S. objectives for the conference were to focus worldwide
attention on the problems of chemical weapons use and chemical
weapons proliferation and help put a stop to the use of these
weapons in violation of international law,'' he said.
   The document reaffirmed the 1925 Geneva Protocol prohibiting the
use of chemical weapons and called for stepped-up negotitions in
Geneva to ban the development, production and storage of chemical
arms. It also urged giving the U.N. secretary-general more power to
investigate chemical weapons use.
   The participating states ``solemnly affirm their commitments not
to use chemical weapons and condemn such use. They recall their
serous concern at recent violations as established and condemned by
the competent organs of the United Nations,'' the declaration said.
   ``The participating states stress the necessity of concluding, at
an early date, a convention on the prohibition of the development,
production, stockpiling and use of all chemical weapons, and on
their destruction. This convention shall be global and comprehensive
and effectively verifiable.''
   Arriving at a consensus required days of haggling and compromise.
U.S. officials said that they got more than they expected.
   ``We're very pleased with a very substantive declaration that
hits all the main points that the conference should have
addressed,'' said Gary Crocker, a member of the U.S. delegation.
``The important thing is that we have the world's attention focused
on this serious problem.''
   The declaration, which is not binding, illustrates ``the common
will of nations to condemn chemical weapons,'' Kalevi Sorsa of
Finland, chairman of the drafting committee, told reporters after
the meeting ended.
   Sorsa said obtaining a consensus ``required concessions and
compromises from all sides.'' But, ``From here on we can refer back
to the Paris conference and its text.''
   The resolution reaffirms participating nations' commitment to a
Geneva protocol that bans the use of chemical weapons but not their
production and storage. The protocol often has been ignored since it
was signed 67 years ago.
   Arab delegates failed to persuade the meeting to implicitly
condemn Israel's alleged nuclear capability. Foreign Minister Tariq
Aziz of Iraq said he and his Arab colleagues finally decided not to
take a position that would prevent the success of the conference.
   Work on the declaration continued through Tuesday night to
reconcile deep-seated differences between industrialized nations and
Arab states. Including the word ``nuclear'' became the main obstacle
to consensus.
   Arab states wishing to retain the right to have chemical weapons
to offset Israel's alleged nuclear force, had asked that chemical
disarmament be linked directly to nuclear disarmament, a position
opposed by the United States and the Soviet Union.
   In the end, the declaration excluded the word ``nuclear,'' but
referred to the final declaration of the 1978 U.N. General Assembly
session devoted to disarmament that linked nuclear and chemical
negotiations.
   Aziz complained, ``That draft falls short of our concerns ...
Where there is one country that has nuclear weapons and that country
that has mass destruction weapons is not a signatory to the
non-proliferation treaty ... and has refused to reach peace ... that
nation constitutes a real threat to the peace and security of the
region.''
   Both the superpowers have thousands of tons of chemical weapons
in storage, and the United States has a program to develop new
sophisticated systems.
   Another 20 nations, including many at the conference, possess the
weapons or are in the process of developing them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
