<FIRST>r i AM-Vietnam-US     01-11 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam-US,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam: More U.S. Remains To Be Returned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE ESPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HANOI, Vietnam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam will give more remains of Americans
missing in action to a U.S. team arriving Thursday, and joint
excavations of crash sites will be conducted, a government official
said.
   ``I think there will be quite a number,'' said Nguyen Can, acting
director of the Vietnam office for MIAs, referring to the remains.
``I don't want to make it known yet because they have to be
carefully identified.''
   Can said in an interview with The Associated Press that Vietnam
had been trying its best to speed up the return of American remains
from the Vietnam War.
   He said it is allowing U.S. teams to roam the country,
interviewing witnesses and officials in regions where the planes are
believed to have gone down. The latest team will be in Vietnam for
about 10 days, he said.
   Can denied again that there are any living American prisoners
being held in Vietnam and that Hanoi was withholding MIA remains and
handing them over to the United States when it suited its political
purposes.
   ``Even the U.S. State Department and Pentagon offcials do not
believe that there are any American prisoners in Vietnam,'' Can
said. ``This they know for sure, but because of the pressure from
the Rambo faction and the right wing in the United States they just
say it cannot be asserted that there are or there are not living
American prisoners in Vietnam.''
   Can said it would make no sense for Vietnam to hold American
prisoners or remains.
   ``What good is it for us to keep one or two American prisoners?''
he said. ``What good is it for us to hold remains if we returned to
the United States nearly 600 POWs? Why should we keep the remains?
Living prisoners of war are much more valuable if we choose to use
them as leverage.''
   Vietnam wants badly to establish diplomatic relations with the
United States. That would open the way for help for its faltering
economy with financial aid and the lifting of an American trade
embargo.
   The United States has said Vietnam first must withdraw all of its
troops from Cambodia, which Hanoi has promised to do no later than
1990.
   The United States insists the question of MIAs is a separate
humanitarian issue, but has told Vietnam that its cooperation in
returning American remains would be looked upon favorably.
   On Dec. 15, Vietnam turned over 38 sets of remains believed to be
those of American servicemen. It was the largest such repatriation
since the Vietnam War ended on April 30, 1975.
   Since the end of the war, Vietnam has returned the remains of 172
Americans identified by the Army.
   There are still 2,383 Americans listed as missing in action,
including 1,747 in Vietnam, 547 in Laos, 83 in Cambodia and six in
China.
   It is unlikely that the United States and Vietnam will be able to
account for all of the MIAs due to the lapse in time and the jungle
terrain where many of the airmen were lost.
   Can said part of the U.S. team arriving Thursday would operate in
what was once the demilitarized zone that divided North and South
Vietnam during the war.
   A joint team probably would excavate a crash site near the
Chinese border, he said.
   This will be the fourth joint effort to account for MIAs since
the joint searches were begun in October. Each operation runs about
10 days.
</TEXT>
