<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1410EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Reagan-Sharansky     01-11 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Sharansky,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sharansky Receives Gold Medals From Reagan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan presented congressional gold
medals to Soviet human rights activists Natan and Avital Sharansky
Wednesday, saying they were given on ``behalf of all mankind, not
just all Americans.''
   Sharansky, receiving the awards for himself and his absent wife
at a ceremony in the Oval Office, praised Reagan's efforts on behalf
of human rights and urged President-elect Bush, standing beside
Reagan, to continue them.
   The awards to the Sharanskys were authorized by a law passed by
Congress on May 13, 1986, for their work for human rights and
freedom of Soviet Jewry.
   ``This is in behalf of all mankind, not just all Americans,
because of what you have done and your courage over the years,''
Reagan said. ``Nine years of imprisonment on false charges and still
retained your poise and your strength to do this.''
   Sharansky told Reagan that ``thousands and thousands of people in
Soviet camps ... are free today not because of some goodwill of
Soviet leaders but because of their struggle and your struggle.''
   ``And you, president-elect, please think about those thousands
and thousands who are still there and who are praying now for you
and that you will be as stubborn, as strong, for defending human
rights in the Soviet Union,'' he told Bush.
   ``All of your record ... convinces us that you will continue the
fantastically good record on human rights that President Reagan ...
had,'' he said.
   While talking to reporters in a White House driveway, Sharansky
said that while he believes an international human rights conference
in Moscow in 1991 ``can be positive,'' he is concerned that it
``could become the biggest public relations event in the history of
Soviet human rights.''
</TEXT>
