<FIRST>r a AM-People-Tower 1stLd-Writethru a0601 01-11 0134</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Tower, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0601,0135</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tower Leaves Dallas Hospital</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf to CORRECT to Habgood, sted Hapgood.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary-designate John Tower was
dismissed from a hospital Wednesday, a week after entering for
removal of a colon polyp.
   ``His physician said he had exemplary recovery,'' said Stephen
Habgood, a spokesman for Baylor University Medical Center, where
Tower underwent surgery Thursday.
   The polyp was discovered during a colonscopy examination Dec. 27
and removed during a three-hour operation by R.J. Dignan. A biopsy
of the growth revealed it to be benign, doctors said.
   A small polyp removed from Tower's rectal area in November
contained both benign and malignant cells, Habgood said.
   Tower, a U.S. senator from Texas for 24 years, was selected Dec.
16 by President-elect Bush as his Defense secretary.
</TEXT>
