<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1432EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     01-11 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new tourism ad campaign invites residents of
Chicago _ known in song as ``that toddling town'' _ to ``toddle on
up to Milwaukee.''
   Some Chicagoans may wonder why, but Milwaukee tourism officials
were ready for that. They hired sports commentator Al McGuire, whom
they tout as a ``noted travel authority'' to describe the charms of
``my hometown, Milwaukee.''
   It's all part of a joint effort by the Wisconsin Council on
Tourism and the Greater Milwaukee Convention and Visitors Bureau to
bring tourists flocking from Chicago, 90 miles to the south.
   Newspaper and radio advertisements due to start Sunday and run
through March in the Chicago area include broadcast commercials in
which McGuire calls on Chicagoans to experience the performing arts,
night life, restaurants and other activities in Milwaukee.
   ``So come on, you toddlin' town,'' he says in one ad. ``Toddle on
up to Milwaukee for the weekend.''
   The campaign is being financed with $100,000 from the state
council and another $100,000 solicited by the bureau from businesses
and hotels.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bronze statue of a wild boar at Kansas
City International Airport has been fed dimes, quarters and an
occasional dollar bill from passers-by. But recently it reaped a
real windfall.
   A Minneapolis couple made out checks for $500 and $250 and
slipped them into a slot at the base of the boar. ``I think it's a
worthy cause,'' said Clarence J. Haugh.
   Haugh wasn't referring to the boar. Contributions given to the
beast _ and to another boar at Kansas City's Country Club Plaza _
are turned over to Children's Mercy Hospital.
   Miller Nichols, former chairman of the company that developed the
Country Club Plaza, said he noticed one of the boar statues in a
store window while strolling along a riverbank in Florence, Italy,
in the late 1940s.
   ``You know,'' he said he remarked to his daughter, ``that's a
marvelous piece of sculpture, but I don't know how I would use it.''
   He said the owner told them that the original wild boar statue
was in the Straw Market of Florence and that gifts made to the
casting went to a children's orphanage. And so an idea was born.
   Nichols said he bought the statue for $2,500 and placed it at the
Country Club Plaza. Years later he returned to Florence and bought a
second statue, this one for $7,500, to put at the airport.
   The two statues produce about $7,000 annually for the hospital.
Half the money is given directly to the hospital and half goes into
an endowment fund, which totals more than $36,000.
</TEXT>
