<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1446EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bentsen-CatastrophicTax     01-11 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bentsen-Catastrophic Tax,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bentsen Anticipates No Changes In New Tax On Older Americans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blaming wealthy retirees for most of the
complaints, the chairman of the Senate Finance Committee said
Wednesday he anticipates no changes in a new tax on older Americans
that pays for protection against costs of catastrophic illness.
   ``There's a vocal minority sounding off'' about the tax, Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, told reporters, adding that the outcry will
subside once details of the program, which took effect Jan. 1, are
better known.
   Mail and phone calls are coming chiefly from ``wealthy people who
want it (cost of the catastrophic protection) to be more heavily
subsidized by taxpayers'' in general, he said.
   Will the clamor lead to repeal or modification of the tax?
Bentsen was asked. ``I don't think that's going to happen,'' he
said, recalling that similar complaints were heard when Social
Security and Medicare were enacted.
   Although dozens of members of Congress have signed bills to
repeal or change the tax, Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of
the House Ways and Means Committee, has taken a stand similar to
Bentsen's.
   Although having Congress' two top tax-writers in support of a
program is good insurance, it was not enough to save another hotly
debated tax law in 1983. Lawmakers eventually bowed to a massive
mail campaign promoted by the banking industry and repealed a
year-old law that withheld taxes from some interest and dividend
payments.
   Congress is hearing few complaints about the basic
catastrophic-protection program, which helps elderly and disabled
Americans who are eligible for Medicare bear the cost of illnesses
that otherwise would threaten their financial stability. The
complaints are directed at the method of financing the program.
   The lion's share of the cost is paid by a surtax that falls on
all those eligible for Medicare whose incomes are high enough that
they pay at least $150 a year in federal income taxes. The surtax is
15 percent of the income tax in 1989; next year it rises to 25
percent, and each year after it could climb by as much as one
percentage point a year.
   Congressional aides estimate about 40 percent of people past the
age of 65 will pay the surtax on their 1989 income.
   The maximum surtax on any person is $800 this year, or $1,600 for
a couple if both spouses are eligible; by 1993 it will rise to
$1,050 and $2,100. Congress estimates the average surtax will be
$285 per person in 1989 and $506 in 1993.
   A couple would have to make more than $70,000 to pay the maximum
$800 premium this year, Bentsen said.
   In addition to the surtax, retirees and the disabled who buy
Medicare to pay for physicians' fees are paying a higher Part B
premium because of catastrophic coverage. The monthly premium is
$31.10 this year and is expected to rise to $42.60 a month by 1993.
   Some retirees are upset that they are forced to buy catastrophic
coverage whether are not they want it, and claim they could do
better by buying private insurance.
   Bentsen said that for most retirees, that is not so. ``It's the
best buy in town,'' he said of catastrophic coverage. ``There's
nothing in the private sector that offers what it offers at those
prices.''
   Although only about 7 percent of retirees are expected to collect
on the catastrophic coverage, ``that's far more than the chanc of a
home burning,'' Bentsen said. Yet, people routinely buy fire
insurance policies, he noted, and predicted having the catastrophic
policy will ``give people the peace of mind that they are not going
to be wiped out financially.''
   He said the Finance Committee probably will have hearings on the
subject but more as a way of publicizing details of the program than
of deciding how to change the tax.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
