<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1452EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TielessTeacher     01-11 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tieless Teacher,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teacher Fired For Dress Code Violation Gets Tuition Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POINT PLEASANT, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school mathematics teacher
fired Dec. 19 for refusing to wear a tie and dress pants to class
received a $4,647 bill from the school system today for his son and
daughter's tuition.
   Bill Webb called the move ``one of lowest forms of harassment
I've ever heard of,'' but Superintendent Charles Chambers said that
Webb was not being singled out and that parents of all out-of-state
students were billed.
   Webb, who lives in Gallipolis, Ohio, said that because he taught
at Point Pleasant High School in West Virginia, tuition for his
children had been waived.
   On Monday, the Mason County Board of Education voted to bill
out-of-state students who attended local schools in the past two
years. Webb was charged for his daughter Jarrod, a senior, and son
Shannon, who graduated in 1987.
   Webb, whose firing for insubordination for not following the
school's faculty dress code was upheld last week by the state
education workers' grievance board, said he will pay the bill and
then fight it.
   Chambers, who became superintendent last summer, said state law
requires him to charge tuition for out-of-state students. He said
previous superintendents may have waived tuitions but had no right
to do so.
   The action applies to a handful of children in addition to Webb's.
   Webb had been suspended three times for defying the school's
dress code, which was instituted in August. He said that he does not
like wearing a tie and that his casual clothes make it easier to
communicate with students.
</TEXT>
