<FIRST>u a PM-AbandonedMarine     01-11 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abandoned Marine,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charges Withdrawn Against Marine In Death Of Corporal After Training
Exercise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charges were withdrawn at least
temporarily today against a sergeant accused of dereliction of duty
in the death of a fellow Marine who died in the California desert
after being left behind on a training exercise.
   A lawyer for Sgt. Christopher Clyde, 28, of Mentor, Ohio, argued
for dismissal of the charges on conflict-of-interest grounds.
   The lawyer, Capt. William Fisher, contended that the battalion
commander who convened the court-martial against Clyde is himself
under scrutiny in the death of Lance Cpl. Jason J. Rother, 19, of
Minneapolis, Minn.
   Presiding judge Maj. Kent Smith approved the withdrawal of
charges, which were referred to another officer and could be refiled.
   Rother's remains were found in the Mojave Desert near Twentynine
Palms, Calif., on Dec. 4. He was serving as a road guide during a
nighttime exercise Aug. 30. He was not reported missing until more
than a day later.
   Clyde, whose court-martial began Tuesday, was charged with
disobeying an order and dereliction of duty in granting leave to
Rother's squad leader the day the exercise ended.
   The squad leader's absence contributed to the delay in searching
for Rother, officials charged.
   On Tuesday, the Marine Corps announced it will reassign the two
top officers of Rother's battalion _ Lt. Col. Edward Robeson, the
battalion commander, and Maj. T.L. Holm, the battalion's executive
officer _ within the unit.
   Maj. Stuart Wagner, the chief spokesman for base, said no
disciplinary action has been taken against Robeson and Holm.
</TEXT>
