<HEAD>Indian Airlines Plane Makes Emergency Landing After Hitting Bulls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Indian Airlines jetliner made an
emergency landing Wednesday after it hit two bulls during takeoff
and caught fire, United News of India news agency said.
   There were no injuries to the 98 passengers and crew members
aboard the Boeing 737, which was severely damaged, the news agency
said.
   Flight IC-213 was taking off from Guwahati for a flight to
Calcutta in eastern India when the incident occurred.
   The two bulls strayed on to the runway when the plane was taking
off, UNI said. The news agency did not say what happened to the
animals.
   Indian Airlines is the country's major domestic carrier, flying
to 93 destinations in India and nine abroad.
   Indian Airlines came under criticism follwoing an Oct. 19 crash
that killed 133 people. It was criticized for the lack of fitness of
its technical staff, for the poor maintenance of its aging fleet,
and for delays that have become endemic.
