<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1545EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SeditionTrial     01-11 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sedition Trial,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Says Woman Accused Of Seditious Conspiracy Acted Only As Mother</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman accused of joining a plot to
bring down the government acted only as a mother and a wife when she
joined her husband in his clandestine life, her attorney told a
federal jury Wednesday.
   ``His reasons ... were political. Her reasons were personal,''
attorney William Newman said in opening arguments in defense of
Patricia H. Gros Levasseur, 40.
   Mrs. Levasseur is the wife of co-defendant Raymond Luc Levasseur,
42, of Calais, Maine. The couple and Richard Williams, 41, of
Boston, are on trial in U.S. District Court on charges of seditious
conspiracy, racketeering enterprise and racketeering conspiracy.
   The three are accused of belonging to the United Freedom Front
and the Sam Melville-Jonathan Jackson Unit, a group that allegedly
plotted bombings and bank robberies throughout the Northeast from
1976 until their arrest in 1984. Prosecutors say their purpose was
to overthrow the government.
   Among the 19 bombings they are accused of planning was a 1976
explosion at the Suffolk Superior Courthouse in Boston that injured
22 people.
   Newman told the 12 jurors and five alternates that Mrs. Levasseur
grew up in a large, poor family in eastern Maryland and was deeply
affected by racial segregation and the impact of the Vietnam War on
her neighborhood.
   He said she became active in community work after leaving home,
including literacy and child-care programs, and met Levasseur in
1976 through a prison-reform group in Portland, Maine.
   Newman said Mrs. Levasseur joined her husband in his decision to
live ``away from the eyes and ears of the government'' in 1976
because she had borne his child. The couple had two more children
before they were arrested in November 1984 in Deerfield, Ohio.
   The attorney described her work before her arrest as that of a
full-time mother who participated in school bake sales and took her
children shopping and to doctors' appointments.
   ``She did everything you expect a normal caring mother to do,''
he said. ``The evidence will not establish that she ever robbed a
bank, ever cased a bank, ever drove a getaway car. ... There will be
no proof that she ever built a bomb or ever set a bomb.''
   The trial opened Tuesday with Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael
Loucks saying he intended to show the defendants conspired to bomb
courthouses, military offices and corporations and planned robberies
from Maine to Virginia.
   Levasseur, serving as his own lawyer, called himself a
revolutionary in opening arguments Tuesday and noted that one of the
explosions listed in the indictment occurred shortly after
anti-apartheid demonstrators were fired upon in South Africa.
   He told the jury: ``You ought to ask yourself the question, `Who
are the real criminals? Those who oppose racist acts in South Africa
or those who support government interests in South Africa?'''
   The three defendants were among eight arrested in one of the
largest manhunts in U.S. history. One will be tried separately, two
have have pleaded guilty to charges, and prosecutors dropped charges
against two others because they are already serving long prison
terms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890111-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1555EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FarmProgram     01-11 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Program,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmers Union: `Decoupling' Subsidies From Crops Would Devastate
Farmers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Farmers Union called Wednesday on
Congress to reject a proposal to let farmers collect federal
subsidies without regard to the kind of crops they produce.
   NFU president Leland Swenson said the idea, known as
``decoupling,'' would be ``devastating for farmers and rural
communities, endanger the environment and destablize the position of
Third World farmers.''
   Swenson told a news conference that decoupling would be a
``short-term welfare program'' and will be opposed vigorously by NFU
lobbyists.
   Decoupling has been around for years but has not had great
support on Capitol Hill. One of the early decisions by the incoming
Bush administration will be whether to embrace decoupling as a way
of containing government farm costs.
   The NFU's main rival, the American Farm Bureau Federation, at one
time supported decoupling but since has backed off to give it a
closer look.
   One of the biggest advocates is the Heritage Foundation, a
Washington-based conservative think tank, which recently issued a
task force report saying that one of the first jobs of the Bush
administration should be to cut subsidies and ``get farmers off the
dole.''
   Decoupling, the Heritage report said, would allow federal
payments to farmers to be based on a flat rate and targeted to those
most in need. As it has been for more than half a century, payments
now are pegged to specific kinds of crops and levels of production _
the larger the farm, the larger the subsidy.
   Under decoupling, farmers would simply be given a cash payment
and then be free to grow or not grow any crop they choose.
   ``Planting decisions (with decoupling) would then be based on
market signals _ consumer demand for a product _ rather than on what
is required by Washington,'' the Heritage report said.
   Swenson also released a report analyzing a decoupling bill
introduced by Sen. Rudy Boschwitz, R-Minn., in 1985 as the Family
Farm Protection and Full Production Act. He said the bill continues
to have some support in Congress, along with backing from big grain
companies such as Cargill Inc.
   ``It's really a cop-out in addressing the real issue of adopting
and implementing a farm program which enhances the market price for
agricultural commodities,'' Swenson said. ``It implies that the
family farm structure of agricuture is not important.''
   The analysis used figures attributed to the Institute for Trade
and Agricultrure, St. Paul, Minn., showing that the Boschwitz bill
would reduce federal price support loans sharply for major crops,
including wheat to $1.60 per bushel from $2.06 this year, and corn
to $1.30 per bushel from the 1989 rate of $1.65.
   ``Lowering of world prices, a result of decoupling, would
aggravate the situation of Third World farmers, who are our best
potential customers for U.S. food exports,'' Swenson said.
   The NFU, he said, will draft its own alternative to decoupling to
``assure consumers an adequate and dependable supply of food'' and
``enhance the market price of agricultural commodities.''
   Although Swenson did not disclose details of what NFU's plan
might include, he said it would ``reduce the budget impact of farm
programs'' and allow for a continued expansion of agricultural
exports.
   The 1988 drought helped siphon off huge stockpiles of U.S. grain,
boosting market prices for wheat to an average of $3.89 per bushel
last month from $2.70 a year earlier. Corn in December, according to
the Agriculture Department, averaged $2.54 per bushel, compared to
the year-earlier mark of $1.72 per bushel.
   Swenson was asked if the NFU would recommend an increase in
federal price supports to as much as current market prices. He
replied, ``Or higher.''
   The Reagan administration for eight years has been committed to a
market-oriented farm policy, less reliance on federal controls and
freer world trade. Those ideals are expected to continue under the
Bush administration.
   But Swenson is not convinced at this time that foreign countries
will go along with current U.S. agricultural trade objectives in the
Bush administration than they have in the Reagan years.
   ``There isn't such a thing as a free market,'' Swenson said. ``It
doesn't exist, will not exist, either in this country or any other
major exporting country in the world.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890111-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1604EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SpaceShuttle     01-11 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Space Shuttle Commander Confident of Feb. 23 Launch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of the next space
shuttle mission said Wednesday he is certain engineers will resolve
outstanding tile and engine problems in time to meet a Feb. 23
launch.
   ``All indications are that the people who are working those two
problems are confident they're going to come up with good answers on
both and they should not impact our launch,'' astronaut Michael
Coats said as he an his four crew members held a news conference to
discuss their flight aboard Discovery.
   Atlantis returned from orbit last month with severe damage to
about 200 of the 28,000 tiles that protect it from re-entry heat,
the most tile damage ever sustained by a shuttle. And during
post-flight inspection, two small cracks were found in a bearing
unit in a high-pressure engine turbopump.
   ``The engine problem is probably unique to that engine,'' Coats
said. ``They're looking at Discovery's engines now, and they have
spare turbopumps in case they have to make a replacement.''
   Engineers believe the cracks were caused by moisture that somehow
penetrated the housing that holds the bearing.
   Coats, who flew on one previous shuttle mission, a Discovery
flight in August 1984, said it appeared that Atlantis' tiles were
damaged by insulation falling off the nose cone of one of the solid
fuel booster rockets during liftoff.
   ``We're concerned about what caused the damage and are confident
it will be resolved,'' he said. ``But we're also reassured because
despite all the damage Atlantis' tiles took, it survived. I'm sure
our tiles will get us through re-entry. I'm not going to have
butterflies about it.''
   Discovery's five-day flight is set for liftoff at 8:30 a.m. EST
on Feb. 23. Flying with Coats will be pilot John Blaha and mission
specialists Robert Springer, James Buchli and James Bagian. Buchli
is the only other shuttle veteran on the crew; he flew aboard
Discovery in January 1983.
   Their main task will be to deploy a tracking and data relay
satellite to complete a network of payloads that will enable ground
control centers to communicate almost full time with the space
shuttle and with several unmanned satellites.
   The astronauts will conduct several scientific and medical
experiments, including one in which four rats will be used to
determine how well injured bones heal in the weightlessness of
space. The legs of the rats will be deliberately cut before launch.
   ``The bone reparation process is an interesting question that has
to be answered before man takes extended space flights,'' said
Bagian, a medical doctor who will observe the rats in orbit.
   The crew also will use a powerful IMAX camera to record damage
that man and nature are causing to planet Earth.
   ``From space, astronauts can see how fragile Earth really is,''
said Springer. ``We want to document it.''
   Among the things the camera will photograph, he said, are
volcanoes in Nicaragua and Indonesia, areas that have been
deforested in Brazil and Madagascar, the Sahara desert in Africa,
and beach erosion around the globe.
   Discovery's flight will be the third for a shuttle since the 1986
Challenger disaster, and Coats said, ``We're anxious to show that
we're back in the space business to stay on a routine basis.''
   He said the mission will be a good kickoff to a busy year in
which seven shuttle launches are planned, including the first two
that will dispatch probes to the planets _ Magellan to Venus in
April and Galileo to Jupiter in October.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
