<SECOND>AM-Courtroom Mural,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects Defense Request To Remove Wall Mural</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHELBYVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has rejected a request to cover
a courtroom mural of the biblical character King Solomon during the
trial of a man accused of killing a mother and her young daughter.
   The mural behind Shelby Circuit Court Judge Charles O'Conner's
bench depicts King Solomon's decision in the case of two women who
claimed to be the mother of the same infant.
   Solomon threatened to cut the baby in half and give part to each
woman before one asked him to spare the child and give him to the
other. Solomon then knew that the woman willing to give up the child
to save its life must be the real mother.
   The painting depicts a soldier ready to strike the infant with a
sword.
   Lawyer Michael McDaniel said the painting could bias the jury
against his client, James Kenneth Utley, charged in the death of
Karen Smith and her 3-year-old daughter, Jacqueline, in their New
Washington home in February.
   McDaniel also said Clark County Prosecutor Jerome Jacobi has a
habit of making Biblical references during trials. During a recent
murder trial, Jacobi referred to the story of Cain and Abel,
McDaniel said.
   The judge rejected McDaniel's motion Tuesday and instructed
Jacobi not to refer to the mural during the trial, which is to begin
Jan. 31.
   The case was venued to Shelby County because of publicity in
Clark County.
