<FIRST>r i AM-East-West     01-11 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East-West,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greek-Turkish Dispute Turned Over To Ministers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Greek-Turkish dispute that is blocking
accord on a date for new East-West arms talks has been turned over
to NATO foreign ministers who will try to break the deadlock,
diplomats said Wednesday.
   The diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a
solution was unlikely before Thursday, although meetings continued
in Vienna to try to break the impasse.
   The deadlock also threatened to hold up a landmark human rights
agreement by the 35-nation Helsinki review conference, whose final
document must include a mandate for new arms talks.
   Washington had insisted Wednesday as a deadline for agreement on
new East-West talks on reducing conventional forces and weapons
across Europe, said a source in another western delegation.
   Agreement on the arms talks has been stymied by a Greek-Turkish
dispute involving the eastern Mediterranean port of Mersin, which
Turkey wants excluded from the talks.
   The port is a main shipping point for supplies to northern
Cyprus, which is controlled by Turkey.
   The Soviet Union agreed to exclude the port, but Greece _
traditionally wary of Turkey and concerned about Cyprus _ is
insisting Mersin be included.
   Western diplomatic sources expressing frustration over the
impasse said they had turned the dispute over to unidentified NATO
foreign ministers for resolution.
   The talks are to encompass conventional weapons and troops across
Europe from the Atlantic to the Ural Mountains in the Soviet Union.
They will replace the Mutual and Balanced Force Reduction talks,
which began in Vienna in 1973 and continue without agreement.
   Meanwhile, Austria has invited the foreign ministers of the 34
other nations in the Helsinki review conference to Vienna next week
for ceremonies to close the conference, which began in November 1986.
   Austrian Foreign Minister Alois Mock said Wednesday he was
confident the ceremonies would go ahead as planned.
   But one diplomat said the arrangements hung ``on a fine thread.''
   The mandate for the new arms talks must be included in the final
document wrapping up the Helsinki conference. That document should
be ready by Friday if Mock's plans are to hold.
   If the conference is not wrapped up next week, there could be a
delay of several weeks while the Administration of President-elect
George Bush takes over, diplomats say.
   If that happens, nations unhappy with certain points of the
Helsinki draft accord might demand it be changed, diplomats fear.
   Romania already has objected to 17 key human rights provisions,
but has not said whether it would reject the document, which must be
approved by all 35 nations for passage.
   The United States, Canada, Soviet Union and all European nations
except Albania are taking part in the Helsinki review conference.
</TEXT>
