<FIRST>u w AM-US-Afghanistan     01-11 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Afghanistan,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Says Soviets Troop Withdrawal From Afghanistan Has
Resumed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Ap Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has resumed its troop
withdrawal from Afghanistan despite an impasse in negotiations with
U.S.-armed rebels over a future government in Kabul, the State
Department said Wednesday.
   Transports carried troops out of the country while other elements
of the Red Army streamed northward from the Soviet garrison in the
capital, spokesman Charles E. Redman said.
   The Soviets agreed last April to withdraw all forces by Feb. 15,
but declared a suspension in November to protest attacks by the
U.S.-backed rebels on departing units. About 50,000 troops remain in
the country.
   The United States had urged the Mujahadeen to hold their fire,
but the collapse last Saturday of negotiations between the Soviets
and the rebels on a government to succeed the pro-Moscow regime in
Kabul raised new obstacles.
   Returning to Moscow, Yuli Vorontsov, a first deputy foreign
minister who is also ambassador to Afghanistan, warned on Tuesday
that there was ``serious danger'' that the Soviets would not meet
the Feb. 15 deadline.
   He said whether the 50,000 troops could be withdrawn within five
weeks would depend on the Afghan guerrillas' willingness to accept a
cease-fire and on the outcome of negotiations to form a new
government.
   Most observers expect President Najibullah's regime to collapse
once it loses the backing of Soviet troops who helped wage a
nine-year war with the guerrillas.
   Reagan administration officials responded they still expected the
Soviets to meet their commitment. Some Western observers in Moscow
were quoted as seeing Vorontsov's warning as an attempt to pressure
the rebels into a political settlement.
   Even so, Redman said, ``We continue to see evidence that the
Soviets are in the process of preparing to withdraw.''
   He said ``these signs include the overland movement north of
Soviet troops from the Kabul garrison in recent days, and the
closure of the Soviet military hospital in Kabul.''
   Moreover, Redman said, ``we have noted an increase in flights by
Aeroflot transport aircraft into and out of the Kabul airport.''
   His statement apparently was based on Western intelligence
reports, and the U.S. official declined to provide further details.
</TEXT>
