<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 2003EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     01-11 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thailand Vows to Push Cambodian Peace Efforts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HANOI, Vietnam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thailand joined Vietnam on Wednesday in
pledging to press forward efforts to remove Vietnamese troops from
Cambodia.
   Foreign Minister Siddhi Savetsila of Thailand told a news
conference that he believes a settlement will be well in place by
September. Cambodia's pro-Hanoi government suggested last week that
Vietnamese troops could withdraw by then if Thailand denies
sanctuary to Cambodian guerrillas and countries, including Thailand,
halt aid to rebels.
   ``I think after September, everything will be all right,'' the
Thai foreign minister said Wednesday. ``The motion will be in full
spin.''
   Nguyen Co Thach, Vietnam's foreign minister, said Monday said
after Vietnamese-Thai talks that: ``Both sides are satisfied.
   ``Both sides have agreed it (the Cambodian conflict) will be
solved soon ... by September 1989 within the framework of a
political settlement,'' said Thach, also deputy premier.
   Vietnam has said it will pull out its forces by 1990 regardless
of a political settlement.
   President Heng Samrin of Cambodia said last week that 50,000
Vietnamese troops are in Cambodia, but Western intelligence
officials estimate the number at about 65,000. Guerrillas say
120,000 Vietnamese troops are in the country. Calling his meetings
with Vietnamese officials in Hanoi on Monday and Tuesday a ``turning
point'' in relations, Siddhi said Wednesday: ``We must now seek to
speed up the efforts to achieve a political settlement.''
   However, he denied Cambodian resistance groups were provided
refuge in his country, saying, ``We don't have any sanctuary in
Thailand. We have (refugee) camps.''
   Asked Thailand's position on Khmer Rouge leader Pol Pot, Siddhi
said: ``We do not count Pol Pot as a person to come back.... As for
the Khmer Rouge, we feel we will discuss it.'' He said the group
might be acceptable in a coalition government.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978 to oust the bloody Khmer
Rouge, during whose rule hundreds of thousands of Cambodians were
killed.
   The Khmer Rouge is the strongest member of a three-party
resistance coalition battling the Soviet-backed Vietnamese. China
and Thailand back the coalition, and the United States supports the
two non-communist groups in it.
   Siddhi, who is to visit China soon, said he wanted Beijing and
Moscow to join in peace talks on Cambodia.
   One round of informal talks was held in Indonesia last year among
the government of Cambodia, the guerrilla groups, Vietnam, Laos and
the countries of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations. That
group, which includes Thailand, is trying to arrange a second
meeting in Jakarta for February.
</TEXT>
