<DOCNO> AP890111-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 2026EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-StrategicForces     01-11 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Strategic Forces,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aspin Calls for Overall Strategic Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee on Wednesday proposed pooling money for such strategic
weapons as Star Wars and the MX missile to force the incoming Bush
administration and Congress to make tough spending decisions.
   Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., said that under his 10-year plan, funds
for the Strategic Defense Initiative, commonly known as Star Wars;
the Trident, MX and Midgetman missiles; and the B-52, B-1B and B-2
stealth bomber would be placed in a ``strategic pot.''
   The annual budget for the pot would remain constant at about $31
billion _ the total budget for the strategic programs in 1989 _ with
adjustments for inflation, Aspin said.
   The $31 billion budget would be available for all strategic
weapons, with none of it earmarked for any specific weapon, he said.
   The program would force Congress and the new administration to
decide what specific weapon systems in the pot should be purchased
and deployed and which should be delayed.
   ``It allows you to make those kind of rational tradeoffs and then
also to make the political tradeoffs,'' Aspin told a National Press
Club audience. ``The fact of the matter is you've got constituencies
for these weapon systems and you've got to finally decide what
you're going to do with them.''
   For example, Aspin mentioned continuing research and development
funding for the truck-mobile, single-warhead Midgetman missile,
which many Democrats in Congress favor but the Reagan administration
proposed scrapping.
   To compensate for moving forward on the Midgetman, Aspin
suggested slowing down stealth bomber purchases for two years and
limiting spending on Star Wars to its current annual level of $4
billion through 1996.
   Aspin also suggested retiring the Poseidon ballistic missile
submarines and the oldest B-52s and using the money saved on
operating costs for the two programs for earlier deployment of the
rail-mobile version of the MX intercontinental ballistic missile,
the stealth bomber, or Star Wars.
   The committee chairman said the time has come for ``Democrats and
Republicans, White House and Congress, to put all the weapon systems
into the pot, take a long, 10-year view, work the trade-offs and
build a strategic consensus.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890111-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 2153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-Quayle-Vacation     01-11 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle-Vacation,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>RNC Paid Part of Quayle's Vacation Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Republican National Committee agreed to
pick up part of the tab for Dan Quayle's Christmas vacation in Vail,
Colo., party officials said Wednesday. But such expenses as airfare,
lodging and food were paid by the vice president-elect and his
family, his spokesman said.
   The committee issued a statement saying it had agreed to pay up
to $25,000 to cover the cost of two aides and such logistical
matters as telephone lines and a four-wheel-drive vehicle for the
skiing vacation.
   Quayle's spokesman, David Beckwith, said that an aide to the vice
president-elect, acting without authorization, had asked the
committee before the trip to cover up to $65,000 of vacation costs,
including Quayle's personal expenses.
   But Beckwith said in an interview that Quayle had considered the
request ``totally out of line.''
   Subsequently, Beckwith said, Quayle had scaled back the vacation
_ eliminating a planned charter plane, scrubbing a stopover in
Tempe, Ariz., for the Jan. 2 Fiesta Bowl, reducing the size of his
entourage and paying all his own expenses.
   ``He never asked for a specific amount,'' the spokesman said.
``The RNC came up with $25,000.''
   At the White House, President-elect Bush said he wasn't troubled
by a newspaper report of the RNC expenditures. When all the facts
come out, said Bush, ``there'll be no hue and cry.''
   RNC Chairman Frank J. Fahrenkopf Jr. said in a statement that the
committee ``is glad it can help out the Republican vice
president-elect with what I and the budget committee consider to be
reasonable expenses.''
   The committee said in the statement that the relevant bills from
the skiing trip had not yet come in, but it was anticipated they
would total about $15,000.
   Fahrenkopf and the RNC budget committee on Dec. 15 authorized
payment of up to $25,000 in committee funds to help defray expenses
``incurred by the vice president-elect that he would not otherwise
incur as a private citizen between Dec. 15 and Jan. 20.''
   The Washington Post Wednesday quoted Fahrenkopf as calling the
original proposal ``a very large amount'' and ``not something I
thought we could do.''
   Bush, asked about the Post report, told reporters:
   ``It didn't trouble me. Wait until they get the facts and they'll
be very interesting. I think to take care of extra security
arrangements in a figure that's going to be 10 percent of the figure
that was originally stated in there _ let's wait until we get all
the facts and I think there'll be no hue and cry about that.''
   Former Vice President Walter F. Mondale recalled in an interview
that in 1976, after he was elected with Jimmy Carter, he spent a
week on vacation in the Virgin Islands.
   Mondale said that he and his wife, Joan, had paid their own
expenses, but that the tab for the one aide who accompanied them
probably had been paid out of the transition budget.
   ``No way I could have paid for it,'' said the former vice
president, who had little income outside his Senate salary in 1976.
   ``One thing I'm sure of, the Democratic National Committee never
gave me $25,000,'' he added, laughing about the impoverished state
of the DNC in those days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
