<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 2058EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Homeless     01-11 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Author Says Housing Riots May Be In America's Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The author of a book about life in a New York
City shelter said Wednesday that housing riots may be in America's
future if state and local governments don't start building
affordable homes instead of shelters.
   ``We're building the biggest permanent poorhouse in the world,''
author Jonathan Kozol said at a news conference to announce model
state legislation to alleviate homelessness.
   ``I don't know if the governors can act independently to reverse
the consequences of an 80 percent cut in federal housing funds,'' he
added. ``If they cannot, the shame of New York will soon be the
shame of a nation.''
   Kozol, author of ``Rachel and Her Children: Homeless Families in
America,'' said he has visited homeless shelters in 29 American
cities, including New York City's Martinique Hotel which is profiled
in the book.
   Kozol said he senses a growing militancy among homeless people,
who are beginning to organize politically.
   ``I think there's a tide of anger building up among homeless
people,'' he said.
   ``I'm afraid that we may soon see housing riots in this country.''
   Kozol praised a demonstration earlier this week by residents of
the Brooklyn Arms Hotel, another New York City homeless shelter. The
residents protested that they are to be moved into city housing
which they say is even worse than the hotel.
   New York City is slated to close its 46 homeless hotels this year
because if it doesn't, it will lose the federal money it has used to
pay the hotel bills. Last month, it closed the first _ the
Martinique, in midtown Manhattan.
   ``As New York City begins at last to renovate real housing,
however, the rest of the nation is moving in the opposite
direction,'' Kozol said. ``Instead of building housing, cities
everywhere are putting up more shelters.''
   He called homeless shelters ``the low-income housing of the
1980s,'' and complained that Cornell University's school of hotel
management is creating a course in shelter management, architects
are starting to design shelters and interior decorators are
suggesting how to furnish them.
   Maria Foscarinis, an attorney for the National Coalition for the
Homeless, presented model state legislation that her organization
has drafted to help solve the problem.
   ``Homelessness in America is a scandal, but it is not a
mystery,'' she said. ``Solutions exist; they must be implemented.''
   The model legislation proposes creating state affordable housing
trust funds to provide grants or loans to public or private entities
to develop low-income housing. It would also launch revolving funds
to provide rent or mortgage relief to people facing the loss of
their homes. The bill would provide emergency services to the
homeless, including temporary shelters, health care and job training.
   Funds for the projects would come from loan repayments and
penalties, as well as interest on real estate taxes in escrow
accounts; tenant security deposits; surtaxes on residential or
commercial sales; surcharges on building licenses and permits; the
sale of state or city property; real estate and hotel taxes; and
unclaimed property funds.
   The coalition honored Minnesota Gov. Rudy Perpich, who was at the
news conference, because his state has already created a housing
trust fund. Perpich said Minnesota has 31 programs to move the
homeless into transitional housing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
