<HEAD>Israeli Planes Attack Abu Nidal Group</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Israeli army saying one base
bombed, details, background. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes bombed the bases of
Palestinian terrorist Abu Nidal on Wednesday night in the first air
raid on Lebanon this year, police said.
   At least four fighter-bombers streaked in to bomb camps of the
Fatah-Revolutionary Council in Bkusta and Majdalyoun valley four
miles east of this southern port city, police said.
   They said the jets fired 24 rockets at the targets in three
sorties spaced over 10 minutes.
   No report of casualties was available. Police said ambulances
dispatched to the stricken bases from Sidon were turned back by Abu
Nidal's guerrillas, who told rescuers, ``We have no victims.''
   The same bases were targeted by the Israeli air force on March 23
and March 24, 1988. Police said 17 people, many of them guerrillas,
were killed and 20 wounded in both air strikes.
   In Jerusalem, the Israeli army said the planes bombed one base
north of the port of Sidon at 9 p.m. The army did not report if the
base was destroyed but added that all the aircraft returned safely.
   The army said the raid was aimed at pre-empting attacks on Israel.
   ``The terrorist target served as a base for launching and
organizing missions,'' an army spokesman said.
   The Fatah-Revolutionary Council has been blamed for numerous
attacks on Israel and western European countries.
   By police count, 128 people were killed and 356 wounded in 25
Israeli air attacks on Lebanon last year.
