<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 2105EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Bulgaria     01-11 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bulgaria,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bulgaria Halting Move Toward Free Enterprise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bulgaria is moving toward free enterprise
by allowing the formation of private firms and joint-stock
companies, but the state will retain partial control over prices and
production, according to a decree published Wednesday.
   The Bulgarian State Council decree published in the state-run
media lacked specifics on the extent of continuing government
interference in private and corporate management.
   Privately owned, small companies will be allowed to employ up to
10 people by labor contract, the decree said, according to a text
from the state news agency BTA.
   Under the decree, foreigners and foreign companies may operate in
Bulgaria with or without Bulgarian participation but require
separate government approval if their share in an enterprise exceeds
49 percent.
   Conversely, all Bulgarian companies _ state-owned or privately
owned _ will be allowed to carry out ``foreign economic activity''
independently, the decree said.
   This suggested they can search for their own export markets and
buy abroad if they have hard currency at their disposal.
   While ``the main form of economic activity is the company,'' the
decree stipulates that individual citizens and groups of citizens
may perform economic activity without registering companies, BTA
reported.
   But the decree also contained a number of provisions for
continued state control.
   ``The state regulates the economic activity through a system of
taxes, duties and subsidies, currency regulations, interest
percentages, regulations for labor payment ... regulations for price
formation and state orders,'' BTA quoted the decree as saying.
   Under the decree, the government also retains a key role in
setting wages.
   In addition, the decree stipulates that ``competent
authorities,'' along with the companies concerned, stipulate
fulfillment of the state production plan ``on the basis of mutual
agreements and state orders.''
   ``State orders'' have been used in the Soviet Union to continue
central control over the economy despite new measures that are
intended to give enterprises broad autonomy.
   Bureaucrats in central Soviet planning organs simply used ``state
orders'' as a replacement for centrally ordained planning targets
that have been abandoned.
</TEXT>
