<FIRST>u a AM-City-Nature Bjt   01-11 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-City-Nature, Bjt,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rare Plant Species to Be Protected in Parks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A variety of rare plants and animals are toughing
it out amid the urban jungle in New York City's parks, according to
a group fighting to protect the winged monkey flower, Smartweed
dodder and other prized species.
   ``I'm sure many people will be surprised to know that unique and
endangered wildlife occurs throughout New York City,'' said J.
Martin Carovano, New York director of the Nature Conservancy.
   The Nature Conservancy, an international, nonprofit, conservation
group, on Wednesday officially teamed up with the city's Parks
Department to find and record rare species.
   New York became the first city to join private landowners around
the nation who are working to preserve rare plants and animals on
their property with the help of the Nature Conservancy's Natural
Area Registry Program.
   ``These natural jewels _ the winged monkey flower, purple
milkweed and persimmon _ are rare and endangered species and endure
despite urban pressures, such as ozone and acid deposition,'' said
Marc Matsil, director of the Park Department's Natural Resources
Group.
   ``Registering these rare flora affirms our commitment to their
protection,'' Matsil said.
   From now on, the Parks Department will take special care of an
endangered moth, known only as Amphiboea erepta ryensis, found in a
wetlands meadow near a parking lot at Pelham Bay Park in the Bronx;
a rare grassland community at LaTourette Park on Staten Island,
which also boasts purple milkweed; and 19 other plant species in
parks around the city. A rare Smartweed dodder grows in Queens.
   Other protected areas include Alley Pond and Cunningham parks in
Queens; Blue Heron Pond Park in Staten Island; Van Cortlandt Parks
in the Bronx; and Inwood Park in upper Manhattan.
   The city might not always be able to save parks from development,
Matsil said. But affiliating with the Nature Conservancy provides
``a justification to protect (the land.)''
   ``We agree in this registry to monitor and protect these
species,'' Matsil said. ``It's a lot more difficult than you think.
The recreation constituency would just as soon fill in the wetlands
for a ball field.''
   The announcement was made as representatives from about 65
conservation groups planned strategies for promoting their cause.
   ``I think the city's physical environment and natural resources
are extraordinarily important _ they are priceless,'' said city
Parks Commissioner Henry Stern, who discussed the dangers of
development.
   ``I think the average lay person really does not understand how
environmental issues affect our lives on a daily basis,'' said U.S.
Rep. Floyd Flake, who told the conservationists he was a recent
convert to their cause.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890111-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1704EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SriLanka     01-11 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emergency Regulations Allowed To Lapse in Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emergency regulations that were in
force in ethnically divided Sri Lanka for over 5{ years, drawing
fire from world human rights activists, lapsed at midnight Wednesday
by presidential proclamation.
   A communique issued by the Ministry of Information said, ``The
state of emergency in force for well over five years, has been
revoked with effect from midnight today (1:30 p.m. EST).''
   The emergency gave police and security forces the right to arrest
and detain people for long periods, to dispose of bodies without
inquests, to search homes without warrants and to override regular
criminal laws.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa, who took office on Jan. 2, had
promised to lift the emergency in an effort to chart a new and more
peaceful course for this Indian Ocean island nation, wracked by
ethnic violence since 1983.
   A military official, however, said security forces still will
have power to arrest and detain suspects without charge and to
search houses without warrants under an anti-terrorism law adopted
four years before the emergency. The official cannot be identified
under briefing rules.
   Amnesty International, the London-based human rights group, last
year issued a report alleging abuse and use of torture by Sri Lankan
security forces. The report, which included photographs of men with
badly burned bodies, contained affidavits by people who said they
were detained or experienced or witnessed torture by members of the
security forces.
   The state of emergency was extended every month since May 1983.
Premadasa vowed it would not be renewed on its next expiration date,
Jan. 15.
   On Wednesday, he told his Cabinet the emergency would be lifted
three days early, according to Information Minister and Cabinet
spokesman Festus Perera.
   Perera said the president wanted the emergency lifted quickly so
political prisoners held without charge could be freed. At least
1,800 political prisoners are still detained.
   About the time the presidential announcement was made, a small
bomb exploded in a market in the center of Colombo, injuring two
people. Police said they did not know if the bombing was related to
Sri Lanka's ethnic or political strife or stemmed from a private
dispute.
   Sri Lanka, once famed only for idyllic beaches and glittering
gemstones, exploded into ever-spiraling violence in 1983 as members
of the Tamil minority launched a separatist movement against the
Sinhalese majority.
   Since then, more than 8,500 people, mostly Sinhalese civilians,
have died in massacres, ambushes and guerrilla battles. The dead
include more than 600 Indian soldiers, part of a peacekeeping force
sent to Sri Lanka in July 1987 to try to disarm Tamil insurgents.
   In addition, more than 650 government supporters, mostly
Sinhalese, were killed by Sinhalese extremists who opposed former
President Junius R. Jayewardene's efforts to make peace with the
Tamils by granting them limited autonomy in the northern and eastern
provinces.
   Tamils, mostly Hindu, comprise about 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16
million population. They say they are discriminated against by the
Buddhist Sinhalese majority.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890111-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 2105EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-SovietJews     01-11 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Soviet Jews ,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Up To 10,000 Soviet Jews Visit Isreal In 1988 Under Glasnost</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Up to 10,000 Soviet Jews were allowed to visit
relatives in Israel last year in a wave inspired by Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev's policy of more openness, a Jewish representative
said Wednesday.
   Arrivals began last spring and ``in 1988 we figure there were
between 8,000 and 10,000 who visited,'' said Rabbi Richard Hirsch,
executive director of the World Union for Progressive Judaism, a
private lobby.
   He said even more Soviet Jews could visit this year. ``We
consider this a harbinger of better times,'' said Hirsch, who
stopped in Geneva during a trip to meet with Swiss Jewish leaders.
   The Soviets, many of whom travel on plane tickets paid for by
relatives in Israel, have tourist visas and stay one to three
months, he said.
   In Israel, the Jewish Agency, a private group, has been
organizing tours of the country once the Soviets arrive in hopes
that showing Israel in a good light will promote more Russian
emigration to the Jewish state.
   Of the 20,082 Soviet Jews allowed to emigrate last year, only 7
percent chose to resettle in Israel, according to the Geneva-based
Intergovernmental Committee for Migration. The overall figure was
the highest since 1980.
   Hirsch said he expects emigration to rise to 30,000 to 40,000
this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
