<FIRST>r a AM-MomRobbery     01-11 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mom Robbery,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Infant Sleeps in Mom's Getaway Car, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZION, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 5-month-old boy slept through the ride of his
life in the back seat of his teen-age mother's getaway car after she
robbed a bank at gunpoint to help pay family bills, authorities said
Wednesday.
   Short on cash and hard up for a baby sitter, police said Tammy L.
Richberg, 19, left young Shawn Maximillian Richberg in the car
Tuesday as she held up the First of America Bank in Zion for the
second time in two months, police said.
   Mrs. Richberg entered the bank, wielded an automatic Luger-type
BB gun, and told a teller to open the vault, where she stuffed
$32,000 into a shopping bag, police said.
   She escaped out a side door just as police, responding to a
silent alarm, entered the front door.
   Then, with the baby in a carseat sleeping in the back seat, she
led police on a chase at speeds up to 65 mph, tossing the gun and
handfuls of $50 bills ``flying like confetti'' out the car window,
said Lt. Ralph Connard of the Lake County Sheriff's Police.
   She finally smashed into a squad car at a roadblock. The toddler
was uninjured and police recovered all $32,000.
   Police in the three cars that gave chase had no idea an infant
was in the back seat, Lt. Chester Iwan said.
   ``Lo and behold, after everything was done, we find the baby,''
Iwan said.
   Mrs. Richberg was in Lake County Jail Wednesday in lieu of $1
million bond, charged with two counts of armed violence and two
counts of armed robbery, police said. A preliminary hearing is
scheduled for Jan. 23.
   The baby was handed over to juvenile authorities after the chase,
but was later returned to his distraught father.
   ``It was a very terrible day,'' said Shawn Richberg, 20, a Navy
seaman apprentice who lives in this city about 45 miles north of
Chicago. ``I'm worried and lost and just don't know where to start
or what to do.''
   Mrs. Richberg told police she robbed the same bank of $10,000 on
Dec. 1 to pay credit card bills, Connard said. Police said she also
had been charged with a felony theft in November because of
allegations of stealing from her former employer.
   Richberg said he didn't know about the Dec. 1 bank robbery or the
charges against his wife in November until authorities told him. And
he said he and his wife had no unusual financial problems.
   ``We were in the same situation as just about everybody else,''
he said.
</TEXT>
