<FIRST>u w AM-Mediterranean-Navy 550   01-11 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mediterranean-Navy, 550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Ships Move Away From Libya</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will rotate two aircraft
carrier battle groups well away from Libya and also has canceled
plans for a missile-firing exercise in the nearby central
Mediterranean Sea, defense sources said Wednesday.
   ``There's no sense being accused of baiting the rattlesnake,''
said one official, referring to the enigmatic Libyan strongman, Col.
Moammar Gadhafi.
   The moves were described within the Pentagon as trying to lower
tensions between the United States and Libya, a week after two Navy
jets shot down two Libyan MiG-23's. Tensions between the two
countries already were high after Washington threatened to attack an
alleged chemical weapons factory near Tripoli.
   The United States has said the two F-14 fighters were far away
from Libya and acted in self-defense when they were approached by
the MiG's over the Mediterranean in a ``hostile manner.''
   The defense officials, who declined to be identified, said
Wednesday the Navy battle group led by the carrier USS John F.
Kennedy _ from which the F-14's flew _ would complete its six-month
deployment and be replaced by the carrier Theodore Roosevelt
starting late this week in the Tyrrhenian Sea _ off the west coast
of Italy.
   The Roosevelt battle group passed through the Strait of Gibraltar
and entered the Mediterranean on Wednesday.
   The sources said it was routine for two carrier groups to operate
together during a brief overlap period to accomplish a rotation
``and nothing will be different here.''
   ``We will have two battle groups together for two or three days,
starting around Saturday in the Tyrrhenian Sea,'' said one Navy
official. ``And they will perform joint operations there.
   ``Then the Kennedy heads west and home and the Teddy Roosevelt
east on patrol and routine operations.''
   The sources said there had been one change in plans, however,
involving the two carriers.
   After the rotation, the Navy had planned a routine missile-firing
exercise in the central Mediterranean, north of Libya, on Jan. 16
and 17, the sources explained.
   As a routine precaution, the Navy had issued a ``Notice to
Airman'' and filed it with air traffic controllers in Tripoli, who
have responsibility for that so-called Flight Information Region.
   On Tuesday, Libya's ambassador to the U.N., Ali A. Treiki,
disclosed the plns and branded them provocative.
   Wednesday, Herbert S. Okun, the second-ranking U.S. ambassador,
told reporters the ``Notice to Airman'' had been cancelled. Another
U.S. Mission officer, John Kriendler, added the whole maneuver had
been called off.
   Neither man elaborated on when the exercise had been canceled, or
the reason for the change in plans.
   ``But it would seem logical that we're trying to ease the
tensions a bit,'' observed one Pentagon official. ``It's not our
intention to press things with Libya right now.''
   The sources said the missile-firing exercise was to have involved
some routine practice with surface-to-air missiles and not any
air-to-ground missiles of the type that would be used in any attack
on Libya.
   ``Our (carrier) rotation is not going to threaten Libya and now
we've canceled the exercise,'' added one source. ``If anything else
is going to happen out there, it will be because Gadhafi once again
started it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
