<FIRST>r p AM-LAMayor     01-11 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LA Mayor,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bradley Files for Fifth Term as LA Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Tom Bradley launched his campaign for an
unprecedented fifth term Wednesday, the first candidate to file in a
field that was thinned by the unexpected withdrawal of his strongest
potential challenger.
   The 71-year-old Democrat was first in line when the city clerk's
office opened Wednesday, the first day candidates could declare
their intent to run in the April 11 election.
   ``I'm looking forward to a very active campaign. I won't overlook
anyone or anything in the city,'' Bradley promised. ``Anyone else
who gets in this race faces an uphill battle.''
   Councilman Zev Yaroslavsky, a liberal Democrat who blames Bradley
for allowing overly rapid growth in the nation's second-largest
city, planned to challenge him in the non-partisan race. But
Yaroslavsky unexpectedly took himself out of contention Thursday.
   Citing a poll and the advice of friends, Yaroslavsky said Bradley
has such a rapport with the public that voters don't blame him for
gang violence, traffic, smog and other problems plaguing Los Angeles.
   Another Democratic councilman, Nate Holden, said this week he was
considering a bid if he can raise $400,000 in contributions by noon
Saturday, the close of the filing period. He said he has already
raised $75,000. Bradley has $2 million in his campaign chest.
   Holden alleged that Bradley, who is black, has broken faith with
the black voters who, in alliance with wealthier Jewish voters, form
the core of his support. Holden called the race ``winnable.''
   Bradley, a former police lieutenant and City Council member, won
his first four-year term as mayor in 1973 but has been unable to
project his popularity statewide. He twice ran for governor, losing
to George Deukmejian in 1982 and 1986.
   Joel Britton, who identified himself as a process operator for
Chevron oil, also filed for the mayor's race Wednesday. He said he
was running because more attention needs to be paid to business
interests. Britton did not identify his political party.
</TEXT>
