<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 2109EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Contras     01-11 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Contras,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contras Announce Peace Proposal With More Flexible Compliance Calender</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the Nicaraguan Contras, boasting a
revised peace proposal and a more flexible attitude, urged the
Sandinistas on Wednesday to begin another round of peace talks.
   The Nicaraguan Resistance, an umbrella group of the rebels, has
proposed opening negotiations with the Sandinistas on Jan. 25 or
some other date agreed upon in Washington.
   But so far there has been no official response from the
Nicaraguan government, according to Adolfo Calero, a director of the
Resistance.
   ``We are being more flexible in this new position,'' Calero said
Wednesday in a news conference at the group's Miami headquarters.
   A major element of the Contras' revised position is to extend the
deadline for compliance by the Sandinistas from 70 days to 120 days,
culminating in the rebels giving up their arms and being
reintegrated into the political and social fabric of Nicaragua.
   ``The Sandinistas have made promise after promise and never
comply,'' said another Contra leader, Wilfredo Montalvan. ``If the
Sandinistas maintain their intransigence, the world will take notice
that they have no desire to implement democratization and we would
have no choice but to seek more military aid.''
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega announced in his year-end
speech in Managua that he would unilaterally extend a cease-fire for
another month and that Nicaragua was ready to ``look for ways to
coexist with the enemies of the revolution.'' But he rejected peace
talks with the Contras.
   Although both sides agreed in March to end offensive operations,
there has been no progress to resolve the 7-year-old conflict.
Thousands of rebels remain at bases along the Honduran border with
Nicaragua.
   Calero said the latest Contra proposal will be sent to Central
American presidents and foreign ministers, who can perhaps pressure
the Sandinistas to agree to peace talks with the rebels.
   Another element of the Contra proposal was to seek an independent
judiciary, with professionals to be ``named in accordance to their
capacity,'' rather than demand the outright removal of current
Supreme Court justices, Calero said. Calero did not elaborate
further on the revised proposal, nor was a copy of it provided to
reporters.
   The Nicaraguan Resistance also denounced the assassination last
week of Commander ``Aureliano,'' a guerrilla physician killed last
week on the outskirts of Tegucigalpa, Honduras.
   ``It's nothing but another step of the Sandinista plan to
decimate the political and military direction of the Resistance,''
Calero said.
   Calero said the killing of the doctor, Adan Rugama Acevedo, was
not an isolated incident. He referred to other incidents, including
the murder two weeks ago of a guard at the home of Contra leader
Enrique Bermudez in Tegucigalpa, the attempted murder of Commander
``Douglas'' last November and a recent bombing at the home of
another anti-Sandinista.
   Montalvan said the rebels are encouraged by the election of
Carlos Andres Perez as president of Venezuela. He said Resistance
director Alfredo Cesar left Tuesday to meet with Perez for
discussions about the future of Nicaragua.
   Asked about the flood of Nicaraguan refugees entering the United
States, with some 100,000 to 125,000 in the Miami area, Calero said
the Resistance has asked U.S. officials to treat the refugees
humanely and not deport them.
</TEXT>
