<FIRST>r p AM-DemocraticChairman     01-11 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democratic Chairman,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brown Wins Labor Backing In DNC Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AFL-CIO on Wednesday endorsed Washington
attorney Ronald H. Brown to succeed Paul G. Kirk Jr. as chairman of
the Democratic National Committee despite public support by building
trades unions for another candidate.
   The nation's largest labor organization announced the endorsement
in two-sentence statement issued after a 90-minute meeting between
AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland and the 16 other members of its
national political committee.
   The statement said the AFL-CIO ``will be urging members of the
DNC to vote for Brown.'' It did not say why he was selected.
   Of the 404 votes on the DNC, 46 are cast by union
representatives. But labor's influence is considered far greater
than those numbers suggest. All five candidates to succeed Kirk met
with labor leaders last week in hopes of securing the endorsement.
   Brown and Richard Weiner, the Michigan state party chairman, are
viewed as the front-runners to replace Kirk. Brown has the support
of many national Democrats but few if any of them vote and Weiner is
believed to have a considerable base among state party chairmen
because he heads their organization.
   The other candidates are former Reps. Jim Jones of Oklahoma,
Michael Barnes of Maryland and James V. Stanton of Ohio.
   All five last week began a series of joint regional meetings
around the country.
   The DNC will pick a successor to Kirk next month.
   The AFL-CIO statement said the Brown endorsement resulted from a
``consensus'' reached during Wednesday's meeting. The organization
generally uses the word ``unanimous'' to describe its endorsements
but building trades unions affilated with AFL-CIO have previously
made public endorsements of Stanton.
   Brown is a longtime party activist who most recently advised the
unsuccessful presidential campaign of Massachusetts Gov. Michael S.
Dukakis.
   Critics of his candidacy argue that his election would signal the
party is lining up behind the liberal stands of Jesse Jackson. Brown
was a top Jackson adviser before joining the Dukakis campaign.
</TEXT>
