<FIRST>r w AM-Honduras-Contras 1stLd-Writethru a0607 01-11 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras-Contras, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0607,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honduran President Asks Nicaragua to Set Up Free System</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Inserts 3 grafs with Contra proposal after 12th graf pvs, At
present,</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduran President Jose Azcona called on the
Nicaraguan government Wednesday to create conditions for the return
of the thousands of Contra rebels who are camped inside Honduran
territory.
   If the Sandinista government establishes a free system, the
Contras will be able to return and ``fight in the political arena
and not in the purely military arena,'' Azcona told a news
conference.
   Azcona ended a two-day visit here in which he paid a farewell
call on President Reagan and also met with President-elect Bush and
Secretary of State-designate James Baker III.
   Azcona gave few clues as to the course Bush expects to follow on
Central America after his inauguration. He said he asked Bush to
find a solution to the Contra problem ``as quickly as possible.''
   But, he said, the principal responsibility for the return of the
Contras to Nicaragua rests with the Sandinista government.
   Asked whether Bush outlined his views on renewed aid to the
Contras, Azcona said that issue received only peripheral treatment
in their discussion. No military aid has been sent to the rebels
since a congressional aid cutoff went into effect last February.
   In his public statements, Bush has been non-committal on the
policy he will follow on Central America.
   He has yet to name his selection for assistant secretary of state
for Latin America, considered one of the State Department's most
difficult jobs because of the continuing turmoil in Central America
and the foreign debt crisis that afflicts many hemispheric countries.
   One contender for the post is Robert Helander, a New York lawyer
with long experience in South America, including business
connections with the Rockefeller family.
   According to State Department officials, congressional staff
members with whom Helander has spoken in recent days have made it
clear they hope Bush will choose someone else from among the long
list of candidates for the post.
   As of late last week, transition team officials said no decision
had been made. The outgoing assistant secretary, Elliott Abrams,
plans to accept a temporary assignment after Jan. 20 with the
Heritage Foundation, a conservative research group.
   At present, there is a stalemate in Central America, with
U.S.-donated food and other humanitarian assistance sustaining the
thousands of rebels and their families who fled Nicaragua to camps
in the border area last year after an interim cease-fire was signed
between the Sandinistas and the Contras.
   In Miami on Wednesday, Contra leaders unveiled a revised
settlement plan and called on the Sandinista government to resume
peace talks, which have been suspended for seven months.
   A major element of the revised position is to extend the deadline
for compliance by the Sandinistas from 70 days to 120 days,
culminating in the rebels giving up their arms and being
reintegrated into the political and social fabric of Nicaragua.
   ``We are being more flexible in this new position,'' Contra
leader Adolfo Calero said at a news conference.
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega has said his government is
prepared to look for ways ``to coexist with enemies of the
revolution'' but rejected new talks with the Contras.
   Honduran officials have been concerned that unless the refugee
issue is resolved, the Contras and their families, with no other
place to go, may be forced to settle permanently in Honduras,
contributing to the country's already severe social and economic
problems.
   According to some estimates, there are about 10,000 rebels in the
border area, along with 15,000 family members.
   There has been little visible international support for a
Honduran call last fall for the formation of an international force
to evict the rebels from Honduras.
</TEXT>
