<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0624 01-11 0763</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0624,0789</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amal Braces For Big Push Against Hezbollah</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with Israeli raid on Abu Nidal
group bases, Amal claiming to capture Hezbollah arsenal. Pickup 10th graf
`Amal on...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KFAR FILLA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem militias battled
with artillery and rockets in the southern mountains Wednesday, and
pro-Syrian fighters massed for an assault on fundamentalists in a
strategic stronghold.
   Also Wednesday, Israeli jets bombed bases of the
Fatah-Revolutionary Council, the radical Moslem group led by Abu
Nidal, in the outskirts of the southern port city of Sidon, police
said.
   As fighting between mainstream Amal militiamen and their cornered
Iranian-backed enemies raged for the fourth day, police reported 12
Amal fighters were killed in abortive overnight attacks on Jbaa.
   The village, 10 miles southeast of Sidon, is the key to a
triangular bastion where 500 Hezbollah fighters are under siege just
northwest of Israel's self-proclaimed security zone.
   ``We'll attack again and again until we uproot those traitors
from Jbaa and the rest of south Lebanon,'' said an Amal commander in
the hamlet of Kfar Filla, who gave only his nom de guerre of Abu Ali.
   It will be no easy victory, he said.
   ``Jbaa is like an eagle's nest. It's difficult to climb the
slopes to reach it and push the Hezbollahis out.''
   An Amal communique said its militiamen seized an underground
Hezbollah arms depot in the village of Ma'roub, 13 miles east of the
southern port of Tyre.
   The communique said 350 Soviet-designed grad rockets, 150 AK-47
assault rifles and two million rounds of ammunition were confiscated.
   Police in Tyre said they could not confirm the claim.
   Police reported eight people wounded have died in the hospital,
raising the casualty toll since Sunday to 107 killed and more than
220 wounded.
   It is the fourth major confrontation between Shiite factions
since April, when rivalry to dominate Lebanon's 1 million Shiites
exploded into warfare. Some 500 people have been killed and 1,500
wounded since then.
   There were no immediate reports of injuries from the Israeli air
raid, the first this year. Police said Abu Nidal's guerrillas turned
away ambulances, saying they had no casualties.
   A police spokesman said 1,000 Amal fighters were regrouping with
their Syrian-supplied T-54 battle tanks, multibarreled rocket
launchers and howitzers for a major three-pronged offensive
Wednesday. Hezbollah repulsed four overnight assaults on Jbaa, said
the spokesman, who cannot be named under standing regulations.
   Amal on Monday cut Hezbollah's supply lines to its
nine-square-mile stronghold, which stretches southeast from Jbaa to
nearby hamlets of Ein Bouswar and Louwaizeh and the wooded slopes of
Mount Safi. At the same time, they recaptured four of five villages
taken by Hezbollah in fighting that police described as ``horrific.''
   They say both sides have committed terrible atrocities, with
Hezbollah fighters hacking off heads and limbs of captured Amal men.
   Shiite housewife Zainab Khater choked back tears Wednesday as she
described watching Hezbollah fighters kill a teacher on Sunday in
Kfar Filla, 1 mile west of Jbaa.
   ``They shot one of the students in the legs and when the teacher
rushed to help him, a Hezbollahi chopped off the teacher's head with
a cutlass,'' she cried.
   Abu Ali said the fighting has changed the future for Shiites.
   ``Life will neve be as it used to be,'' he told reporters. ``The
Hezbollahis and us used to live together in the same villages before
this broke out. We'll never be able to coexist.''
   Hezbollah seeks to create an Iranian-style Islamic republic in
Lebanon. The more secular Amal prefers a multisect government with
Moslems and Christians sharing power.
   The southern fighting raged despite efforts by Syrian President
Hafez Assad and Iran's first deputy foreign minister, Ali Mohammad
Besharati, who met Tuesday to discuss how to end the bloodshed.
   Beirut's pro-Syrian Ash-Sharq daily said they agreed to continue
their efforts.
   An Iranian Embassy source in the Syrian capital, Damascus, said
Assad had asserted a cease-fire could be achieved only by
coordination between Syria and Iran.
   He denied reports that Besharati was going to Beirut to mediate,
a suggestion Amal has rejected.
   Amal drove Hezbollah out of most of the south in a four-day
battle in April. A month later, Hezbollah ousted Amal from most of
south Beirut in a three-week war.
   Syria deployed troops in south Beirut to quell the fighting. But
violence erupted again in November.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, maintains about 40,000
troops in eastern and northern provinces as well as Moslem sectors
of Beirut.
</TEXT>
