<HEAD>Bush Staff Jobs Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roger B. Porter, a Harvard University professor
and former presidential aide, was named George Bush's chief domestic
policy adviser on Wednesday.
   Porter, 42, was a White House adviser in President Reagan's first
term and also worked as an assistant to former President Ford. He is
currently a professor of business and government at Harvard.
   He was among a group of new White House staff selections
announced by Bush's incoming chief of staff, John Sununu.
   Other announcements included:
   _ Stephen M. Studdert, a former Bush campaign aide who now is
director of Bush's inaugural committee, as assistant to the
president for special activities and initiatives.
   _ Richard Breeden, a Washington lawyer and former vice
presidential aide, as assistant for issues analysis.
   _ John P. Schmitz as deputy counsel, the same job he has held in
Bush's vice presidential office.
   _ B. Jay Cooper, Stephen Hart and Alixe Reed Glen, as deputy
press secretaries. Cooper is currently a deputy press secretary in
the Reagan White House, while Hart is Bush's vice presidential
spokesman and Ms. Glen serves in a similar capacity in Bush's
transition office.
