<DOCNO> AP890111-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 2251EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HomeEquityLoans     01-11 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Home Equity Loans,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Proposed Tightening Disclosure Requirements</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve Board on Wednesday proposed
new rules requiring lenders to provide home equity loan borrowers
with more information about the cost of such loans.
   In general, lenders would have to provide potential borrowers
with a written explanation of the terms and conditions of the loan
at the time of loan application and before any non-refundable fee is
collected.
   For applications taken over the telephone, lenders would have
three days to supply the required information.
   The disclosures must include a full explanation of how the
interest rate and monthly payments might change and the
circumstances under which immediate repayment of the loan could be
demanded.
   Congress has prohibited lenders from unilaterally changing the
terms of the loan after it has been taken out. The Federal Reserve
is proposing to allow changes, such as providing a lower monthly
payment over a longer term, provided the borrower agrees to the
changes in writing.
   Lenders offering variable-rate loans would be forbidden to base
the rate on an index that is under their control, such as the bank's
own prime rate. The Fed said about 26 percent of home equity lenders
would be affected by this provision.
   The board is allowing 60 days for public comment on the rules,
which are required by legislation that Congress enacted in November.
The Fed had been working on a rule since December 1987, but held off
on enacting it while Congress debated the legislation.
   Home equity loans have mushroomed in popularity since passage of
the 1986 tax act, which phased out the deductibility of interest on
most consumer loans, except loans secured by homes.
   According to the Federal Reserve staff, about 5.7 percent of all
homeowners, roughly 3.3 million families, have home equity loan
accounts totaling more than $50 billion.
   The staff said consumers have used the loans conservatively. It
said about 0.75 percent of the borrowers were behind in their
payments, compared with a delinquency rate three to four times
higher for other kinds of consumer borrowing, such as auto loans,
credit cards and personal loans.
   Consumer advocates have been wary of the loans, even though they
often have lower rates, because borrowers can lose their homes if
they can't repay.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
