<DOCNO> AP890111-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1757EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-MIARepatriation 430   01-11 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MIA Repatriation, 430</SECOND>
<HEAD>More MIA Remains Being Returned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vietnamese government has told the United
States it will return the suspected remains of 25 Americans killed
in the Vietnam War and also let five U.S. teams of experts in the
country for a search mission, the Pentagon said Wednesday.
   The repatriation of the 25 remains will occur Jan. 23, with an
American cargo plane flying to Hanoi and transporting the remains to
the U.S. Army's Central Identification Laboratory in Honolulu,
Hawaii, the Pentagon said.
   Prior to that, starting Jan. 14, ``five teams of U.S. technical
experts will arrive in Hanoi to work with Vietnamese counterparts
during the fourth 10-day joint mission to investigate and survey
incidents involving Americans missing in Vietnam,'' the Pentagon
said.
   ``The U.S. government is pleased that Vietnam has agreed'' to
allow five American teams in the country instead of the four teams
allowed on previous missions, the Pentagon added.
   ``The U.S. delegation will be composed of two investigation
teams, two excavation teams and a forensic team. They will be joined
by counterparts from the Vietnamese Office for Seeking Missing
Persons.''
   The announcement of the repatriation comes less than a month
after Vietnam transferred the largest single group of remains ever
to the United States since the war's end _ 38 individuals.
   The largest previous repatriation, which occurred in April 1988,
totaled 27 individuals.
   Currently, 2,383 Americans continue to be listed as missing in
Indochina as a result of the Vietnam War, of whom 1,747 are listed
as missing in either North or South Vietnam.
   All told, the remains of 172 Americans have been repatriated to
the United States from Vietnam and subsequently identified by the
Army lab since the end of the war.
   The Pentagon, in its statement Wednesday, noted the upcoming
repatriation would be the eighth since a special presidential
mission was undertaken by retired Gen. John Vessey. The retired Army
general went to Vietnam at President Reagan's request in August 1987
with orders to seek greater cooperation with the Vietnamese in
resolving the cases of missing Americans.
   ``The U.S. government appreciates the initiative taken by Vietnam
to repatriate these remains and hopes to continue the increasing
joint cooperation to resolve this long-standing humanitarian
issue,'' the Pentagon said.
   In the past, remains repatriated by Vietnam have occasionally
included those of Vietnamese individuals. As a result, the Pentagon
routinely declines to predict whether all repatriated remains can be
individually identified by the Army laboratory in Honolulu.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
