<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Palestine     01-11 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Palestine,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Wins Symbolic Recognition As Palestine Before Security Council</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PLO won a diplomatic victory Wednesday
when the Security Council granted it the right to speak directly to
the council as ``Palestine,'' on the same basis as any U.N. member
nation.
   The United States was the only nation to vote against the move.
Britain, Canada and France abstained, while the Soviet Union, China,
Finland, Brazil, Colombia, Malaysia, Algeria, Ethiopia, Nepal,
Senegal and Yugoslavia voted in favor.
   In the past, the Palestine Liberation Organization had to ask
another nation to sponsor its right to speak to the council.
Organizations must be invited to speak; member states may directly
ask to address the council.
   The Palestinian delegates will be addressed as ``Palestine,'' as
they are in the General Assembly, rather than under their former
title as the observer mission of the PLO.
   The PLO's diplomatic victory came as it pursued the right to
speak before the council on the U.S. Navy's downing of two Libyan
military planes last week.
   Acceptance of the PLO's bid to address the council directly as
``Palestine'' gave symbolic weight to its claim to represent a
nation, but not formal recognition. The Security Council would have
to vote to formally admit Palestine as a member state.
   ``The United States, consequently, opposes extending to the PLO
the same rights to participate in the proceedings of the Security
Council as if that organization represented a member state of the
United Nations,'' said Herbert S. Okun, the second-ranking U.S.
ambassador.
   The Palestine National Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile,
proclaimed an independent Palestinian state in November. The PLO
says more than 90 countries have recognized that state.
   The parliament did not specify the boundaries of the state, but
it roughly encompasses the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip
with Jerusalem as its declared capital.
   In December, the General Assembly passed a resolution elevating
the PLO's status as an organization with observer status to become
the Palestine Observer Mission, a non-voting member.
   The United States and Israel voted against the resolution, and 44
nations abstained, including the rest of the Western bloc.
   The elevation in status put ``Palestine'' in a class with the
Vatican, North Korea, South Korea, Monaco, San Marino and
Switzerland as non-member states with permanent observer missions.
   Western nations contended that the state proclaimed by the PLO
lacks the normal attributes of a nation, such as a functioning
goverment in control of territory and a population within defined
borders.
   One of the General Assembly's committees also voted in December
to let the PLO address the General Assembly directly instead of
through intermediaries, the right which it now seeks from the
Security Council.
   On simple procedural matters such as on the PLO's right to speak,
the five permanent Security Council members _ the United States,
Soviet Union, Britain, France and China _ do not have veto power.
They can veto substantial political resolutions. The other members
are non-permanent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
