<FIRST>u a AM-ArsonArrest 1stLd-Writethru a0664 01-11 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arson Arrest, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0664,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Charged In Fatal Fire, `Tells Us He Needs a Lot of Help'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `O'Meara said ..., with 3 grafs to ADD police
denial that Marts called fire victims; picks up 10th graf: `Marts, one
...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 21-year-old man who kept showing up at the scene
of fires and offering information about them to authorities has been
charged with setting four blazes, including one that killed four
people, authorities said.
   Buddy W. Marts, 21, may have started 25 or more fires, police
said.
   Marts was arrested Tuesday and charged with arson and murder in
the Aug. 31 fatal fire that also left 31 people homeless, and with
setting three other fires, police said.
   ``He was basically a pyromaniac. He enjoyed fires. He said he set
them to keep warm. But it was August; how cold can it be?''
Detective William Barker said Wednesday.
   The arrest has led authorities to reassess charges against
another young man who was indicted in one of the non-fatal blazes on
the basis of information provided by Marts.
   On Wednesday, Circuit Judge Michael Bolan ordered Marts held
without bail and set Jan. 25 as the next court date in the case,
said spokeswoman Lisa Howard of the Cook County state's attorney's
office.
   Detectives in the Police Department's Bomb and Arson Unit had
come to know Marts when he started offering bits of information
about fires in his neighborhood.
   ``There was something familiar about the fires,'' Detective Tim
O'Meara said. ``He was at a lot of them. His name kept popping up
too many times.''
   O'Meara said Marts admitted setting the fatal fire, and ``tells
us he needs a lot of help.''
   Earlier police reported that Marts often would call the fire
department or people in the building to alert them to blazes he set.
But Detective Wayne Micek, who investigated the case, said that
wasn't so.
   ``I've never seen anybody that perfectly fits the definition of a
pyromania,'' Micek said. ``But he was never hospitalized for mental
illness and wasn't on any medication.''
   Marts, one of nine children, worked at odd jobs near where he was
staying lately with relatives, said Barker. ``He was what we call a
bustout,'' he added. ``He lived where he could until he outstayed
his welcome.''
   Marts provided information on a non-fatal fire that led to the
Nov. 29 indictment of Michael J. Gillon, 21. But last week, police
began to suspect Marts knew too much to be only a witness.
   Authorities are reassessing the charges against Gillon, said Ms.
Howard. He has been free on bond.
   Marts' motive was simply ``rash, angry expression,'' said Chief
of Detectives Edward Wodnicki. ``When he'd have a fight with
someone, he'd vent his frustration by setting fires.''
   The fires were started by lighting piles of trash and many were
small blazes confined to the garbage, O'Meara said. ``If he would
see a pile of garbage in an alley, something would tell him to set
it on fire,'' O'Meara said.
   The fatal fire was in a three-story building that contained
stores and apartments. According to O'Meara, Marts said he didn't
know anyone in the building when he set fire to packing materials on
the first floor.
   Marts was charged with four counts of first-degree murder in the
deaths of Kum Yi, 60; her son, Hong Yi, 30; Jack Kaufman, 84; and
Young Suk Kim, 31. Nine people were injured and 31 left homeless by
the August fire.
   Marts also was charged with arson in three other fires that
damaged property but caused no injuries. He had previous arrests on
charges criminal damage to property and criminal trespass, police
said.
</TEXT>
