<FIRST>r i AM-Iraq-Chemicals     01-11 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iraq-Chemicals,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraq Denies It Will Export Chemical Weapons Know-How</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chemical Conference, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said Wednesday it will not export chemical
weapons technology learned during its war with Iran.
   On the sidelines of the international chemical weapons conference
here, Western delegates have been alleging that Iraq's Middle East
neighbors are lining up in Baghdad to learn how to make toxic arms.
   One Western expert, speaking to reporters on condition of
anonymity, said, ``Iraq has used them (chemical arms) for five years
and has lots of experience with a range of agents and delivery
systems. ... more even than the United States and Soviet Union.
   ``Some Third World countries are going to Iraq to learn.''
   But Iraq's foreign minister, Tarik Aziz, speaking in English at a
news conference Wednesday, declared, ``Whatever experience we have
in this respect we will not spread it to others. We are not very
much fond of exporting our experience in this respect.''
   Iraq is believed to have several plants producing chemical
weapons.
   Commenting on negotiations to end the 8-year-old Iraq-Iran
conflict, Aziz said: ``Our feeling is that Iranians are not yet
ready to accept peace.''
   Iraq has said it used chemical weapons only after Iran did.
</TEXT>
