<FIRST>r a AM-TeamstersTrial     01-11 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teamsters Trial,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial of Teamsters Officials Charged in Payroll Padding Scheme Goes
to Jury</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.R. KROPKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury began deliberating charges Wednesday
against two Teamsters union officials accused of participating in a
$700,000 ``ghost employees'' scheme that allegedly involved the late
union boss Jackie Presser.
   The labor racketeering and embezzlement trial of Harold Friedman
and Anthony Hughes culminated a six-year effort by the Justice
Department and Department of Labor to turn up wrongdoing in the
Cleveland power base of Presser, president of the 1.6 million-member
union from 1983 until his death July 9 from brain cancer.
   Presser would have been a co-defendant. His health problems led
to several delays of the trial, which started Oct. 24.
   Friedman, 66, is a Teamsters international vice president and
Hughes, 52, a recording secretary for Local 507.
   The 12 jurors received instructions from U.S. District Judge
George W. White in the morning and deliberated for three hours
before adjourning for the day. They were scheduled to resume
Thursday morning.
   Much of the testimony concerned Presser's actions from the early
1970s through 1981, the period when four men are alleged to have
been paid a combined $700,000 from union dues without working.
   Friedman, who became Ohio's most powerful Teamster after
Presser's death, faces two counts owo Pennsylvania utilities on
Wednesday from billing electricity customers for nearly $50 million
invested in four abandoned plants.
   In another action, the court lengthened the time union members
have to sue their unions over alleged free-speech violations,
reviving a North Carolina man's lawsuit against his union.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines, seeking to raise cash, has sold
six A-300 wide-body jet planes to sister carrier Continental
Airlines.
   Eastern will receive $103 million cash and a $67 million note at
17.5 percent interest for the sale, Eastern spokeswoman Karen
Ceremsak said Wednesday. The planes had been leased earlier to
Continental and therefore will have no effect on the size of
Eastern's fleet, she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This is the winter of the New England ski
industry's discontent: Snowfall is below average and business is off
despite efforts to blanket the slopes with man-made white stuff.
   Christopher H. Gill, manager of Great American Ski Renting Co.'s
store in North Conway, N.H., said Wednesday ``the skiing is really
good,'' thanks to artificial snow making in his area. But, he said,
business is down about 25 percent from last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1988 cotton crop is expected to be at a
7-year high of 15.4 million bales, up 5 percent from the 1987
harvest and 2 percent more than forecast last month, the Agriculture
Department said.
   In its new estimate based on Jan. 1 conditions, the department's
Agricultural Statistics Board also said Wednesday orange production,
estimated at 215 million boxes, would be up 7 percent from last
season.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market revived its early-1989 rally Wednesday as the
Dow Jones industrial average rose 13.22 points to 2,206.43, its
highest close since it stood at 2,246.74 on Oct. 16, 1987.
   The dollar fell in hectic foreign-exchange trading as central
banks engaged in concerted dollar-selling.
   Bond prices were mixed as municipal and corporate issues rose
while Treasury bonds fell.
   Coffee futures prices plunged; energy futures rose sharply;
grains, soybeans, livestock, meat and precious metal futures fell;
and stock-index futures advanced.
