<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru   01-11 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0710,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grenade Attack Kills One, Injures Five, Including Two North Americans</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to UPDATE with army denial; picks up 3rd
graf, `In a separate...' INSERTS three grafs after 11th, `Ever since..'
with details, U.S. comment; picks up 12th, `El Salvador's...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANCHIMILAMA, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fragmentation grenade tossed
into a settlement of civil war refugees killed a peasant and injured
five other people, including two church workers from the United
States and Canada.
   Witnesses on Wednesday blamed the army for the Tuesday night
attack. An army spokesman denied military involvement.
   In a separate incident, the military arrested a human rights
activist sociology professor from Hunter College in New York and a
Salvadoran human rights activist, the El Salvador Human Rights
Commission said Wednesday.
   Jose Sixto Montoya, 35, died at the scene of the grenade attack.
The injured were evacuated to the Central Diagnostic Hospital in San
Salvador, the capital, about 22 miles away. They were carried out of
the isolated coffee-growing area in hammocks.
   Deborah Cohen, 26, of New York, and Evan Fox Decent, 21, of
Canada, both Lutheran Church workers, suffered shrapnel wounds.
   ``I don't know what happened,'' Ms. Cohen told journalists in
Spanish as she was being evacuated. ``We were talking when I heard a
noise and saw a flash. I have shrapnel in my arms and legs. My eyes
are very bad. I can barely see.''
   Red Cross workers said Decent was in serious condition.
   The two lived in Panchimilama, aiding 350 refugees from El
Salvador's civil war.
   ``They are beloved by the peasants for the work they are doing,''
said Bishop Medardo Gomez, who rushed to Panchimilama after hearing
of the attack.
   Residents said they suspected soldiers of lobbing the grenade
into the camp. They said they have been harassed by soldiers since
they arrived in Panchimilama.
   ``Ever since we arrived at this place in 1986, we have been
accused of being guerrillas,'' said 21-year-old Petrona Alvarado.
``The army constantly searches our homes.''
   An armed forces spokesman denied army troops were involved.
   ``The armed forces is not responsible for a terrorist act
directed against humble campesinos and is investigating the case to
determine those who were responsible,'' the spokesman said, speaking
on the usual condition of anonymity.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Joseph McManus said he had no information
about the case and that even if he did, he would be unauthorized to
release it.
   El Salvador's U.S.-backed government has been at war with leftist
guerrillas for eight years.
   The Human Rights Commission said soldiers on Tuesday arrested
Jack Hammond, a sociology professor at Hunter College, and Celia
Medrano, a member of the commission, near the community of Jucuaran
in Usulutan province, about 80 miles from the capital.
   It said they were investigating allegations of human rights
abuses by the military at the time of their arrest.
   Armed forces spokesman Col. Galileo Torres said he had no
information about any arrests.
</TEXT>
