<FIRST>r a AM-People-Sadler     01-11 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Sadler,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Singer to Appear at Hearing, Wife's Attorney Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARGARET LILLARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer-author Barry Sadler, who wrote the
``Ballad of the Green Berets,'' left a hospital where he was being
treated for brain damage and is believed to be staying with friends,
a lawyer said Wednesday.
   Sadler's wife, Lavona Ruth Sadler, and mother claim he is
incompetent and should be placed under guardianship. His 24-year-old
son on Tuesday was named temporary guardian.
   Sadler, 48, was shot in the head during a robbery attempt at his
home in Guatemala City in September and lost 30 percent of his
brain, said Hal Hardin, an attorney for Sadler's wife.
   ``Sometimes he's lucid, sometimes he's not. Sometimes he's
conversant, sometimes he's not,'' Hardin said, adding that Sadler is
partly paralyzed and has other physical problems that call for
medical supervision.
   Sadler was discharged Sunday night from a Veterans Administration
Hospital in Cleveland. Hospital spokeswoman Jane Kennedy-Aspis was
not immediately available for comment Wednesday, her office said.
   Hardin said he and Mrs. Sadler believe Sadler's whereabouts are
known by, or he is with, Stephen K. Somers and Paul E. Hill, two
Ohio men identified as former members of the U.S. Special Forces,
the Green Berets.
   The men were identified in a lawsuit filed by Mrs. Sadler in
Nashville seekng to place her husband under guardianship. She said
she has not seen her husband since Dec. 26, when she visited him in
Cleveland.
   The singer's mother, Blanche Bebe Sadler of Denver, filed a
petition Thursday in Cleveland for guardianship.
   Lawyers for Somers and Hill have promised that Sadler will attend
a court hearing Friday in Cleveland, where Sadler's competence will
be discussed and a guardian appointed if needed, Hardin said.
   ``Their position is Mr. Sadler is competent,'' Hardin said.
``They assure me he's in good shape.''
   ``We assume and we're hoping that he's in good hands and that
he's going to be brought to court,'' Hardin said. ``We're just
concerned that he gets proper medical treatment.''
   ``It's so complicated right now,'' Mrs. Sadler said. ``I want him
back in the hospital.''
   Sadler's ``Ballad of the Green Berets'' was a No. 1 song in 1966.
</TEXT>
