<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti-Cuba     01-11 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti-Cuba,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuba Repatriates 234 Haitian `Boat People'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Cuban military planes landed here
Wednesday with 234 Haitians whose rickety boats, apparently sailing
for Florida, drifted to Cuba, a radio station reported.
   Radio Inter, an independent station, said they included Jean
Tatoune, who led demonstrations in the northern port of Gonaives
that helped drive dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier into exile in
February 1986.
   The Haitians reached Cuba in November and December and were
returned in two groups Wednesday about 5{ hours apart, met by
officials of the Red Cross and Haitian immigration, the radio said.
   Tatoune had not been heard from since last summer, after telling
radio stations he was being persecuted by the military and was
unable to hold a steady job. Soldiers ransacked his home in a
Gonaives slum during unrest in 1987.
   Haitians fleeing poverty and political violence normally head for
Florida, but Tatoune and his companions drifted ashore in Cuba, 90
miles west of Haiti.
   Cuba usually shelters and feeds Haitian who wind up in its waters
for several months before either returning them or sending them on
their way in repaired boats. It does not have diplomatic relations
with Haiti or the United States.
   A record 6,000 Haitians who set sail from their homeland were
repatriated in 1988 by the Bahamas and the U.S. Coast Guard, the
Haitian Red Cross has reported.
</TEXT>
