<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 2045EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NoahRobinson     01-11 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Noah Robinson,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Robinson Pleads Innocent To Murder Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Businessman Noah Robinson, Jesse
Jackson's half-brother, pleaded innocent Wednesday to charges that
he ordered members of a Chicago gang to kill a former employee here
in January 1986.
   Robinson was accompanied by two lawyers and several ministers
when he entered his plea during a brief arraignment hearing.
   Robinson has been charged with murder and conspiracy in
connection with the slaying of Leroy ``Hambone'' Barber, who once
worked for Robinson in Chicago. Authorities believe Robinson hired
members of the El Rukn gang to kill Barber after several disputes,
then conspired to kill a witness to the slaying.
   A lawyer for Robinson criticized extensive security measures
ordered by Circuit Judge James Moore for Robinson's trial, which
begins Monday.
   The measures are unnecessary and designed to intimidate defense
witnesses and influence jurors, said Albert Taylor Jr., one of
Robinson's Greenville lawyers.
   ``If you can't get a conviction in the courtroom, you can get it
by creating mass hysteria before you walk in,'' Taylor said.
   Spectators will have to pass through a metal detector before
entering the courtroom, and police sharpshooters may be stationed
atop the courthouse, law enforcement officials said.
   Officers also plan to watch for unfamiliar faces in the crowd,
said Greenville Police Chief Mike Bridges, and officers have
received photographs of El Rukn gang members who could be in the
courtroom.
   Robinson, who owns a construction company and several other
enterprises across the country, has maintained that the case is
politically motivated, and that the only state witnesses against him
are criminals who have been promised lenient sentences in exchange
for testimony.
   Although Robinson and Jackson share relatives in Greenville, the
former Democratic presidential hopeful has said he has had no recent
contact with his half-brother.
</TEXT>
