<FIRST>r a AM-Grammys     01-11 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grammys,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chapman And Michael Likely Multiple Nomination Candidates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer-songwriter Tracy Chapman, who
had a surprise hit with an album of ballads and protest songs and
crossover pop master George Michael are heavy favorites for multiple
nominations for the 31st annual Grammy Awards.
   The nominations were set for announcement Thursday morning at the
Beverly Hilton Hotel, when the results of nomination ballots sent to
more than 6,000 National Association of Recording Arts and Sciences
members will be read.
   Winners will be announced at the Shrine Auditorium in Los Angeles
on Feb. 22 during a three-hour awards ceremony to be televised on
CBS at 8 p.m. EST. Pierre Cossette will produce the show.
   Miss Chapman, whose self-titled album has sold more than 2
million copies, was a surprise star of 1988 amid the techno-pop and
thriving heavy metal sounds.
   Her single ``Fast Car'' was a Top 10 hit, and the album had
several other nuggets. Nominations seem certain for best song, best
album, best single, best new artist, best female pop vocalist and
best contemporary folk performance.
   Michael's ``Faith'' LP has sold more than 6 million copies and
has spawned six hits, including several crossovers on both pop and
soul charts.
   Michael, whose musical style has changed considerably _ some
would say pretentiously, since the days when he was half of the pop
duo Wham! _ should be in line for best song, single and album and
best performance in one or all of the pop, rock and rhythm and blues
categories.
   Others to watch for are nominations for vocal gymnast Bobby
McFerrin, his ``Don't Worry, Be Happy'' single and ``Simple
Pleasures,'' LP; the Beach Boys, who have never won a competitive
Grammy, getting another chance with the song ``Kokomo;'' and
possible multiple nods to Steve Winwood for his ``Roll With It''
song and LP; and INXS for their ``Kick'' album and ``Need You
Tonight-Mediate'' single; and Terence Trent D'Arby's debut album.
   Forecasting Grammy nominees and winners is no longer the easy job
it once was, agreed Billboard magazine columnist Paul Grein, who
said the changes in NARAS have become the most apparent over the
past five years.
   ``The academy has recruited many new members, most of them
younger and more ready to give rock its due,'' Grein said Wednesday.
``It's much harder now to get a handle on what they do. Once it was
pretty easy to just line up whoever fit in the Barbra
Streisand-Doobie Brothers-Billy Joel middle of the road form. Now
those acts still do well, but they also recognize rock acts like
Prince, U2, and Bruce Springsteen.''
   The Grammy nominations for an all-time high 76 categories were
culled this year from a record 6,800 entries released between Oct.
1, 1987, and Sept. 30, 1988.
   The membership of NARAS includes certified musicians who have had
their work recorded and distributed, recording engineers and other
technicians as well as music executives and others associated with
the music industry.
   Besides hard rock-heavy metal and rap, best bluegrass was added
as a new award for 1989, and a new fusion field was established by
the academy for the existing categories of best jazz fusion
performance and best new age performance.
</TEXT>
