<FIRST>u w AM-Nancy-Barbara 500   01-11 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nancy-Barbara, 500</SECOND>
<HEAD>First-Laday-to-Be Gets House Tour</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY SUSANNE SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush got a tour of her next home _ 1600
Pennsylvania Avenue _ Wednesday and vowed afterwards ``not...to
change one thing,'' her spokeswoman said.
   First lady Nancy Reagan treated her successor to a 45-minute
afternoon tea and tour of the White House, in particular the second
and third floor areas that will serve as the private residence for
George Bush and his wife after he is inaugurated Jan. 20.
   Mrs. Bush's spokeswoman, Sondra Haley, quoted her as saying after
the private tour, ``It's the most beautiful house I have ever seen.
I'm not going to change one thing.''
   Eight years ago, when the nation was in an economic slump, Mrs.
Reagan was criticized for organizing a high-priced redecoration of
the White House, even though the effort was privately financed.
   Mrs. Reagan, according to her spokeswoman Elaine Crispen,
expressed confidence in Mrs. Bush, saying, ``I know she will take
good care of this wonderful old house.''
   Traditionally, the outgoing president leaves the mansion to
attend the Inaugural, while the new president and his family enter
the White House after the ceremonies.
   The domestic staff at the White House sees to it during the
festivities that the personal belongings of the outgoing president
and his wife are packed and removed. At the same time, the new
families' items are brought in for them.
   Mrs. Reagan, however, had most of their furniture and personal
items transferred to their new home in Los Angeles last October.
President Reagan and his wife spent nine nights at the $2.5 million
Bel-Air estate over the Christmas holidays.
   Mrs. Crispen said that even though Mrs. Bush, as the wife of the
vice president, has often visited the executive mansion, there were
many rooms that she hadn't seen _ such as the kitchen on the second
floor and the laundry on the third floor.
   ``They just kind of went around, looking and seeing what it's all
about,'' Mrs. Crispen said.
   Mrs. Crispen said Mrs. Bush will most probably arrange for the
placement of her own larger pieces of furniture after the inaugural.
   At the moment, the private rooms are decorated with items from
the store of furniture, china and artworks that are available for
use in the executive mansion.
   Ms. Healey said Mrs. Bush is currently overseeing the packing at
the vice president's mansion, and she expected the first couple to
bring many things that had graced their home on the grounds of the
Naval Observatory.
   ``All their sitting room, living room and bedroom furniture is
coming, her needlepoint rug, many of their personal things,'' she
said.
   Mrs. Bush crafted the rug over an 8-year period, Ms. Haley said.
   The spokeswoman said she was certain Mrs. Bush would also make
use of the many ``touches of China'' they owned, the items of
furniture and artwork the couple bought during Bush's tenure as the
first American envoy to Peking.
</TEXT>
