<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     01-11 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armenian, Azerbaijani Leaders Agree to Tell Refugees to Go Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the strife-torn republics of Armenia and
Azerbaijan agreed Wednesday to try persuading more than 200,000
refugees who fled ethnic violence to return home, the official news
agency Tass reported.
   This will require ``reliable guarantees of security for the
people,'' Tass said.
   About 160,000 Azerbaijanis fled Christian Armenia and at least
90,000 Armenians fled Moslem Azerbaijan when long-term ethnic
tension broke out in riots, arson and other violence that killed at
least 74 people in 1988.
   The government and Communist Party authorities of the two
republics agreed that a turning point is upon them, in apparent
reference to the current lull in ethnic violence, which followed the
Armenian earthquake Dec. 7 that killed at least 25,000 people.
   ``Not only a particular turn of events in Azerbaijan and Armenia,
but also the destinies of perestroika as a whole'' depends on
decisive action, Tass said of the officials' discussion.
Perestroika, or restructuring, is the word used for President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's economic and social reforms.
   The leaders agreed on joint appeals to refugees to return home,
and to establish contacts between Armenian and Azerbaijani
organizations at all levels in an attempt to promote peace. They
also agreed to combat rumors and misinformation, which have been
blamed for fanning the unrest.
   The meeting included the first and second secretaries of the
Communist parties of both republics, as well as the president and
prime minister of each, Tass said.
   The news agency said nothing about a meeting on the same subject
and the same day that was to include a commission of Gorbachev and
the ruling Communist Party Politburo.
</TEXT>
