<FIRST>r w AM-Reagan-Warning     01-11 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Warning,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Embargoed For Release at 9 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Young People Need Fuller Appreciation of American Heritage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan used Wednesday night's
farewell address to warn that parents need to do a better job of
teaching their children about America's heritage, saying that
``well-grounded patriotism is no longer the style.''
   In an apparent reference to Dwight D. Eisenhower's farewell
warning in January 1961 about an emerging military-industrial
complex, Reagan talked of ``a great tradition of warnings in
presidential farewells, and I've got one that's been on my mind for
some time.''
   He said that while he was proud about a resurgence of national
pride during his eight years as president, ``it won't count for much
and it won't last unless it's grounded in thoughtfulness and
knowledge.''
   `` ... Now we're about to enter the '90s, and some things have
changed,'' Reagan said. ``Younger parents aren't sure that an
unambivalent appreciation of America is the right thing to teach
modern children.''
   ``If we forget what we did, we won't know who we are.''
   Reagan said that Americans who are 35 or older ``grew up in a
different America'' where patriotic values were taught by parents,
relatives, neighbors and friends. And if all else failed, you could
get a sense of patriotism from the popular culture.''
   ``As as for those who create the popular culture, well-grounded
patriotism is no longer the style,'' he said.
   ``Our spirit is back,'' Reagan said, ``but we haven't
reinstitutionalized it. We've got to do a better job of getting
across that America is freedom _ freedom of speech, freedom of
religion, freedom of enterprise. ... It's fragile. It needs
protection.''
</TEXT>
