<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 2300EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     01-11 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow For The Rockies, Rain South-Centrally, Winds In The West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell on the northern Plains and Rockies on Wednesday, winds
gusted to 60 mph in the California mountains, fog prevailed in parts
of the Mississippi Valley and a few thunderstorms rumbled near the
Gulf Coast.
   Six to 10 inches of snow fell overnight in the mountains of
northern Colorado and southern Wyoming.
   In Colorado, 10 inches of snow fell at Powderhorn Ski Area, 6
inches at Steamboat Springs and 4 inches at Aspen.
   In the northern Plains, several inches of snow fell overnight in
eastern Montana and the Dakotas, with 5 inches of snow reported at
Crookston, Minn.
   Strong high pressure off the Pacific Coast brought gusty winds to
the Southwest, with high wind watch in effect through Thursday for
the mountains and higher deserts of Southern California, with winds
gusting to 60 mph.
   Southerly winds brought warmer weather to parts of the southern
Plains and lower and middle Mississippi Valley, with temperatures
were in the 50s for parts of Missouri and up to 60 degrees at
Emporia, Kan.
   Along the Louisiana coast, temperatures were well up into the 70s.
   Moisture from the Gulf of Mexico produced rain and a few
thunderstorms from the Tennessee and lower Ohio valleys across much
of Arkansas and portions of Louisiana to eastern Texas. Some of the
rain was locally heavy.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 3
degrees below zero at Minot, N.D., to 82 degrees at Naples, Fla. The
low for the nation was 33 degrees below zero at Grand Forks, N.D.
   The national weather forecast for Thursday called for rain
widespread from Arkansas across the Tennessee and Ohio valleys to
western New York and the mid Atlantic Coast, with freezing rain in
parts of Pennsylvania and eastern New York will also have some
freezing rain.
   Mixed rain, freezing rain and snow will occur over New England.
Thunderstorms are expected from Kentucky across the Tennessee and
lower Mississippi valleys to eastern Texas. Rain will reach across
much of Texas, with freezing rain in northwest Texas. Snow will
extend from the Texas Panhandle across New Mexico and the southern
Colorado mountains to portions of Arizona. Rain will fall over
western Washington state.
   High temperatures will be in the teens in northern North Dakota
and northern Minnesota; in the 20s and 30s over the Intermountain
West, the Rockies, the Great Plains, the upper and middle
Mississippi Valley and the upper Great Lakes, with mostly 30s over
eastern Pennsylvania, much of New York and New England; in the 60s
and 70s from southern South Carolina and southern Georgia across the
central Gulf Coast to southern Texas and in southern California; in
the 80s in southern Florida. Elsewhere, highs will be in the 40s and
50s.
</TEXT>
