<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Unterecker     01-11 0142</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Unterecker,0147</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poet Dies After Heart Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Unterecker, a poet and biographer, has died
of complications following heart surgery. He was 66.
   Unterecker, who died Tuesday night at Straub Hospital, was
nominated for the National Book Award in 1970 for ``Voyager: A Life
of Hart Crane.'' He also wrote ``A Reader's Guide to W.B. Yeats,'' a
definitive text on the life of the poet.
   Unterecker's poetry had appeared in such magazines as The New
Yorker, Nation and Poetry.
   Unterecker was named to the Citizen's Chair in English Literature
at the University of Hawaii in 1969 after heading the English
department's graduate division of Columbia University.
   He was born in Buffalo, N.Y., and was a graduate of Middlebury
College. He received his doctorate in English from Columbia.
   Unterecker is survived by a sister, Helen Fiske of Rochester, N.Y.

</TEXT>
