<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 2315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Nuclear     01-11 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Nuclear,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Seek To Stop Construction of Crimean Nuke Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Soviet scientists on Wednesday called on
the government to halt construction of a nuclear power plant in the
Crimea, a popular resort area they say is prone to powerful
earthquakes.
   The 10 scientists, in a letter published by the Communist Party
daily Pravda, said the plant's first reactor, capable of generating
1 million kilowatts, is projected to begin operating sometime this
year.
   Construction of the plant began in 1980 and it is designed to
withstand earthquakes that measure 7 on the 12-point Soviet scale.
   The scientists said, however, that a government commission has
concluded that its site on the Crimea's Kerch Peninsula is prone to
force-9 quakes. In comparison, last month's Armenian earthquake was
rated a force-8 quake by the Soviets.
   The quake measured 6.9 on the Richter scale, a gauge of energy
released by an earthquake as measured by the ground motion recorded
on a seismograph.
   Experts have also found the Crimean plant to be located almost
directly atop an underground dome where high pressures could cause
deformation of the earth's surface and eruptions of volcanic mud and
gas, the scientists said.
   Tuesday night, the Soviet television news program ``Vreyma''
announced that Armenia's sole nuclear power station, which is built
on a geological fault in the southern republic, will be shut down by
March.
   Officials have said the Armenian plant was shaken but not damaged
by the Dec. 7 quake that killed at least 25,000 people in northwest
Armenia, but the quake apparently accelerated the government's
decision to shut down the plant.
   Since the April 1986 Chernobyl nuclear plant accident in the
Ukraine, the Soviets have moved away from a previously professed
faith in nuclear power as a completely safe energy source and public
opposition has grown.
   Nikolai Lukonin, the Soviet nuclear power minister, announced
Dec. 23 that six projects to build nuclear plants or add more
reactors at exisiting stations had been scrapped because of
earthquake danger or tougher standards imposed after the Chernobyl
accident.
   The Crimean power plant was not among those mentioned by Lukonin.
   The Crimea has some of the Soviet Union's most popular beach
resorts. It is home to 2 million people and welcomes at least as
many vacationers annually, the scientists said.
   The scientists, who included A. Yanshin, a member of the
prestigious Soviet Academy of Sciences, said they decided to go
public with experts' conclusions on the Crimean site because of
``many examples'' in the past where government agencies had either
silenced or twisted the conclusions of scientists and gone ahead
with building projects.
   ``Now the last word rests with the Council of Ministers of the
U.S.S.R., which must decide the fate of this construction project,
which was begun without the necessary scientific survey,'' the 10
scientists said.
   The 1986 Chernobyl accident, the worst in the history of nuclear
power, killed at least 31 people and released a cloud of radiation
that eventually circled the globe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
