<FIRST>r i AM-Peru-Violence     01-11 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru-Violence,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Reportedly Kill 36 In Three Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maoist guerrillas killed four police officers
in a bold raid against a jungle electric plant, and mountain
insurgents executed four members of a merchant family after a mock
trial, officials said Wednesday.
   The violence occurred Monday night, bringing to 36 the number of
people killed since Saturday in the Mao-inspired guerrilla group's
9-year-old fight to install Marxist rule.
   ``The Shining Path is intent on sabotaging all signs of economic
activity and isolating these regions from the rest of the country to
expand its armed fight,'' said a police spokesmen who refused to be
named for security reasons.
   Police said three dozen rebels attacked a power generating plant
on the outskirts of Tingo Maria but were driven away by police
guards in a 30-minute gun battle that left four officers dead.
   Another Shining Path column in San Jose de Quero shot dead
74-year-old Alfredo Tacza, his son, and a daughter and her husband
after accusing them during a mock trial of providing supplies to
military troops, police said.
   Police said the family operated five dry goods stores in San Jose
and four other hamlets surrounding the highland capital of Huancayo,
125 miles east of the capital Lima.
   The government has given the military broad policing and
political powers throughout the central highlands and
cocaine-producing jungle to resist the Shining Path, whose
insurgency has claimed more than 12,000 lives.
   Tingo Maria, 240 miles northeast of Lima, is the center of
government anti-drug operations into the nearby Huallaga Valley,
where officials estimate 60 percent of the world's cocaine-producing
coca leaf is grown.
   Police said the valley's reputation as a lawless no-man's land
has grown since the Shining Path recently began providing protection
to drug traffickers _who smuggle semi-processed cocaine to Colombia
for refining _ in exchange for money to purchase weapons.
   In previously reported violence since the weekend, rebels killed
11 policemen near Tingo Maria, and 12 campesinos and five others in
the Andes Mountains.
</TEXT>
