<FIRST>u a AM-BabyMissing 1stLd-Writethru a0724 01-11 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baby Missing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0724,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Charge Parents In Child's Murder</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with details of charges and continuing
search for missing body part; picks up 5th graf pvs: `Mrs. Dacri ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young mother was charged Wednesday with
murdering her 2-month-old son and the father was charged with
dismembering the body before the couple told police two purse
snatchers kidnapped the child.
   Officers dredging suburban creeks found five bags containing
parts of Zachary Dacri's body, including his head, police said.
   Part of the body still was missing, and medical examiners had not
determined what caused the infant's death sometime over the weekend,
Capt. Robert Grasso said.
   Grasso would not say what led police to search the waterways or
whether a knife found outside the couple's home was the murder
weapon.
   Police confirmed reports that the couple temporarily lost custody
of another child on allegations of child abuse.
   The baby's 20-year-old mother, Tanya, faces charges of murder,
false reports, hindering apprehension, tampering with evidence,
obstruction of justice and conspiracy in tampering with a corpse,
police said.
   The child's father, Phillip, 22, faces charges of obstruction of
justice, tampering with evidence, aiding in a crime and conspiracy
in tampering with a corpse, police said.
   Assistant District Attorney Barbara Christie said the couple
would be prosecuted in Philadelphia, but would not say what led
police to believe the murder was committed in the city.
   The body parts found Wednesday were in a creek in Bucks County.
Police divers also were to resume a search Thursday morning in
Carbon County for a torso believed tossed into the Pohopoco Creek
from a Pennsylvania Turnpike overpass Sunday night, said Bud
Campbell, a Philadelphia detective.
   Accompanying Campbell at the search site near the Lehigh River
was a young, gaunt woman he identified only as a witness in the case.
   Mrs. Dacri, who also has a 1-year-old daughter, told police one
man grabbed her by the neck and another yanked Zachary from her arms
along with her purse Tuesday afternoon as she walked to a doctor's
office in a Philadelphia shopping mall. She said the two left in a
brown sedan without a license plate and driven by a third man.
   She said there were no other witnesses.
   Police began to suspect murder when the investigation kept
turning up more questions than answers, Capt. Richard DeLise said.
   Police said the couple had lost custody of the other child,
Christine, last January on allegations of child abuse. The girl was
returned to her parents several months later after they received
counseling and underwent therapy.
   The Philadelphia Daily News reported Wednesday that the couple
had taken the older child to Frankford Hospital for emergency
treatment, saying she had stopped breathing while in the bathtub.
   During treatment, doctors noticed signs of swelling related to
malnutrition and that she appeared to be of below-average weight,
the newspaper said. The hospital notified the city Department of
Human Services, which placed the baby in the care of relatives, the
newspaper said.
   DeLise had no comment on the report.
   Police told the newspaper the Dacris had been treated last year
at the Benjamin Rush Center for Mental Health and Mental
Retardation. Preston Ringo, deputy executive director of the center,
said she could not comment on whether the couple had received
treatment.
   The Dacris are natives of northeastern Pennsylvania. He is from
Wyoming County and the baby's mother is from nearby Scranton.
</TEXT>
