<FIRST>r i AM-GorbachevNominated     01-11 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev Nominated,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Gets Guaranteed Congressional Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev won't be out kissing
babies to win election to the new Congress of People's Deputies
because the Communist Party nominated him to a guaranteed seat.
   The official news agency Tass reported Wednesday that Gorbachev
was one of the 100 people nominated by the party's Central Committee
on Tuesday for its 100 guaranteed seats. The new 2,250-member
congress will elect a working parliament and the nation's president
from among its members.
   Gorbachev, the Communist Party leader, was named president by the
old parliment in October. He is widely expected to be elected to
that position by the new one.
   The political reform law passed in November promised
multiple-candidate elections would be allowed. But the Communist
Party example of one seat, one candidate dampens the prospects for
widespread contention.
   Tass also reported Wednesday that the Soviet Peace Foundation and
eight other official peace organizations nominated 17 candidates for
the congress, including journalist Fyodor Burlatsky and former world
chess champion Anatoly Karpov.
   Tass did not say if the peace organizations also have guaranteed
seats or if they nominated more candidates than positions.
   One-third of the 2,250 deputies will be elected by organizations
such as the Communist Party and trade unions. The other two-thirds
will be elected by the public on March 26.
</TEXT>
