<FIRST>u w AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0715 01-11 0785</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0715,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Defends Japan Trip</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds:Top 3 grafs new to update with CBS report about Watkins picked
as Energy Secretary, 4th graf edited for transition, picks up into 2nd
graf previous</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush has picked retired Admiral
James D. Watkins to be the Secretary of Energy in his
administration, CBS News reported Wednesday night.
   The selection of the 61-year-old former Chief of Naval Operations
would fill the last remaining spot in the Bush Cabinet as the vice
president prepares for next week's inauguration.
   The only major post still unfilled by Bush is the ``drug czar''
to oversee the nation's fight against illegal drugs.
   Earlier Wednesday, Bush defended his decision to attend Japanese
Emperor Hirohito's funeral next month against criticism from those
who still resent Hirohito's World War II role.
   ``I'm doing what's right,'' Bush told reporters. President Reagan
had earlier said Bush was doing the proper thing.
   Bush, in remarks to reporters before a meeting with black college
presidents, said his appointment of an energy secretary _ the last
vacancy in his Cabinet _ will be ``coming up pretty soon.''
   ``We'll probably have some announcements soon, very soon,'' Bush
added.
   There has been an outcry in Great Britain over the royal family's
plan to send Prince Philip as its representative to the funeral of
its former wartime adversary.
   There has been little U.S. commentary over Bush's decision. Bush
had no qualms about criticism he may get from fellow World War II
veterans.
   Bush, a former Navy aviator whose plane was shot down by the
Japanese in the Pacific in 1944, said, ``I think I speak from a
pretty good vantage point and the answer is no.''
   ``We have a good relationship with Japan. I want to see it even
better. And this doesn't concern me a bit. And you're talking to a
person who was in combat in World War II,'' he said.
   ``I feel you look ahead, not always look back. You do what's
right. I'm doing what's right,'' Bush said.
   Asked if he would visit Australia and Korea as well when he goes
to Japan, Bush said, ``There are no plans formulated, but I am going
to Japan.''
   Asked if he would stop in any other countries on the journey to
Japan, Bush said, ``I haven't thought about that.''
   His future chief of staff, John Sununu, joked to reporters,
``Don't forget Tahiti and Guam.''
   Bush, 64, became the Navy's youngest aviator after enlisting on
his 18th birthday soon after the Japanese bombed Pearl Harbor.
   He was shot down Sept. 2, 1944, while piloting a torpedo bomber
near a Japanese-held island, Chicachi Jima. Two of his crew
perished, but Bush himself was rescued by an American submarine that
happened to be patrolling in the area.
   Bush got an early start Wednesday to his stated plan of barring
questions at photo opportunities once he becomes president. He did
so by striding up to the pool of reporters waiting to follow him
into the meeting with black educators, and fielding several
questions.
   ``We're starting this marvelously enlightened policy that
respects the dignity of the job you do in this _ it is the fifth
estate, isn't it?'' Bush joked.
   ``Aren't you thrilled with the new policy, though, seriously? The
dignity that goes now with your jobs?'' he asked.
   Afterwards, Bush spoke with two dozen leaders of black colleges
and universities.
   Dr. Louis Sullivan, president of Morehouse School of Medicine and
Bush's choice for secretary of health and human services, also
attended the meeting, along with Vice President-elect Dan Quayle and
Lauro F. Cavazos, the holdover secretary of education.
   Benjamin Payton, president of Tuskegee University in Alabama,
said the presidents asked Bush not to penalize colleges for high
student loan default rates, as former Education Secretary William J.
Bennett proposed last year. The Education Department, under Cavazos,
has held off on the crackdown.
   ``Institutions of higher education do not make these loans. ...
These are transactions between banks and individuals,'' said Payton,
who asked Bush to ``see to it that institutions are not penalized.''
   S. Dallas Simmons, president of Virginia Union University, said
Bush and Cavazos ``indicated this would not be the last meeting, but
only the first of many during the years to come.'' He added, ``I am
leaving the meeting feeling very, very good.''
   Leroy Keith Jr., president of Morehouse College in Atlanta,
called it ``an extraordinary session.''
   ``He indicated that he was going to be an education president. He
reiterated it to us,'' said William R. Harvey, president of Hampton
University in Virginia. He called Bush ``a very apt pupil'' with ``a
long history of support for black higher education.''
</TEXT>
