<FIRST>a a PM-ReligionRoundup Adv13   01-11 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Religion Roundup, Adv 13,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Fri PMs Jan. 13, or thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The theme for Roman Catholicism's 1989 National
Migration Week, observed across the country Jan. 9-14, is ``Migrants
and the Blessed Mother.''
   In designating the theme, Pope John Paul II pointed out that the
Virgin Mary's ``earthly life was marked by a continual pilgrimage
from one place to another'' _ from Nazareth to Bethlehem and then in
flight to Egypt to save the child Jesus and later back again to
Nazareth.
   ``She shines as a sign of certain hope and comfort to the pilgrim
people of God,'' the pope said.
   The week was insituted by the U.S. National Conference of
Catholic Bishops in 1980 to emphasize commitment and service to
people on the move, including political refugees, economic migrants,
seasonal farm workers and displaced persons.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seymour D. Reich of Great Neck, N.Y., a lawyer
and international president of B'nai B'rith, has been elected
chairman of the Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish
Organizations.
   He succeeds Morris B. Abram. The conference includes 46 national
Jewish secular and religious groups whose members comprise most
American Jews.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates to an assembly of Lutherans Concerned,
an organization of Lutheran homosexuals, expressed ``deep grief and
sadness'' that the churches have ``denied us full participation.''
   They have ``permitted malicious, false and antiquated images of
lesbian and gay persons'' and ``abandoned us in the face of growing
homophopia, violence and oppression,'' the assembly said in a ``Call
for Repentence.''
   It appealed for dialogue with church leaders and said, ``The
dream of participating fully and openly in the life of the church
remains a dream, and only a dream, for most of us.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most failures of past plans to evangelize the
world have resulted from ``internal problems within the church and
the Christian world,'' says a new book distributed to a conference
about such current efforts.
   The book, ``Seven Hundred Plans to Evangelize the World,'' by
researcher David Barrett and evangelical editor James Reapsome, says
failures of the plans can't be blamed on external circumstances.
   Numerous groups with goals of evangelizing the world by the year
2000 were among about 300 participants in the meeting here last
weekend.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. J. Eddie Fox, evangelism staff
executive for the United Methodist Board of Discipleship, has been
named world director of evangelism for the World Methhodist Council.
   He succeeds the Rev. Alan Walker of Sydney, Australia, who has
retired after more than 10 years in the post.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tendency to assume that religion is concerned
largely with salvation in the hereafter rather than with present
life was stunningly refuted by a recent study.
   It found that religious bodies led the field in charitable work
for others, surpassing foundations and corporations.
   Brian O`Connell, president of Independent Sector, a coalition of
660 corporate, foundation and voluntary philanthrophic organizations
which sponsored the study, said:
   ``We realize more than we had expected how much the organized
neighborliness of religious organizations means to the kind of
caring society we are.''
   The study found that almost half of the $4l.4 billion contributed
in 1986 to religion was used to support services to others, the rest
spent on internal activities such as worship and religious education.
   Pollster George Gallup, whose organization gathered the data,
said it showed churches are ``among our most cost-effective
institutions'' in philanthropic work, with minimal administrative
overhead.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Jan. 13.</NOTE>
