<FIRST>a a PM-Inaugural-BoysChoir Adv16   01-11 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Inaugural-Boys Choir, Adv16,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs Jan 16 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Appalachian Boys Choir Ready to Perform at Bush Inauguration</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ROBRAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARLAN, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harlan County, an Appalachian coal town passed
by in the economic recovery of the Reagan years, hopes to move
beyond the stereotypes of poverty and strike violence when its
award-winning boys choir performs at the inauguration of George Bush
this week.
   ``We know how people perceive us, and we hope our offering will
allow us an opportunity to change that,'' choir director David
Davies said, adding that he thought ``it's only natural'' for
outsiders to buy the stereotypes about Appalachia.
   The community of 3,000 has reacted with pride to the 76-member
group's selection last month to be the lead choir for the
inauguration.
   ``It's been one of the biggest and best things that's happened to
the community,'' said Harlan County Judge-Executive Delzinna
Belcher. ``The choir is one of the good traditions that's just
particular to Harlan County.''
   Some people are wary that publicity about the choir may be
accompanied by yet another wave of stories about the troubles in the
region.
   ``Frankly, I'm sick and tired of people who are not from this
area making a two-hour visit or a four-day goodwill tour and then
thinking they're experts about our area and our culture,'' Ms.
Belcher said.
   But she is among the first to acknowledge the county faces some
tough problems.
   Unemployment remains in double digits, blamed on overproduction
and increased automation in the coal industry. Poor roads and
utility services hamper economic development efforts.
   The community has been plagued by the lingering memory of
violence associated with coal strikes in the 1930s and 1940s that
earned the town the name ``Bloody Harlan.''
   Ms. Belcher said she hoped the choir, which represents 25 percent
of the male students in the Harlan city school district, would
provide people across the country a positive image of the area that
might help offset the negatives.
   The Bush family selected the choir from a list of several groups
that were candidates for the honor, said Mike Ruehlig, a staff
member for a congressional inaugural committee.
   Davies said the choir would sing ``This Is My Country'' on the
platform on the front lawn of the U.S. Capitol minutes before Bush
is sworn in as the nation's 41st president.
   The choir director said he hoped people watching the inauguration
would be impressed with the group's musical abilities and
discipline. He said the inaugural performance would stand out in the
choir's 24-year history, which has included international trips and
numerous competition trophies.
   Roy Allison, an insurance agent who is the choir's business
coordinator, said the group is raising the $25,000 needed for the
trip through donations.
   Television crews have been in Harlan for the past two weeks, and
one morning network television show plans to feature the choir
during a program on the morning of the inauguration.
   ``We're getting used to the TV cameras,'' said choir member
Jeremy Disney, 12. ``It will help us. This might get us ready for
when we get to Washington.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance PM Mon Jan. 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
