<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1421EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-BehindtheWheel Adv21-22   01-11 0791</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Behind the Wheel, Adv 21-22,0810</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv21-22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Jan. 21-22, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mercury Topaz a Sleeker Machine This Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thank heavens Ford saw fit to tweak the styling of its Ford Tempo
and Mercury Topaz cars. They have gone from blimpy jelly beans to
sleeker, more neatly packaged exteriors.
   Judging from last year's sales, American car buyers liked the
change, too. Topaz sales in 1988 rose 45 percent from 1987 levels,
to about 93,000, said company analyst Ray Windecker.
   Company spokesman Jim Trainor said Topaz sales of more than 7,600
last November set a monthly record. The Topaz sister car, the Ford
Tempo, also was up, with sales of about 280,000 in 1988 _ a 29
percent increase from 1987.
   Windecker and Trainor agreed the strong boost came mainly from
the new appearance. Starting in the 1988 model year, the vehicles
have taken styling cues from Ford's popular Taurus-Sable cars.
   The 1989 Mercury Topaz LS test car was a sturdy compact that took
little time getting used to. The Topaz hasn't changed much since its
introduction four years ago, so there wasn't an array of distracting
newfangled gadgets. The Topaz was just a car you could get into and
drive away.
   It offers sensible, day-to-day transportation. Don't look for
excitement.
   The 2.3-liter, four-cylinder engine _ in the Topaz since its
introduction _ seemed underpowered at times. Coupled with a
three-speed automatic transmission, it developed a maximum 100
horsepower at 4,400 rpm.
   But passing on the highway produced a loud whine under the Topaz
hood and a sluggish increase in speed. Speeding up in the city _ for
lane changes or whatever _ also was a bit disappointing.
   Still, Trainor noted that more power is not necessarily what the
average Topaz buyer wants, and the recent sales figures bear him
out. Price may be a factor in the Topaz purchase.
   The base price of the test Topaz was a little over $11,000
compared with a base price of $14,101 for the low-end Sable.
   The Topaz is between the Mercury Tracer and the Sable in the mix
of cars in Lincoln-Mercury dealerships, Trainor said, adding that
many buyers are looking for a good family car and thus opt for the
Topaz over the small Tracer.
   Topaz competitors include the Pontiac Grand Am and Chevrolet
Corsica, which start at around $11,000. Windecker said the Topaz has
an overall family image, with the median age of buyers at 44.4
years. Seventy-three percent are married, 50 percent are women, 21
percent are in professional-technical occupations, 12 percent are
office workers and 18 percent are retired. Median income is $33,000
annually.
   Besides the engine power, I had one other note about the Topaz.
Ford has installed automatic lap belts on the front seats. Though I
have driven other Ford cars with the belts, they seemed particularly
annoying in the Topaz, perhaps because the cloth seats also were
impossible to slide out of. As a result, I had to carefully plan how
to get out so my purse wouldn't keep getting hung up in the belts,
which automatically move towards the body when the key is turned in
the ignition and automatically move away when the door is opened.
   I don't even want to describe the scene when I lifted a small bag
of groceries out of the front seat. I finally started putting my
purse in the back seat and fetching it through a rear door after I
was out of the car.
   I also had a passenger who, unfamiliar with the belts, was hit in
the face by a belt when I started the car. The automatic shoulder
belts, by the way, still require manual attachment of the lap belts.
   Suspension in the Topaz was decent for a family car.
   There was lots of room in the trunk, though you have to lift
items up and over the car body in back before getting them into the
trunk.
   Seats were comfortable, and rear legroom was adequate.
   The all-wheel-drive option ($915) is chosen by just a small
percentage of Topaz buyers, Trainor said. But it really helped the
test car shine. Activated by a button above the rear-view mirror, it
performed well and was comforting on slick, snow-covered roads.
   Consumer Reports magazine says early models of the Topaz _ 1984
and 1985 _ ranked much worse than average in trouble reported by
owners. But later models _ 1986 and 1987 _ improved to average.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ann Job, former executive business editor of The
Detroit News, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The Associated
Press. She has covered the automobile industry for seven years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Jan. 21-22</NOTE>
