<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 0042EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   01-11 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0545</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's advisers recommended
curtailing deposit insurance for bank and savings and loan accounts,
triggering swift negative reaction from Congress and the Treasury
Department.
   In its final report to Reagan, the president's Council of
Economic Advisers said Tuesday reducing protection for depositors
would encourage them to more closely monitor the institutions
holding their money.
   But the Treasury Department, through Rep. Chalmers Wylie of Ohio,
senior Republican on the House Banking Committee, promptly distanced
itself from the latest proposal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The incoming Bush administration gave a
high-level advisory panel the go-ahead to begin work in earnest on
forging a solution to the federal government's huge deficit problems.
   Officials of the National Economic Commission said Tuesday they
had received word from Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady, who will
stay on as the Bush administration's chief economic spokesman, that
Bush will be looking for the panel's report March 1.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Attorney Rudolph W. Giuliani has resigned
after a 5{-year tenure that saw several successful prosecutions of
insider trading cases.
   Giuliani, 44, said Monday he would leave the office before next
month.
   Among Giuliani's targets on Wall Street was Dennis Levine, former
managing director at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., who pleaded guilty
to securities fraud and other charges. That led to guilty pleas by
financier Ivan Boesky and Drexel, among others.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mistrial has been declared in the stock
manipulation case against GAF Corp. and a top company officer,
throwing one of the biggest prosecutions spawned by the Wall Street
insider trading scandal into confusion.
   The mistrial ruling by U.S. District Judge Mary Johnson Lowe came
Tuesday after the defense challenged the government prosecutor's
handling of an important piece of evidence and said it had unfairly
hurt their case.
   Defense attorneys then requested dismissal of the entire
indictment, but Lowe rejected their request and said she intended to
begin picking jurors for a new trial later in the week. The defense
attorneys said they would appeal her decision to the 2nd Circuit
Court of Appeals.
