<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 0211EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GAFTrial Bjt   01-11 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GAF Trial, Bjt,0714</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Seeks Dismissal of Entire Indictment After Mistrial Declared</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense attorneys for GAF Corp. and a senior
company officer fighting stock manipulation charges have seized on
the declaration of a mistrial as grounds to have the entire
indictment dismissed.
   If they succeed, it would mark a major defeat for prosecutors
because the GAF trial marks the first important case arising from
the Wall Street corruption scandal to reach the trial phase.
   It has been seen as a key test of the government's ability to
persuade a jury of criminal charges resulting from the scandal,
which is now more than two years old.
   U.S. District Judge Mary Johnson Lowe's mistrial ruling Tuesday
stunned a packed courtroom and came after the defense challenged the
government prosecutor's handling of an important piece of evidence
and said it had unfairly hurt their case.
   Lowe dismissed the jurors, apologizing one month into a trial
that has attracted widespread attention. The judge said she intended
to start picking a jury for a new trial later in the week.
   Defense attorneys then requested dismissal of the entire
indictment, arguing the government is constitutionally barred from
bringing two actions against a defendant for the same charges.
   After Lowe rejected their request, the defense attorneys filed an
intention to appeal to the 2nd Circuit Court of Appeals, but it was
unclear late Tuesday whether the higher court would grant their
request for a hearing.
   ``We're appealing on grounds that the law says you don't have to
wear the same wet bathing suit twice,'' Arthur Liman, the lead
lawyer for GAF and one of the most prominent defense attorneys in
the country, told reporters.
   Liman and Stephen Kaufman, attorney for GAF vice chairman James
T. Sherwin, said they had no other option than to request a mistrial
because of a controversy about an invoice the government had
introduced to support its charges of stock manipulation.
   After defense attorneys challenged the invoice's authenticity
during testimony last week, prosecutor Carl Loewenson acknowledged
he had failed to provide them with a report indicating the evidence
may have been tampered with.
   Loewenson called the error an act of carelessness that would not
affect the trial. But the judge said under strict rules of
evidence-gathering, the prosecutor was obligated to share such
information with the defense attorneys, who claimed they would have
altered their strategy had they known about it.
   The government minimized the significance of the mistrial, which
coincided with the announcement that U.S. Attorney Rudolph W.
Giuliani _ the leader of a major crackdown on Wall Street corruption
_ will resign at the end of the month after more than five years of
service.
   ``This is not a last-minute slap in the face,'' Giuliani told a
news conference. ``We can't criticize her (Lowe's) decision,
although we would have preferred to go forward with the case.''
   Legal experts said they doubted the GAF defense team would
succeed in getting the indictment thrown out by an appeals court,
which ordinarily grants wide discretionary powers to lower-court
judges who declare mistrials.
   ``It sounds like the defense is doing what it has to do, leaving
no stone unturned, to get the maximum benefit out of it,'' said
Gerard Lynch, a professor at Columbia Law School in New York.
   GAF and Sherwin were indicted in July on charges they attempted
to manipulate up the value of Union Carbide Corp. stock in late 1986
after a failed takeover attempt of the larger company. The alleged
motive was to maximize the gain GAF would realize from the sale of
its stake in Carbide.
   Evidence for the indictment has been supplied largely by
securities trader Boyd L. Jefferies, who claimed his Los Angeles
brokerage was utilized by GAF to conduct manipulative trades in
Carbide stock to inflate the price.
   Jefferies, an admitted felon who has not been sentenced, is a
leading government witness in at least three major securities-fraud
prosecutions.
   He was implicated by Ivan F. Boesky, the notorious insider trader
who turned state's evidence in late 1986. Boesky is now serving a
three-year federal prison term.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890111-0241 </DOCNO>
