<DOCNO> AP890111-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1014EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Germany-MeatBan     01-11 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Germany-Meat Ban,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohl Calls For Reasonable Solution in Trade Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl on
Wednesday called for a reasonable solution to a trade dispute
between the European Economic Community and the United States over a
ban on the imports of American hormone-treated beef.
   ``Both sides should resolve their problems in a reasonable way in
the spirit of trans-Atlantic partnership and aware of their
responsibility for the world economy,'' Kohl told reporters at a
news conference in Bonn.
   The EEC ban on U.S. beef produced from cattle that had been fed
growth hormones took effect on Jan. 1.
   The United States retaliated with punitive tariffs on several
European products.
   ``Such trade conflicts can only hurt both sides economically and
politically,'' Kohl said.
   He said such disputes give a ``completely false signal'' for a
meeting of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade that will be
held in April and for the world economic summit scheduled this
summer.
   Kohl did not suggest any possible solutions to the beef dispute.
   He pledged strong support for the 12 European nations' efforts to
forge a single European market by the end of 1992.
   ``We've reached the point of no return; the target date will be
met,'' Kohl said, adding that West Germany will make every effort to
assist Spain and France, which hold the rotating EEC presidency this
year, in pushing through important decisions that have to be made.
   Kohl said agreement has to be reached before the end of 1990 on
tax harmonization, on the so-called ``social dimensions'' of the
internal market, on a joint monetary policy and on the ways and
means of coping with the security effect of open borders.
   He said those decisions have to be made well before 1992 to allow
individual nations to adapt domestic legislation to EEC changes.
   Kohl said that Europe will not turn into a protectionist
``fortress,'' once internal borders are eliminated. He stressed that
West Germany, as the world's largest exporter, is well aware of the
need for free trade and will strongly promote an EEC-wide free-trade
approach.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
