<HEAD>Centaur Extends Offer For Pennwalt; Releases Financial Facts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Centaur Partners said its $765 million cash offer
for chemical manufacturer Pennwalt Corp., scheduled to expire at
midnight tonight, was being extended two weeks to midnight on Jan.
25.
   Centaur also said Wednesday it was voluntarily submitting
unaudited financial information on itself and some of its limited
partners to the Securities and Exchange Commission, even though it
maintained the disclosure was not required by securities laws.
   Pennwalt had complained to the SEC that Centaur had not released
enough information about its financial standing. The principal
partners in Centaur are New York financiers Abbey J. Butler and
Melvyn J. Estrin.
   Centaur owns about 1 million or 12.7 percent of Pennwalt's 7.89
million outstanding shares and has made a tender offer to
shareholders to acquire the rest of the company at $100 a share.
That would come to about $690 million, not counting fees and other
expenses that could bring the cost of the deal to $765 million,
Centaur said.
