<FIRST>r f BC-Cetus-Hoffman     01-11 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Cetus-Hoffman,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cetus Announces New Deal With Hoffmann-La Roche</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cetus Corp., which recently settled a
question over patent rights with Hoffmann-La Roche, has reached a
multimillion dollar agreement with the Swiss pharmaceutical giant to
collaborate on the development and marketing of diagnostic tests
using Cetus' ``gene amplification'' technique.
   Cetus President Robert Fildes said Tuesday that his firm, based
in Emeryville, Calif., and Hoffman-La Roche have agreed not to
reveal the financial aspects of the five-year agreement, which
represents ``many millions of dollars.''
   Fildes said increased demand for diagnostic kits is expected to
create a $500 million to $600 million market by the middle of the
next decade.
   Last month, Cetus avoided a legal fight with the Swiss company
over patent rights by reaching a cross-licensing agreement on the
cancer fighting agent interleukin-2, Cetus' most important product.
Cetus agreed to pay Hoffmann-La Roche royalties on future sale of
the drug, and Hoffmann-La Roche said it would buy up to 7 percent of
Cetus' shares for $30 million.
   Under the latest agreement, Hoffman-La Roche will finance
development of the diagnostic tests using Cetus' GeneAmp polymerase
chain reaction, or PCR, technology. It also will pay Cetus an
undisclosed royalty on sales.
   The GeneAmp PRC process was developed by Cetus, and allows gene
sequences to be replicated millions of times. The technology has
helped the company develop accurate testing in the areas of genetic
disorders, cancer and infectious diseases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
