<DOCNO> AP890111-0247 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-DeedJail     01-11 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deed Jail,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parents Ordered To Jail If Teen Still Living With Them Next Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZEPHYRHILLS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of a 14-year-old say they
will keep their daughter at home despite the threat of jail for
violating a local ban on children under 15.
   ``I can't shoot her. It's as simple as that,'' Beverly Elmer said
in response to a judge's threat last week to jail her and her
husband for 10 days if daughter Staci Lynn isn't out of their
double-wide mobile home by Jan. 20.
   ``They don't like me,'' Staci said of the subdivision residents
who sued the Elmers. ``They're just mean. They don't like any
children.''
   The case mirrors one in Margate, Fla., where directors of an
adults-only condominium have been trying to evict 9-year-old Jamie
Swartz, who moved in with her father while her mother was dying of
cancer.
   The condominium directors voted last week to allow Jamie to stay
until March, when a housing law goes into effect that could nullify
child-exclusion deeds.
   In the Zephyrhills case, Circuit Judge Wayne L. Cobb said he had
no choice but to enforce the order.
   ``It's incomprehensible, a bunch of people who don't want
youngsters around,'' Cobb said. ``I don't understand why anybody,
period, would want to live in a place that didn't allow kids.''
   Mrs. Elmer said she and her husband, Thomas, don't have money to
rent another house while they try to sell their home, situated about
15 miles from Tampa. They say their mortgage doesn't permit them to
rent the home if they move.
</TEXT>
