<DOCNO> AP890111-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1102EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-California-Insurance     01-11 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-California-Insurance,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Agencies Clear The Way For Banks To Sell Insurance Under Prop.
103</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two state agencies have cleared the way for
banks to sell insurance for the first time in California as called
for by the voter-approved insurance reform initiative Proposition
103, officials said.
   But attorneys for the state's largest association of insurance
agents vowed Tuesday to challenge the decision in court.
   State Insurance Commissioner Roxani Gillespie and state Bank
Superintendent Howard Gould both issued recent rulings saying
Proposition 103 effectively repeals all state laws keeping banks out
of the insurance business.
   In a letter to the Independent Insurance Agents and Brokers of
California, Mrs. Gillespie said she and Gould rejected the agents'
argument that the banks are still barred from selling insurance
because Proposition 103 didn't explicitly repeal two provisions in
the financial code regulating banks.
   The agents argued that Proposition 103's wording aimed at
repealing provisions in the insurance code forbidding such sales
couldn't be applied to the banking codes.
   But Gould released a bulletin saying, ``The Banking Department
considers that the Financial Code restrictions ... are repealed by
implication with the passage of Proposition 103, and has prepared a
legal opinion to that effect.''
   The commissioner also denied a request for a public hearing on
the dispute.
   ``We are disappointed with Mrs. Gillespie's refusal to hold a
hearing and her decision to defer to the Banking Department's
opinion,'' said the agents' legal counsel, Stephen Young. ``We do
not agree with their reasoning.''
   About half of the banks in California, those possessing state
charters, are affected by Proposition 103. Allowing these banks to
sell insurance has long been a goal of insurance reformers trying to
boost competition and cut prices in the insurance business.
   Insurance companies are challenging the constitutionality of
Proposition 103 in the state Supreme Court. The high court has
allowed most of the ballot initiative to become law pending its
review. The proposition's provision calling for a 20 percent
rollback in insurance rates has not been put into effect, however.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
