<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed Amid Lack Of News</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat and corn futures prices opened slightly
lower while soybean futures were narrowly mixed in early trading
today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid a lack of significant new
supply-and-demand developments.
   Analysts said the mixed soybean market reflected mixed weather
conditions in the South American soybean belt. Scattered showers
continued in Brazil but Argentina remained mostly dry.
   Wheat futures continued to retreat from last week's 7{-year highs
due to a slowdown in U.S. export sales and growing expectations
among traders of a sharp increase in wheat planting after last
year's drought.
   ``Everybody's looking at the current price level and saying we
will have 15 percent to 20 percent more wheat acreage,'' said Walter
Spilka, a grain-market analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
in New York.
   The Agriculture Department will announce 1988-89 U.S. winter
wheat acreage in a report to be released Friday afternoon. The
report also will contain new estimates of the nation's grain and
soybean surplus and the final 1988 crop production figures.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 1\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.46{ a bushel; corn was { cent
to 1 cent lower with March at $2.88{ a bushel; oats were } cent
lower to \ cent higher with March at $2.39\ a bushel; soybeans were
{ cent lower to 2{ cents higher with January at $8.05 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were mixed in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .12 cent lower to .05 cent higher with February
at 74 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .37 cent lower
with January at 84.90 cents a pound; live hogs were .07 cent to .27
cent lower with February at 45.90 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were unchanged to .58 cent higher with February at 42.70 cents a
pound.
   Cattle futures closed higher on Tuesday while pork futures
finished mixed.
