<FIRST>u f PM-OilPrices 1stLd-Writethru   01-11 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crude Oil Prices Decline</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 5 new grafs to show Mexican oil strike affecting
futures prices; edits 2nd graf pvs to conform; picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``Among
refined ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures opened higher today, partly in
response to a nationwide shutdown of Mexico's refinery operations by
striking union workers.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, gasoline prices shot up as
much as 0.79 cent a gallon before midday pulling crude prices up
with them. The February contract for crude oil was up 18 cents at
$17.87 a barrel.
   Analysts said the stronger prices partially reflected investor
concern that the disruption in Mexican refinery operations could
mean lower U.S. supplies. The striking workers are protesting the
arrest of their union boss on gun-running charges.
   ``The U.S. doesn't get that many oil imports from Mexico. The
concern is that we might move production into Mexico,'' said Andrew
Lebow, senior broker and analyst for E.D.&amp;F. Man International
Futures Inc.
   Today's rise in oil prices also resulted from Tuesday's American
Petroleum Institute report showing that crude oil inventories
declined sharply last week, analysts said.
   On Tuesday, the February contract for West Texas Intermediate,
the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, settled 3 cents lower at
$17.69 a barrel after having been down as much as 25 cents during
the session. On Monday, the February contract closed 17 cents higher
at $17.72 a barrel.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, domestic heating
oil futures ended mixed, with the February contract settling at
53.86 cents a gallon, down 0.29 cent.
   Unleaded gasoline futures also closed mixed, with the February
contract down 0.05 cent at 47.91 cents a gallon.
   Analysts said prices were dragged down by profit-taking. Energy
analysts said investors decided to take advantage of steadily rising
prices and began a round of heavy selling early in the day.
   Prices later recovered most of their losses on reports that
non-OPEC oil producing countries were preparing to announce
production cutbacks to help bolster the recent accord among members
of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   After the close of trading, the American Petroleum Institute
reported that for the week ended Jan. 6, crude oil stocks fell by
5.5 million barrels, to 328.86 million barrels. Gasoline supplies
increased by 531,000 barrels to 229.1 million and heating oil stocks
were up 726,000 to 127.5 million barrels.
   Nauman Barakat, vice president of energy investments at
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., said the API report would probably
send crude futures higher.
   ``Many people were expecting a buildup of as high as 7 million
barrels of crude so the API report will be construed to be very
positive for the market,'' he said.
</TEXT>
