<DOCNO> AP890111-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1428EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv12   01-11 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 12 ,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thurs., Jan. 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>Illusions in The Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The free marketplace is a magnificent,
disciplined creation that distributes goods to where they should be
at the right _ or competitive _ price, the right time and generally
in the right amount.
   But it also is contrary. At the same time, it is forever filled
with idle dreams and grand illusions, some of which become so
all-enveloping that for a time they capture the minds of otherwise
sensible people.
   The eccentricity that leads to excess seems to occur with special
intensity in real estate and securities, but it can be found in
almost every area of the market, including automobiles, sports,
clothing, food, housing, electronics.
   The latest and biggest in the financial area, by far, is the
notion that junk bonds can be sold in enormous quantities at high
rates of interest and with little regard to a corporation's
financial structure _ without penalty.
   The penalty, of course, is merely delayed, since no corporation
can afford to pay rates greater than the market and greater than the
competition and still manage to operate as if it hadn't done so. The
penalty is delayed, not erased.
   Nobody can say when reality will appear, but economists who
examine the situation believe it might be in the midst of an
economic downturn and relatively high interest rates. That is,
business will be off and expenses up.
   It isn't the only major illusion at work today. One that is
growing popular in certain circles is that the economic cycle of ups
and downs has been broken, and that major booms and recessions are a
thing of the past.
   True, there is a growing body of evidence that suggests the cycle
has been muted, at least, and that instead of nationwide booms and
busts the economy now experiences what is sometimes termed ``rolling
readjustments.''
   Such economic events are limited rather than general, usually
involving one or a few geographical areas or industries at a time.
In mid-1986, for example, the nation's heartland was slumping while
the coastal economies were strong.
   The rolling adjustment thesis gains support from the current
six-year-long expansion, which generally is expected to last another
year or so. But to say the economic cycle has been broken is to take
a Grand Canyon-like leap.
   That is, while the immediate evidence might seem to substantiate
the belief, economic events are not nearly that forecastable. One
major event, such as a sudden rise in the price of oil, could
distill that notion to vapor.
   Do you recall when oil ``experts'' forecast $100 a barrel? When
the rage in the late 1960s was for growth stocks at price-earnings
ratios of 60? When in 1987 now-chagrined analysts foresaw 3500
points on the Dow Jones average?
   Can you forget the Texas-size optimism of savings and loans that
there were easy billions in real estate? That in the 1960s companies
risked their futures on bowling as the participant game of the
future?
   The no-check society? The home electronic center? Do you recall
how so many farmers lost their land by acquiring too much land,
believing that the price per acre would continue to rise like a line
to the horizon?
   Never underestimate the ability of the marketplace, a relatively
sane place when you analyze it, to produce aberrations that
continually find a stable of naive believers who, strangely, had
managed to succeed by using their heads.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs., Jan. 12.</NOTE>
</DOC>
