<FIRST>r f AM-GasPipeline     01-11 0121</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gas Pipeline,0126</SECOND>
<HEAD>Construction of 1,000-Mile Pipeline To Begin In 1989</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coastal Corp. announced Wednesday it would
begin construction this year of a 1,000-mile natural gas pipeline
from southwestern Wyoming to California.
   The $665 million project, given final approval by the Federal
Energy Regulatory Commission on Wednesday, will eventually transport
400 million cubic feet of gas a day from Wyoming, Coastal said.
   The gas will be used mainly to generate steam for recovering
heavy oil from California wells.
   Harold Burrow, chairman of WyCal and vice chairman of Coastal,
said the pipeline will begin transporting gas to California by early
1991.
   Colorado Interstate Gas Co., a subsidiary of Coastal, will build
and operate the project, Burrow said.
</TEXT>
