<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1745EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-SkiWoes Bjt   01-11 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ski Woes, Bjt,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>New England Ski Resorts Suffer Slightly From Lack of Snow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This is the winter of the New England ski
industry's discontent: Snowfall is below average and business is off
despite efforts to blanket the slopes with man-made white stuff.
   Packed natural powder provides the best skiing conditions and
most skiers tend to turn up their noses at the loose or frozen
granular cover provided by snow guns, if only for aesthetic reasons.
   ``It's a strange feeling to stand on a ski slope that's covered
in white and look out around at the houses down below and it's all
covered in brown,'' said Phil Camp, director of the New England Ski
Areas Council. ``The romance, the ambiance just isn't there.''
   Christopher H. Gill, manager of Great American Ski Renting Co.'s
store in North Conway, N.H., said ``the skiing is really good,''
thanks to artificial snow making in his area. But, he said, business
is down about 25 percent from last year.
   ``It really affects us when there's no snow down in Boston,''
Gill said. ``It's funny, if we get 3 inches of snow up here but
there's a foot in Boston, it does us more good than the other way
around.''
   Camp, who was hosting the council's annual convention for about
500 ski resort operators at Vermont's Stratton Mountain, said
man-made snow has received a bad reputation.
   ``A short period of time ago it was called `artificial snow,'
what a mistake that was,'' he said.
   Leslie B. Otten, director of Maine's Sunday River ski resort,
agreed: ``The first misnomer is that there's any difference in
quality between a man-made surface and a natuarl surface. What
generally changes skiing surface conditions is weather changes.''
   Those surfaces can be improved by grooming, and most slopes can
be almost completely groomed in two days of cold weather, Camp said.
   Operators have not seen a ``mass exodus from the slopes'' this
season, but Camp said that while the man-made snow is easier to
groom and moves better because it has less air, many still find it
too slick and don't like to ski on it.
   ``I'm here at Stratton Mountain and the average skier sure can't
complain,'' he said. ``There's a lot of skiing out here for people
who want it.''
   Only 4.1 inches of snow fell in the Boston area during the first
half of this season, compared to the average over the last 30 years
of about 9 inches. Up in ski country, the snowfall has been even
more disappointing for skiers.
   ``We're well below (average). We've had a big 3.8 inches this
season and that's almost 2 feet below normal,'' said John Cannon of
the National Weather Service in Portland, Maine.
   And in the last 108 years, this is the 100th driest snow season
in Maine, he said.
   Better snowmaking technology and high attendance last year
inspired resort operators to invest millions in upgrading their
snowmaking equipment, Camp said.
   ``If ever snowmaking is going to earn its keep it's this
season,'' he said.
   Okemo and Killington ski areas in Vermont have invested heavily
in snowmaking facilities and are operating at nearly full capacity,
Camp said.
   But small ski areas without adequate snowmaking facilities are
hurting. Sonnenberg in Barnard, Vt., hasn't even opened yet for the
season.
   ``I wish we had the equipment for the people, but sadly we
don't,'' said John Lancaster, whose wife, Virginia, operates the
hill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
