<FIRST>r f AM-GloveGlut     01-11 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Glove Glut,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Distributor Ends Up With Millions Of Unsold Rubber Gloves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BRITAIN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A medical supplier that profited from
an AIDS-induced shortage of latex rubber gloves says it expects to
report a big loss because a glove glut has emerged, leaving it with
mountains of unsold merchandise.
   ``We have millions of gloves _ and more arriving,'' said John
Murray, vice president for finance at Moore Medical Corp.
   Moore Medical Corp., had profits of more than $4 million a year
in 1986 and 1987 and pre-tax earnings of $3.1 million in the first
three quarters of 1988, but it has alerted stockholders to brace for
a loss in the final quarter and for the year.
   The company said a one-time charge in the fourth quarter would be
in in the range of $7 million to $11 million, or $4.3 million to
$6.8 million on an after-tax basis.
   Moore's situation is typical of that of many medical supply
companies.
   Publicity about AIDS created an unprecedented demand for the
gloves last year. By spring, Moore Medical and other distributors
were rationing gloves to customers at a few boxes per order.
   ``We doubled and tripled up on orders to suppliers,'' Murray
said. But then supplies from new factories in Asia began arriving.
By late fall, he said, ``All of a sudden a lot of our orders were
coming in (and) what had been close to zero supply became a glut.''
</TEXT>
