<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     01-11 0783</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0810</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coffee Futures Collapse As Speculator Flight Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee futures prices collapsed Wednesday on New York's Coffee,
Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange as speculators, spooked by weakening
technical signals, resumed their flight from the market.
   On other markets, energy futures scored sharp gains; grains and
soybeans declined; livestock and meat were mostly lower; precious
metal futures were down slightly; and stock-index futures advanced.
   Most coffee futures declined 6 cents a pound, the permitted limit
for daily trading. The limitless contract for delivery in March
settled 11.67 cents lower amid heavy volume at $1.3881 a pound, a
four-week low.
   ``The coffee market obviously crashed,'' said Arthur Stevenson,
an analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York. ``We
had a literal avalanche.''
   But analysts could point to no new supply-and-demand developments
that might have precipitated the collapse. Instead, they said, the
barrage of sell orders was triggered by the market's decline through
successive ``sell stops,'' which are price levels at which
speculators had previously decided they would sell.
   Selling rapidly accelerated as the March contract's price
approached $1.43 a pound, Stevenson said.
   ``Once we fell through there, it attracted a great deal of
additional selling,'' he said.
   Coffee futures have been in a downward trend since Jan. 3, the
first trading session of the new year, when March coffee reached a
27-month high of $1.669 a pound on bullish supply and demand factors.
   Analysts said those factors, which include drought damage to the
Brazilian coffee crop and strong seasonal demand, have not changed,
although recent rains in Brazil may have halted the damage there.
   ``The only thing you can say is that volatility in the coffee
market continues to be very high,'' said Sandra Kaul, an analyst in
New York with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. ``The extent of the move
upward is making the market very vulnerable to a downside
correction.''
   Energy futures prices rose sharply on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, mostly in reaction to a weekly American Petroleum
Institute report showing a 5.5 million barrel decline in U.S. crude
oil stocks.
   ``A lot of oil that should have hit the market has not,'' said
Peter Cardillo, an analyst with Josephthal &amp; Co. in New York.
   Other analysts said members of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries apparently were adhering to OPEC's new
production curbs, which became effective Jan. 1.
   West Texas Intermediate crude settled 9 cents to 48 cents higher
with February at $18.17 a barrel; heating oil was .11 cent lower to
.33 cent higher with February at 53.75 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .05 cent lower to .89 cent higher with February at
48.80 cents a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures finished moderately lower on the
Chicago Board of Trade in a late sell-off linked to increasingly
bearish expectations for Friday's Agriculture Department crop report.
   The report, scheduled for release after Friday's close of
trading, will contain the government's final 1988 crop production
totals, new estimates of the nation's grain and soybean stockpiles,
projections for 1989 corn and soybean plantings and an actual tally
of the 1988-89 winter wheat acreage.
   Analysts said they expected the report to show winter wheat
seedings to be more than 15 percent above the previous year. The
1988 corn and soybean production totals are expected to be higher
than the last USDA estimate.
   Wheat settled 1 cent to 3\ cents lower with March at $4.44{ a
bushel; corn was \ cent to 2} cents lower with March at $2.86} a
bushel; oats were } cent to 3 cents lower with March at $2.36 a
bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents to 7 cents lower with January at
$7.97{ a bushel.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, cattle futures finished mixed
in technically inspired trading while pork futures fell amid bearish
fundamental factors.
   Live cattle settled .22 cent lower to .25 cent higher with
February at 73.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .35 cent lower
to .30 cent higher with January at 84.92 cents a pound; live hogs
were .05 cent to .75 cent lower with February at 45.42 cents a
pound; frozen pork bellies were .35 cent to .75 cent lower with
February at 41.95 cents a pound.
   Most gold and silver futures drifted lower in lackluster trading
on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   Gold settled 30 cents to 40 cents lower with February at $405.20
a troy ounce; silver was 0.1 cent lower to 0.5 cent higher with
March at $5.995 a troy ounce.
   Stock-index futures posted moderate gains on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index settled 1.20 points higher at 284.40.
Each point is worth $500.
</TEXT>
