<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern     01-11 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sells Six Planes To Continental</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines, seeking to raise cash, has sold
six A-300 wide-body jet planes to sister carrier Continental
Airlines, the company announced Wednesday.
   Eastern will receive $103 million cash and a $67 million note at
17.5 percent interest for the sale, Eastern spokeswoman Karen
Ceremsak said.
   The planes had been leased earlier to Continental and therefore
will have no effect on the size of Eastern's fleet, she said.
   Ms. Ceremsak said the sale was unconnected to the breakdown of
federally-mediated talks between Eastern and its machinists' union.
   ``This is part of the continued efforts to raise cash,'' she said.
   When the talks collapsed on Monday, Joseph B. Leonard, an Eastern
senior vice president, said the company would have to move faster on
sales of its assets. The airline, which is seeking $150 million in
wage concessions from the 8,500-member International Association of
Machinists, estimates it is losing $1 million a day.
   Eastern is awaiting completion of a $365 million sale of its
Northeast shuttle service to New York developer Donald Trump, and
reportedly is seeking buyers for such assets as Philadelphia gates
and some Canadian routes.
   Eastern insists that only a federal declaration of an impasse,
which would set a 30-day deadline, will get the 15-month-old
contract talks moving with the machinists, its largest union.
   Federal mediators have indicated they are not ready to take that
action, although there has been no word from the Washington-based
National Mediation Board about new talks.
   Under an impasse, if no settlement were reached in 30 days,
Eastern could impose its own work conditions and the union could
strike.
   Eastern reported $233.7 million in losses for the first three
quarters of 1988 and has lost more than $1 billion in the past
decade.
</TEXT>
