<DOCNO> AP890111-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1859EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-GAF     01-11 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GAF,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Grants Defense Motion Aimed At Halting New Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court granted a defense request
Wednesday for a hearing to determine whether it should at least
temporarily halt a new trial in the stock-manipulation case against
GAF Corp. and a top company aide.
   The appellate move came a day after a lower-court judge declared
a mistrial and dismissed the jurors because of prosecutorial
mishandling of a key piece of evidence in the GAF case, the first
major case arising from the Wall Street corruption scandal to reach
the trial phase.
   U.S. District Judge Mary J. Lowe wanted to start over and pick
new jurors, but the defense objected on grounds of double jeopardy,
the legal theory that a defendant can't be retried twice for the
same offense.
   Defense attorneys immediately appealed her intention to restart
the trial to the 2nd Circuit Court of Appeals, which said it would
hear arguments on the matter Thursday.
   GAF and Vice Chairman James Sherwin were indicted in July on
charges they attempted to manipulate upward the value of Union
Carbide Corp. stock in late 1986 after a failed takeover attempt of
the larger company. The alleged motive was to maximize the gain GAF
would realize from the sale of its stake in Carbide.
   Evidence for the indictment has been supplied largely by
securities trader Boyd L. Jefferies, who claimed his Los Angeles
brokerage was utilized by GAF to conduct manipulative trades in
Carbide stock to inflate the price.
   Jefferies is a leading government witness in at least three major
securities fraud prosecutions. He has been cooperating as a result
of his own plea bargain with federal prosecutors to settle
securities law violations.
</TEXT>
