<FIRST>r f AM-MostAdmired     01-11 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Most Admired,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merck Tops List Of Most Admired Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merck &amp; Co., the pharmaceuticals giant, tops a
list of America's most admired companies for the third year in a
row, while Financial Corp. of America again was the least admired,
Fortune magazine said Wednesday.
   To compile the list of corporate reputations, contained in
Fortune's Jan. 30 issue, the magazine said it surveyed about 8,000
top executives, outside corporate directors and financial analysts
for their opinions on 305 companies in 32 industries.
   Among the criteria the companies were rated on were
innovativeness, community responsibility, quality of products or
services, quality of management, value as a long-term investment,
abilty to keep talented people, financial soundness and use of
assets.
   Rubbermaid Inc. again came in No. 2 on the most admired list. No.
3 was Minnesota Mining &amp; Manufacturing Co., the adhesives maker
commonly called 3M, which moved up from 6th place in the magazine's
1987 survey.
   The other top 10 on the list, in descending order: Philip Morris
Cos., the tobacco and food giant; Wal-Mart Stores Inc., the discount
retail chain; Exxon Corp.; Pepsico Inc.; Boeing Co., Herman Miller,
an office-furniture maker; and Shell Oil.
   On the least admired list, after Financial Corp. of America, a
California-based savings and loan holding company that has filed for
reorganization, came Gibralter Financial Corp., another
California-based thrift, and Texas Air Corp., the controversial
holding company for Eastern Airlines and Continental Airlines.
   The other bottom 10, in descending order: Meritor Financial
Group, a Philadelphia savings institution holding company;
BankAmerica Corp., the San Francisco bank holding company; LTV
Corp., the steel company; Goldome Inc., a Buffalo, N.Y., financial
institution holding company; Control Data Corp., the computer
company; Manufacturers Hanover Corp., the New York bank holding
company; and KaiserTech Ltd., the parent of Kaiser Aluminum &amp;
Chemical Corp.
</TEXT>
