<FIRST>u f BC-HollyFarms     01-11 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Holly Farms,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holly Farms Meeting Put Off Until Tuesday, Tyson Chief Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poultry processor Holly Farms Corp. has
put off until next week a decision on competing buyout offers from
Tyson Foods Inc. and ConAgra Inc., Tyson's chief executive said
Wednesday.
   Holly Farms had scheduled a meeting of its board for Wednesday to
consider the bids, but delayed the session until Tuesday to give
Tyson executives a chance to visit Holly Farms' plants and talk to
its employees, Don Tyson said.
   Holly Farms, based in Memphis, Tenn., refused to comment on its
plans.
   Tyson Foods has offered $1.06 billion, or $60 a share, for Holly
Farms, which has agreed to be acquired by ConAgra in a $1 billion
stock swap.
   Tyson Foods, the nation's largest poultry processor, has been
trying since the fall to buy Holly Farms, the nation's third-largest
poultry processor. ConAgra, based in Omaha, Neb., is in second
place, and whichever company wins Holly Farms will rank as No. 1.
   Tyson is based in Springdale, Ark.
   ConAgra has refused to say if it will counter Tyson's bid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
